\pard\keepn\s2\sb240\sa240\qc\kerning0\i\fs28 CONVERSATION WITH A COMMISSIONER\par
\pard\fi216\qj\b0\i0\f0\fs24 Lije Baley had just reached his desk when he became aware of R. Sammy watching him expectantly.\par
The dour lines of his long face hardened. \ldblquote What do you want?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The boss wants you, Lije. Right away. Soon as you come in.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All right.\rdblquote\par
R. Sammy stood there blankly.\par
Baley said, \ldblquote I said, all right. Go away!\rdblquote\par
R. Sammy turned on his heel and left to go about his duties. Baley wondered irritably why those same duties couldn\rquote t be done by a man.\par
He paused to examine the contents of his tobacco pouch and make a mental calculation. At two pipefuls a day, he could stretch it to next quota day.\par
Then he stepped out from behind his railing (he\rquote d rated a railed corner two years ago) and walked the length of the common room.\par
Simpson looked up from a merc-pool file as he passed. \ldblquote Boss wants you, Lije.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I know. R. Sammy told me.\rdblquote\par
A closely coded tape reeled out of the merc-pool\rquote s vitals as the small instrument searched and analyzed its \ldblquote memory\rdblquote  for the desired information stored in the tiny vibration patterns of the gleaming mercury surface within.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote d kick R. Sammy\rquote s behind if I weren\rquote t afraid I\rquote d break a leg,\rdblquote  said Simpson. \ldblquote I saw Vince Barrett the other day.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He was looking for his job back. Or any job in the Department. The poor kid\rquote s desperate, but what could I tell him. R. Sammy\rquote s doing his job and that\rquote s all. The kid has to work a delivery tread on the yeast farms now. He was a bright boy, too. Everyone liked him.\rdblquote\par
Baley shrugged and said in a manner stiffer than he intended or felt, \ldblquote It\rquote s a thing we\rquote re all living through.\rdblquote\par
The boss rated a private office. It said JULIUS ENDERBY on the clouded glass. Nice letters. Carefully etched into the fabric of the glass. Underneath, it said COMMISSIONER OF POLICE, CITY OF NEW YORK.\par
Baley stepped in and said, \ldblquote You want to see me, Commissioner?\rdblquote\par
Enderby looked up. He wore spectacles because his eyes were sensitive and couldn\rquote t take the usual contact lenses. It was only after one got used to the sight of them that one could take in the rest of the face, which was quite undistinguished. Baley had a strong notion that the Commissioner valued his glasses for the personality they lent him and suspected that his eyeballs weren\rquote t as sensitive as all that.\par
The Commissioner looked definitely nervous. He straightened his cuffs, leaned back, and said, too heartily, \ldblquote Sit down, Lije. Sit down.\rdblquote\par
Baley sat down stiffly and waited.\par
Enderby said, \ldblquote [\'85]?\rdblquote\par
[\'85], said Baley, [\'85]\par
\ldblquote Fine,\rdblquote  echoed Enderby. \ldblquote Just fine.\rdblquote\par
It had been a false start.\par
Baley thought: Something\rquote s wrong with his face.\par
Aloud, he said, \ldblquote Commissioner, I wish you wouldn\rquote t send R. Sammy out after me.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, you know how I feel about those things, Lije. But he\rquote s been put here and I\rquote ve got to use him for something.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s uncomfortable, Commissioner. He tells me you want me and then he stands there. You know what I mean. I have to tell him to go or he just keeps on standing there.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, that\rquote s my fault, Lije. I gave him the message to deliver and forgot to tell him specifically to get back to his job when he was through.\rdblquote\par
Baley sighed. The fine wrinkles about his intensely brown eyes grew more pronounced. \ldblquote Anyway, you wanted to see me.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, Lije,\rdblquote  said the Commissioner, \ldblquote but not for anything easy.\rdblquote\par
He stood up turned away, and walked [to] the wall behind his desk.\par
The Commissioner smiled. \ldblquote I had this arranged specially last year, Lije. I don\rquote t think I\rquote ve showed it to you before. Come over here and take a look. In the old days, all rooms had things like this. They were called \lquote windows.\rquote  Did you know that?\rdblquote\par
Baley knew that very well, having viewed many historical novels.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ve heard of them,\rdblquote  he said.\par
\ldblquote Come here.\rdblquote\par
Baley squirmed a bit, but did as he was told. There was something indecent about the exposure of the privacy of a room to the outside world. Sometimes the Commissioner carried his affectation of Medievalism to a rather foolish extreme.\par
Like his glasses, Baley thought.\par
That was it! That was what made him look wrong!\par
Baley said, \ldblquote Pardon me, Commissioner, but you\rquote re wearing new glasses, aren\rquote t you?\rdblquote\par
The Commissioner stared at him in mild surprise, took off his glasses, looked at them and then at Baley. Without his glasses, his round face seemed rounder and his chin a trifle more pronounced. He looked vaguer, too, as his eyes failed to focus properly.\par
He said, \ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
He put his glasses back on his nose, then added with real anger, \ldblquote I broke my old ones three days ago. What with one thing or another I wasn\rquote t able to replace them till this morning. Lije, those three days were hell.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote On account of the glasses?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And other things, too. I\rquote m getting to that.\rdblquote\par
He turned to the window and so did Baley. With mild shock, Baley realized it was raining. For a minute, he was lost in the spectacle of water dropping from the sky, while the Commissioner exuded a kind of pride as though the phenomenon were a matter of his own arranging.\par
\ldblquote This is the third time this month I\rquote ve watched it rain. Quite a sight, don\rquote t you think?\rdblquote\par
Against his will, Baley had to admit to himself that it was impressive. [In] his forty-two years he had rarely seen rain, or any of the phenomena at nature, for that matter.\par
He said, \ldblquote It always seems a waste for all that water to come down on the city. It should restrict itself to the reservoirs.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Lije,\rdblquote  said the Commissioner, \ldblquote you\rquote re a modernist. That\rquote s your trouble. In Medieval times, people lived in the open. I don\rquote t mean on the farms only. I mean in the cities, too. Even in New York. When it rained, they didn\rquote t think of it as waste. They gloried in it. They lived close to nature. It\rquote s healthier, better. The troubles of modern life come from being divorced from nature. Read up on the Coal Century, sometimes.\rdblquote\par
Baley had. He had heard many people moaning about the invention of the atomic pile. He moaned about it himself when things went wrong, or when he got tired. Moaning like that was a built-in facet of human nature. Back in the Coal Century, people moaned about the invention of the steam engine. In one of Shakespeare\rquote s plays, a character moaned about the invention of gunpowder. A thousand years in the future, they\rquote d be moaning about the invention of the positronic brain.\par
The hell with it.\par
He said, grimly, \ldblquote Look, Julius.\rdblquote  (It wasn\rquote t his habit to get friendly with the Commissioner during office hours, however many \lquote Lijes\rquote  the Commissioner threw at him, but something special seemed called for here.) \ldblquote Look, Julius, you\rquote re talking about everything except what I came in here for, and it\rquote s worrying me. What is it?\rdblquote\par
The Commissioner said, \ldblquote I\rquote ll get to it, Lije. Let me do it my way. It\rquote s--it\rquote s trouble.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Sure. What isn\rquote t on this planet? More trouble with the R\rquote s?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote In a way, yes, Lije. I stand here and wonder how much more trouble the old world can take. \ldblquote When I put in this window, I wasn\rquote t just letting in the sky once in a while. I let in the City. I look at it and I wonder what will become of it in another century.\rdblquote\par
Baley felt repelled by the other\rquote s sentimentality, but he found himself staring outward in fascination. Even dimmed by the weather, the City was a tremendous thing to see. The Police Department was in the upper levels of City Hall, and City Hall reached high. From the Commissioner\rquote s window, the neighboring towers fell short and the tops were visible. They were so many fingers, groping upward. Their walls were blank, featureless. They were the outer shells of human hives.\par
\ldblquote In a way,\rdblquote  said the Commissioner, \ldblquote I\rquote m sorry it\rquote s raining. We can\rquote t see Spacetown.\rdblquote\par
Baley looked westward, but it was as the Commissioner said. The horizon closed down. New York\rquote s towers grew misty and came to an end against blank whiteness.\par
\ldblquote I know what Spacetown is like,\rdblquote  said Baley.\par
\ldblquote I like the picture from here,\rdblquote  said the Commissioner. \ldblquote It can just be made out in the gap between the two Brunswick Sectors. Low domes spread out. It\rquote s the difference between us and the Spacers. We reach high and crowd close. With them, each family has a dome for itself. One family: one house. And land between each dome. Have you ever spoken to any of the Spacers, Lije?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote A few times. About a month ago, I spoke to one right here on your intercom,\rdblquote  Baley said, patiently.\par
\ldblquote Yes, I remember. But then, I\rquote m just getting philosophical. We and they. Different ways of life.\rdblquote\par
Baley\rquote s stomach was beginning to constrict a little. The more devious the Commissioner\rquote s approach, the deadlier he thought might be the conclusion.\par
He said, \ldblquote All right. But what\rquote s so surprising about it? You can\rquote t spread eight billion people over Earth in little domes. They\rquote ve got space on their worlds, so let them live their way.\rdblquote\par
The Commissioner walked to his chair and sat down. His eyes looked unblinkingly at Baley, shrunken a bit by the concave lenses in his spectacles. He said, \ldblquote Not everyone is that tolerant about differences in culture. Either among us or among the Spacers.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All right. So what?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote So three days ago, a Spacer died.\rdblquote\par
Now it was coming. The corners of Baley\rquote s thin lips raised a trifle, but the effect upon his long, sad face was unnoticeable. He said, \ldblquote Too bad. Something contagious, I hope. A virus. A cold, perhaps.\rdblquote\par
The Commissioner looked startled, \ldblquote What are you talking about?\rdblquote  Baley didn\rquote t care to explain. The precision with which the Spacers had bred disease out of their societies was well known. The care with which they avoided, as far as possible, contact with disease-riddled Earthmen was even better known. But then, sarcasm was lost on the Commissioner.\par
Baley said, \ldblquote I\rquote m just talking. What did he die of?\rdblquote  He turned back to the window.\par
The Commissioner said, \ldblquote He died of a missing chest. Someone had used a blaster on him.\rdblquote\par
Baley\rquote s back grew rigid. He said, without turning, \ldblquote What are you talking about?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m talking about murder,\rdblquote  said the Commissioner, softly. \ldblquote You\rquote re a plain-clothes man. You know what murder is.\rdblquote\par
And now Baley turned. \ldblquote But a Spacer! Three days ago?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But who did it? How?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The Spacers say it was an Earthman.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It can\rquote t be.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why not? You don\rquote t like the Spacers. I don\rquote t. Who on Earth does? Someone didn\rquote t like them a little too much, that\rquote s all.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Sure, but--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote There was the fire at the Los Angeles factories. There was the Berlin R-smashing. There were the riots in Shanghai.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All right.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It all points to rising discontent. Maybe to some sort of organization.\rdblquote\par
Baley said, \ldblquote Commissioner, I don\rquote t get this. Are you testing me for some reason?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  The Commissioner looked honestly bewildered.\par
Baley watched him. \ldblquote Three days ago a Spacer was murdered and the Spacers think the murderer is an Earthman. Till now,\rdblquote  his finger tapped the desk, \ldblquote nothing\rquote s come out. Is that right? Commissioner, that\rquote s unbelievable. Jehoshaphat, Commissioner, a thing like this would blow New York off the face of the planet if it really happened.\rdblquote\par
The Commissioner shook his head. \ldblquote It\rquote s not as simple as that. Look, Lije, I\rquote ve been out three days. I\rquote ve been in conference with the Mayor. I\rquote ve been out to Spacetown. I\rquote ve been down in Washington, talking to the Terrestrial Bureau of Investigation.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh? And what do the Terries have to say?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote They say it\rquote s our baby. It\rquote s inside city limits. Spacetown is under New York jurisdiction.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But with extraterritorial rights.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I know. I\rquote m coming to that.\rdblquote  The Commissioner\rquote s eyes fell away from Baley\rquote s flinty stare. He seemed to regard himself as having been suddenly demoted to the position of Baley\rquote s underling, and Baley behaved as though he accepted the fact.\par
\ldblquote The Spacers can run the show,\rdblquote  said Baley.\par
\ldblquote Wait a minute, Lije,\rdblquote  pleaded the Commissioner. \ldblquote Don\rquote t rush me. I\rquote m trying to talk this over, friend to friend. I want you to know my position. I was there when the news broke. I had an appointment with him--with Roj Nemennuh Sarton.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The victim?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The victim.\rdblquote  The Commissioner groaned. \ldblquote Five minutes more and I, myself, would have discovered the body. What a shock that would have been. As it was, it was brutal, brutal. They met me and told me. It started a three-day nightmare, Lije. That on top of having everything blur on me and having no time to replace my glasses for days. That won\rquote t happen again, at least. I\rquote ve ordered three pairs.\rdblquote\par
Baley considered the picture he conjured up of the event. He could see the tall, fair figures of the Spacers approaching the Commissioner with the news and breaking it to him in their unvarnished emotionless way. Julius would remove his glasses and polish them. Inevitably, under the impact of the event, he would drop them, then look down at the broken remnants with a quiver of his soft, full lips. Baley was quite certain that, for five minutes anyway, the Commissioner was much more disturbed over his glasses than over the murder.\par
The Commissioner was saying, \ldblquote It\rquote s a devil of a position. As you say, the Spacers have extraterritorial rights. They can insist on their own investigation, make whatever report they wish to their home governments. The Outer Worlds could use this as an excuse to pile on indemnity charges. You know how that would sit with the population.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It would be political suicide for the White House to agree to pay.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And another kind of suicide not to pay.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You don\rquote t have to draw me a picture,\rdblquote  said Baley. He had been a small boy when the gleaming cruisers from outer space last sent down their soldiers into Washington, New York, and Moscow to collect what they claimed was theirs.\par
\ldblquote Then you see. Pay or not pay, it\rquote s trouble. The only way out is to find the murderer on our own and hand him over to the Spacers. It\rquote s up to us.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why not give it to the TBI? Even if it is our jurisdiction from a legalistic viewpoint, there\rquote s the question of interstellar relations--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The TBI won\rquote t touch it. This is hot and it\rquote s in our lap.\rdblquote  For a moment, he lifted his head and gazed keenly at his subordinate. \ldblquote And it\rquote s not good, Lije. Every one of us stands the chance of being out of a job.\rdblquote\par
Baley said, \ldblquote Replace us all? Nuts. The trained men to do it with don\rquote t exist.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote R\rquote s,\rdblquote  said the Commissioner. \ldblquote They exist.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote R. Sammy is just a beginning. He runs errands. Others can patrol the expressways. Damn it, man, I know the Spacers better than you do, and I know what they\rquote re doing. There are R\rquote s that can do your work and mine. We can be declassified. Don\rquote t think differently. And at our age, to hit the labor pool ...\rdblquote\par
Baley said, gruffly, \ldblquote All right.\rdblquote\par
The Commissioner looked abashed. \ldblquote Sorry, Lije.\rdblquote\par
Baley nodded and tried not to think of his father. The Commissioner knew the story, of course.\par
Baley said, \ldblquote When did all this replacement business come up?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Look, you\rquote re being naive, Lije. It\rquote s been happening all along. It\rquote s been happening for twenty-five years, ever since the Spacers came. You know that. It\rquote s just beginning to reach higher, that\rquote s all. If we muff this case, it\rquote s a big, long step toward the point where we can stop looking forward to collecting our pension-tab booklets. On the other hand, Lije, if we handle the matter well, it can shove that point far into the future. And it would be a particular break for you.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote For me?\rdblquote  said Baley.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote ll be the operative in charge, Lije.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t rate it, Commissioner. I\rquote m a C-5, that\rquote s all.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You want a C-6 rating, don\rquote t you?\rdblquote\par
Did he? Baley knew the privileges a C-6 rating carried. A seat on the expressway in the rush hour, not just from ten to four. Higher up on the list-of-choice at the Section kitchens. Maybe even a chance at a better apartment and a quota ticket to the Solarium levels for Jessie.\par
\ldblquote I want it,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote Sure. Why wouldn\rquote t I? But what would I get if I couldn\rquote t break the case?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why wouldn\rquote t you break it, Lije?\rdblquote  the Commissioner wheedled. \ldblquote You\rquote re a good man. You\rquote re one of the best we have.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But there are half a dozen men with higher ratings in my department section. Why should they be passed over?\rdblquote\par
Baley did not say out loud, though his bearing implied it strongly, that the Commissioner did not move outside protocol in this fashion except in cases of wild emergency.\par
The Commissioner folded his hands. \ldblquote Two reasons. You\rquote re not just another detective to me, Lije. We\rquote re friends, too. I\rquote m not forgetting we were in college together. Sometimes it may look as though I have forgotten, but that\rquote s the fault of rating. I\rquote m Commissioner, and you know what that means. But I\rquote m still your friend and this is a tremendous chance for the right person. I want you to have it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s one reason,\rdblquote  said Baley, without warmth.\par
\ldblquote The second reason is that I think you\rquote re my friend. I need a favor.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What sort of favor?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I want you to take on a Spacer partner in this deal. That was the condition the Spacers made. They\rquote ve agreed not to report the murder; they\rquote ve agreed to leave the investigation in our hands. In return, they insist one of their own agents be in on the deal, the whole deal.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It sounds like they don\rquote t trust us altogether.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Surely you see their point. If this is mishandled, a number of them will be in trouble with their own governments. I\rquote ll give them the benefit of the doubt, Lije. I\rquote m willing to believe they mean well.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m sure they do, Commissioner. That\rquote s the trouble with them.\rdblquote  The Commissioner looked blank at that, but went on. \ldblquote Are you willing to take on a Spacer partner, Lije?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You\rquote re asking that as a favor?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, I\rquote m asking you to take the job with all the conditions the Spacers have set up.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll take a Spacer partner, Commissioner.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Thanks, Lije. He\rquote ll have to live with you.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, now, hold on.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I know. I know. But you\rquote ve got a large apartment, Lije. Three rooms. Only one child. You can put him up. He\rquote ll be no trouble. No trouble at all. And it\rquote s necessary.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Jessie won\rquote t like it. I know that.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You tell Jessie,\rdblquote  the Commissioner was earnest, so earnest that his eyes seemed to bore holes through the glass discs blocking his stare, \ldblquote that if you do this for me, I\rquote ll do what I can when this is all over to jump you a grade. C-7, Lije. C-7!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All right, Commissioner, it\rquote s a deal.\rdblquote\par
Baley half rose from his chair, caught the look on Enderby\rquote s face, and sat down again.\par
\ldblquote There\rquote s something else?\rdblquote\par
Slowly, the Commissioner nodded. \ldblquote One more item.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Which is?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The name of your partner.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What difference does that make?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The Spacers,\rdblquote  said the Commissioner, \ldblquote have peculiar ways. The partner they\rquote re supplying isn\rquote t--isn\rquote t ...\rdblquote\par
Baley\rquote s eyes opened wide. \ldblquote Just a minute!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You\rquote ve got to, Lije. You\rquote ve got to. There\rquote s no way out.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Stay at my apartment? A thing like that?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote As a friend, please!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No. No!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Lije, I can\rquote t trust anyone else in this. Do I have to spell it out for you? We\rquote ve got to work with the Spacers. We\rquote ve got to succeed, if we\rquote re to keep the indemnity ships away from Earth. But we can\rquote t succeed just any old way. You\rquote ll be partnered with one of their R\rquote s. If he breaks the case, if he can report that we\rquote re incompetent, we\rquote re ruined, anyway. We, as a department. You see that, don\rquote t you? So you\rquote ve got a delicate job on your hands. You\rquote ve got to work with him, but see to it that you solve the case and not he. Understand?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You mean co-operate with him 100 per cent, except that I cut his throat? Pat him on the back with a knife in my hand?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What else can we do? There\rquote s no other way out.\rdblquote\par
Lije Baley stood irresolute. \ldblquote I don\rquote t know what Jessie will say.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll talk to her, if you want me to.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, Commissioner.\rdblquote  He drew a deep, sighing breath. \ldblquote What\rquote s my partner\rquote s name?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote R. Daneel Olivaw.\rdblquote\par
Baley said, sadly, \ldblquote This isn\rquote t a time for euphemism, Commissioner. I\rquote m taking the job, so let\rquote s use his full name. Robot Daneel Olivaw.\rdblquote\par
