\pard\keepn\s2\sb240\sa240\qc\kerning0\i\fs28 INCIDENT AT A SHOE COUNTER\par
\pard\fi216\qj\b0\i0\f0\fs24 The interior of the store was emptier than the street outside. The manager, with commendable foresight, had thrown the force door early in the game, preventing potential troublemakers from entering. It also kept the principles in the argument from leaving, but that was minor.\par
Baley got through the force door by using his officer\rquote s neutralizer. Unexpectedly, he found R. Daneel still behind him. The robot was pocketing a neutralizer of his own, a slim one, smaller and neater than the standard police model.\par
The manager ran to them instantly, talking loudly. \ldblquote Officers, my clerks have been assigned me by the City. I am perfectly within my rights.\rdblquote\par
There were three robots standing rodlike at the rear of the department. Six humans were standing near the force door. They were all women.\par
\ldblquote All right, now,\rdblquote  said Baley, crisply. \ldblquote What\rquote s going on? What\rquote s all the fuss about?\rdblquote\par
One of the women said, shrilly, \ldblquote I came in for shoes. Why can\rquote t I have a decent clerk? Ain\rquote t I respectable?\rdblquote  Her clothing, especially her hat, were just sufficiently extreme to make it more than a rhetorical question. The angry flush that covered her face masked imperfectly her overdone makeup.\par
The manager said, \ldblquote I\rquote ll wait on her myself if I have to, but I can\rquote t wait on all of them, Officer. There\rquote s nothing wrong with my men. They\rquote re registered clerks. I have their spec charts and guarantee slips--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Spec charts,\rdblquote  screamed the woman. She laughed shrilly, turning to the rest. \ldblquote Listen to him. He calls them men! What\rquote s the matter with you anyway? They ain\rquote t men. They\rquote re ro-bots!\rdblquote  She stretched out the syllables. \ldblquote And I tell you what they do, in case you don\rquote t know. They steal jobs from men. That\rquote s why the government always protects them. They work for nothin\rquote  and, on account o\rquote  that, families gotta live out in the barracks and eat raw yeast mush. Decent hard-working families. We\rquote d smash up all the ro-bots, if I was boss. I tell you that!\rdblquote\par
The others talked confusedly and there was always the growing rumble from the crowd just beyond the force door.\par
Baley was conscious, brutally conscious, of R. Daneel Olivaw standing at his elbow. He looked at the clerks. They were Earthmade, and even on that scale, relatively inexpensive models. They were just robots made to know a few simple things. They would know all the style numbers, their prices, the sizes available in each. They could keep track of stock fluctuations, probably better than humans could, since they would have no outside interests. They could compute the proper orders for the next week. They could measure the customer\rquote s foot.\par
In themselves, harmless. As a group, incredibly dangerous.\par
Baley could sympathize with the woman more deeply than he would have believed possible the day before. No, two hours before. He could feel R. Daneel\rquote s nearness and he wondered if R. Daneel could not replace an ordinary plain-clothes man [C-1]. He could see the barracks, as he thought that. He could taste the yeast mush. He could remember his father.\par
His father had been a nuclear physicist, with a rating that had put him in the top percentile of the City. There had been an accident at the power plant and his father had borne the blame. He had been declassified. Baley did not know the details; it had happened when he was a year old.\par
But he remembered the barracks of his childhood; the grinding communal existence just this side of the edge of bearability. He remembered his mother not at all; she had not survived long. His father he recalled well, a sodden man, morose and lost, speaking sometimes of the past in hoarse, broken sentences.\par
His father died, still declassified, when Lije was eight. Young Baley and his two older sisters moved into the Section orphanage. Children\rquote s Level, they called it. His mother\rquote s brother, Uncle Boris, was himself too poor to prevent that.\par
So it continued hard. And it was hard going through school, with no father-derived status privileges to smooth the way.\par
And now he had to stand in the middle of a growing riot and beat down men and women who, after all, only feared declassification for themselves and those they loved, as he himself did.\par
Tonelessly, he said to the woman who had already spoken, \ldblquote Let\rquote s not have any trouble, lady. The clerks aren\rquote t doing you any harm.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Sure they ain\rquote t done me no harm,\rdblquote  sopranoed the woman. \ldblquote They ain\rquote t gonna, either. Think I\rquote ll let their cold, greasy fingers touch me? I came in here expecting to get treated like a human being. I\rquote m a citizen. I got a right to have human beings wait on me. And listen, I got two kids waiting for supper. They can\rquote t go to the Section kitchen without me, like they was orphans. I gotta get out of here.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, now,\rdblquote  said Baley, feeling his temper slipping, \ldblquote if you had let yourself be waited on, you\rquote d have been out of here by now. You\rquote re just making trouble for nothing. Come on now.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well!\rdblquote  The woman registered shock. \ldblquote Maybe you think you can talk to me like I was dirt. Maybe it\rquote s time the guv\rquote min\rquote  reelized robots ain\rquote t the only things on Earth. I\rquote m a hard-working woman and I\rquote ve got rights.\rdblquote  She went on and on and on.\par
Baley felt harassed and caught. The situation was out of hand. Even if the woman would consent to be waited on, the waiting crowd was ugly enough for anything.\par
There must be a hundred crammed outside the display window now. In the few minutes since the plain-clothes men had entered the store, the crowd had doubled.\par
\ldblquote What is the usual procedure in such a case?\rdblquote  asked R. Daneel Olivaw, suddenly.\par
Baley nearly jumped. He said, \ldblquote This is an unusual case in the first place.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What is the law?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The R\rquote s have been duly assigned here. They\rquote re registered clerks. There\rquote s nothing illegal about that.\rdblquote\par
They were speaking in whispers. Baley tried to look official and threatening. Olivaw\rquote s expression, as always, meant nothing at all.\par
\ldblquote In that case,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel, \ldblquote order the woman to let herself be waited on or to leave.\rdblquote\par
Baley lifted a corner of his lip briefly. \ldblquote It\rquote s a mob we have to deal with, not a woman. There\rquote s nothing to do but call a riot squad.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It should not be necessary for citizens to require more than one officer of the law to direct what should be done,\rdblquote  said Daneel.\par
He turned his broad face to the store manager. \ldblquote Open the force door, sir.\rdblquote\par
Baley\rquote s arm shot forward to seize R. Daneel\rquote s shoulder, swing him about. He arrested the motion. If, at this moment, two law men quarreled openly, it would mean the end of all chance for a peaceful solution.\par
The manager protested, looked at Baley. Baley did not meet his eye.\par
R. Daneel said, unmoved, \ldblquote I order you with the authority of the law.\rdblquote\par
The manager bleated, \ldblquote I\rquote ll hold the City responsible for any damage to the goods or fixtures. I serve notice that I\rquote m doing this under orders.\rdblquote\par
The barrier went down; men and women crowded in. There was a happy roar from them. They sensed victory.\par
Baley had heard of similar riots. He had even witnessed one. He had seen robots being lifted by a dozen hands, their heavy unresisting bodies carried backward from straining arm to straining arm. Men yanked and twisted at the metal mimicry of men. They used hammers, force knives, needle guns. They finally reduced the miserable objects to shredded metal and wire. Expensive positronic brains, the most intricate creation of the human mind, were thrown from hand to hand like footballs and mashed to uselessness in a trifle of time.\par
Then, with the genius of destruction so merrily let loose, the mobs turned on anything else that could be taken apart.\par
The robot clerks could have no knowledge of any of this, but they squealed as the crowd flooded inward and lifted their arms before their faces as though in a primitive effort at hiding. The woman who had started the fuss, frightened at seeing it grow suddenly so far beyond what she had expected, gasped, \ldblquote Here, now. Here, now.\rdblquote\par
Her hat was shoved down over her face and her voice became only a meaningless shrillness.\par
The manager was shrieking, \ldblquote Stop them, Officer. Stop them!\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel spoke. Without apparent effort, his voice was suddenly decibels higher than a human\rquote s voice had a right to be. Of course, thought Baley for the tenth time, he\rquote s not--\par
R. Daneel said, \ldblquote The next man who moves will be shot.\rdblquote\par
Someone well in the back yelled, \ldblquote Get him!\rdblquote\par
But for a moment, no one moved.\par
R. Daneel stepped nimbly upon a chair and from that to the top of a Transtex display case. The colored fluorescence gleaming through the slits of polarized molecular film turned his cool, smooth face into something unearthly.\par
Unearthly, thought Baley.\par
The tableau held as R. Daneel waited, a quietly formidable person. R. Daneel said crisply, \ldblquote You are saying, This man is holding a neuronic whip, or a tickler. If we all rush forward, we will bear him down and at most one or two of us will be hurt and even they will recover. Meanwhile, we will do just as we wish and to space with law and order.\rdblquote\par
His voice was neither harsh nor angry, but it carried authority. It had the tone of confident command. He went on, \ldblquote You are mistaken. What I hold is not a neuronic whip, nor is it a tickler. It is a blaster and very deadly. I will use it and I will not aim over your heads. I will kill many of you before you seize me, perhaps most of you. I am serious. I look serious, do I not?\rdblquote\par
There was motion at the outskirts, but the crowd no longer grew. If newcomers still stopped out of curiosity, others were hurrying away. Those nearest R. Daneel were holding their breath, trying desperately not to sway forward in response to the mass pressure of the bodies behind them.\par
The woman with the hat broke the spell. In a sudden whirlpool of sobbing, she yelled, \ldblquote He\rquote s gonna kill us. I ain\rquote t done nothing. Oh, lemme outta here.\rdblquote\par
She turned, but faced an immovable wall of crammed men and women. She sank to her knees. The backward motion in the silent crowd grew more pronounced.\par
R. Daneel jumped down from the display counter and said, \ldblquote I will now walk to the door. I will shoot the man or woman who touches me.\par
When I reach the door, I will shoot any man or woman who is not moving about his business. This woman here--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, no,\rdblquote  yelled the woman with the hat, \ldblquote I tell ya I didn\rquote t do nothing. I didn\rquote t mean no harm. I don\rquote t want no shoes. I just wanta go home.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote This woman here,\rdblquote  went on Daneel, \ldblquote will remain. She will be waited on.\rdblquote\par
He stepped forward.\par
The mob faced him dumbly. Baley closed his eyes. It wasn\rquote t his fault, he thought desperately. There\rquote ll be murder done and the worst mess in the world, but they forced a robot on me as partner. They gave him equal status.\par
It wouldn\rquote t do. He didn\rquote t believe himself. He might have stopped R. Daneel at the start. He might at any moment have put in the call for a squad car. He had let R. Daneel take responsibility, instead, and had felt a cowardly relief. When he tried to tell himself that R. Daneel\rquote s personality simply dominated the situation, he was filled with a sudden self-loathing. A robot dominating.\par
There was no unusual noise, no shouting and cursing, no groans, no yells. He opened his eyes.\par
They were dispersing.\par
The manager of the store was cooling down, adjusting his twisted jacket, smoothing his hair, muttering angry threats at the vanishing crowd.\par
The smooth, fading whistle of a squad car came to a halt just outside. Baley thought: Sure, when it\rquote s all over.\par
The manager plucked his sleeve. \ldblquote Let\rquote s have no more trouble, Officer.\rdblquote\par
Baley said, \ldblquote There won\rquote t be any trouble.\rdblquote\par
It was easy to get rid of the squad-car police. They had come in response to reports of a crowd in the street. They knew no details and could see for themselves that the street was clear. R. Daneel stepped aside and showed no sign of interest as Baley explained to the men in the squad car, minimizing the event and completely burying R. Daneel\rquote s part in it.\par
Afterward, he pulled R. Daneel to one side, against the steel and concrete of one of the building shafts.\par
\ldblquote Listen,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote I\rquote m not trying to steal your show, you understand.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Steal my show? Is it one of your Earth idioms?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I didn\rquote t report your part in this.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I do not know all your customs. On my world, a complete report is usual, but perhaps it is not so on your world. In any case, civil rebellion was averted. That is the important thing, is it not?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Is it? Now you look here.\rdblquote  Baley tried to sound as forceful as possible under the necessity of speaking in an angry whisper. \ldblquote Don\rquote t you ever do it again.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Never again insist on the observance of law? If I am not to do that, what then is my purpose?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t ever threaten a human being with a blaster again.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I would not have fired under any circumstances, Elijah, as you know very well. I am incapable of hurting a human. But, as you see, I did not have to fire. I did not expect to have to.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That was the purest luck, your not having to fire. Don\rquote t take that kind of chance again. I could have pulled the grandstand stunt you did--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Grandstand stunt? What is that?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Never mind. Get the sense from what I\rquote m saying. I could have pulled a blaster on the crowd myself. I had the blaster to do it with. But it isn\rquote t the kind of gamble I am justified in taking, or you, either. It was safer to call squad cars to the scene than to try one-man heroics.\rdblquote\par
R Daneel considered. He shook his head. \ldblquote I think you are wrong, partner Elijah. My briefing on human characteristics here among the people of Earth includes the information that, unlike the men of the Outer Worlds, they are trained from birth to accept authority. Apparently this is the result of your way of living. One man, representing authority firmly enough, was quite sufficient, as I proved. Your own desire for a squad car was only an expression, really, of your almost instinctive wish for superior authority to take responsibility out of your hands. On my own world, I admit that what I did would have been most unjustified.\rdblquote\par
Baley\rquote s long face was red with anger. \ldblquote If they had recognized you as a robot--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I was sure they wouldn\rquote t.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote In any case, remember that you are a robot. Nothing more than a robot. Just a robot. Like those clerks in the shoe store.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But this is obvious.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And you\rquote re not human.\rdblquote  Baley felt himself being driven into cruelty against his will.\par
R. Daneel seemed to consider that. He said, \ldblquote The division between human and robot is perhaps not as significant as that between intelligence and non-intelligence.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Maybe on your world,\rdblquote  said Baley, \ldblquote but not on Earth.\rdblquote\par
He looked at his watch and could scarcely make out that he was an hour and a quarter late. His throat was dry and raw with the thought that R. Daneel had won the first round, had won when he himself had stood by helpless.\par
He thought of the youngster, Vince Barrett, the teenager whom R. Sammy had replaced. And of himself, Elijah Baley, whom R. Daneel could replace. Jehoshaphat, at least his father had been thrown out because of an accident that had done damage, that had killed people. Maybe it was his fault; Baley didn\rquote t know. Suppose he had been eased out to make room for a mechanical physicist. Just for that. For no other reason. Nothing he could do about it.\par
He said, curtly, \ldblquote Let\rquote s go now. I\rquote ve got to get you home.\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel said, \ldblquote You see, it is not proper to make any distinction of lesser meaning than the fact of intel--\rdblquote\par
Baley\rquote s voice rose. \ldblquote All right. The subject is closed. Jessie is waiting for us.\rdblquote  He walked in the direction of the nearest intrasection communo-tube. \ldblquote I\rquote d better call and tell her we\rquote re on our way up.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Jessie?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote My wife.\rdblquote\par
Jehoshaphat, thought Baley, I\rquote m in a fine mood to face Jessie.\par
\pard\keepn\pagebb\s1\sb240\sa60\qc\kerning32\b\f2\fs32 Chapter 4\par
\pard\keepn\s2\sb240\sa240\qc\kerning0\i\fs28 INTRODUCTION TO A FAMILY\par
\pard\fi216\qj\b0\i0\f0\fs24 It had been her name that had first made Elijah Baley really conscious of Jessie. He had met her at the Section Christmas party back in \rquote 02, over a bowl of punch. He had just finished his schooling, just taken his first job with the City, just moved into the Section. He was living in one of the bachelor alcoves of Common Room 122A. Not bad for a bachelor alcove.\par
She was handing out the punch. \ldblquote I\rquote m Jessie,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote Jessie Navodny. I don\rquote t know you.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Baley,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote Lije Baley. I\rquote ve just moved into the Section.\rdblquote  He took his glass of punch and smiled mechanically. She impressed him as a cheerful and friendly person, so he stayed near her. He was new and it is a lonely feeling to be at a party where you find yourself watching people standing about in cliques of which you aren\rquote t a part. Later, when enough alcohol had trickled down throats, it might be better.\par
Meanwhile, he remained at the punch bowl, watching the folks come and go and sipping thoughtfully.\par
\ldblquote I helped make the punch.\rdblquote  The girl\rquote s voice broke in upon him. \ldblquote I can guarantee it. Do you want more?\rdblquote\par
Baley realized his little glass was empty. He smiled and said, \ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote  The girl\rquote s face was oval and not precisely pretty, mostly because of a slightly overlarge nose. Her dress was demure and she wore her light brown hair in a series of ringlets over her forehead.\par
She joined him in the next punch and he felt better.\par
\ldblquote Jessie,\rdblquote  he said, feeling the name with his tongue. \ldblquote It\rquote s nice. Do you mind if I use it when I\rquote m talking to you?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Certainly. If you want to. Do you know what it\rquote s short for?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Jessica?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You\rquote ll never guess.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I can\rquote t think of anything else.\rdblquote\par
She laughed and said archly, \ldblquote My full name is Jezebel.\rdblquote\par
That was when his interest flared. He put his punch glass down and said, intently, \ldblquote No, really?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Honestly. I\rquote m not kidding. Jezebel. It\rquote s my real-for-true name on all my records. My parents liked the sound of it.\rdblquote\par
She was quite proud of it, even though there was never a less likely Jezebel in the world.\par
Baley said, seriously, \ldblquote My name is Elijah, you know. My full name, I mean.\rdblquote\par
It didn\rquote t register with her.\par
He said, \ldblquote Elijah was Jezebel\rquote s great enemy.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He was?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why, sure. In the Bible.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh? I didn\rquote t know that. Now isn\rquote t that funny? I hope that doesn\rquote t mean you\rquote ll have to be my enemy in real life.\rdblquote\par
From the very beginning there was no question of that. It was the coincidence of names at first that made her more than just a pleasant girl at the punch bowl. But afterward he had grown to find her cheerful, tender-hearted, and, finally, even pretty. He appreciated her cheerfulness particularly. His own sardonic view of life needed the antidote.\par
But Jessie never seemed to mind his long grave face.\par
\ldblquote Oh, goodness,\rdblquote  she said, \ldblquote what if you do look like an awful lemon? I know you\rquote re not really, and I guess if you were always grinning away like clockwork, the way I do, we\rquote d just explode when we got together. You stay the way you are, Lije, and keep me from floating away.\rdblquote\par
And she kept Lije Baley from sinking down. He applied for a small Couples apartment and got a contingent admission pending marriage.\par
He showed it to her and said, \ldblquote Will you fix it so I can get out of Bachelor\rquote s, Jessie? I don\rquote t like it there.\rdblquote\par
Maybe it wasn\rquote t the most romantic proposal in the world, but Jessie liked it.\par
Baley could only remember one occasion on which Jessie\rquote s habitual cheer deserted her completely and that, too, had involved her name. It was in their first year of marriage, and their baby had not yet come.\par
In fact, it had been the very month in which Bentley was conceived.\par
(Their I.Q. rating, Genetic Values status, and his position in the Department entitled him to two children, of which the first might be conceived during the first year.) Maybe, as Baley thought back upon it, Bentley\rquote s beginnings might explain part of her unusual skittishness. Jessie had been drooping a bit because of Baley\rquote s consistent overtime.\par
She said, \ldblquote It\rquote s embarrassing to eat alone at the kitchen every night.\rdblquote\par
Baley was tired and out of sorts. He said, \ldblquote Why should it be? You can meet some nice single fellows there.\rdblquote\par
And of course she promptly fired up. \ldblquote Do you think I can\rquote t make an impression on them, Lije Baley?\rdblquote\par
Maybe it was just because he was tired; maybe because Julius Enderby, a classmate of his, had moved up another notch on the C-scale rating while he himself had not. Maybe it was simply because he was a little tired of having her try to act up to the name she bore when she was nothing of the sort and never could be anything of the sort.\par
In any case, he said bitingly, \ldblquote I suppose you can, but I don\rquote t think you\rquote ll try. I wish you\rquote d forget your name and be yourself.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll be just what I please.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Trying to be Jezebel won\rquote t get you anywhere. If you must know the truth, the name doesn\rquote t mean what you think, anyway. The Jezebel of the Bible was a faithful wife and a good one according to her lights. She had no lovers that we know of, cut no high jinks, and took no moral liberties at all.\rdblquote\par
Jessie stared angrily at him. \ldblquote That isn\rquote t so. I\rquote ve heard the phrase, \lquote a painted Jezebel.\rquote  I know what that means.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Maybe you think you do, but listen. After Jezebel\rquote s husband, King Ahab died, her son, Jehoram, became king. One of the captains of his army, Jehu, rebelled against him and assassinated him. Jehu then rode to Jezreel where the old queen-mother, Jezebel, was residing. Jezebel heard of his coming and knew that he could only mean to kill her. In her pride and courage, she painted her face and dressed herself in her best clothes so that she could meet him as a haughty and defiant queen. He had her thrown from the window of the palace and killed, but she made a good end, according to my notions. And that\rquote s what people refer to when they speak of \lquote a painted Jezebel,\rquote  whether they know it or not.\rdblquote\par
The next evening Jessie said in a small voice, \ldblquote I\rquote ve been reading the Bible, Lije.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  For a moment, Baley was honestly bewildered.\par
\ldblquote The parts about Jezebel.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh! Jessie, I\rquote m sorry if I hurt your feelings. I was being childish.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No. No.\rdblquote  She pushed his hand from her waist and sat on the couch, cool and upright, with a definite space between them. \ldblquote It\rquote s good to know the truth. I don\rquote t want to be fooled by not knowing. So I read about her. She was a wicked woman, Lije.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, her enemies wrote those chapters. We don\rquote t know her side.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote She killed all the prophets of the Lord she could lay her hands on.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote So they say she did.\rdblquote  Baley felt about in his pocket for a stick of chewing gum. (In later years he abandoned that habit because Jessie said that with his long face and sad, brown eyes, it made him look like an old cow stuck with an unpleasant wad of grass it couldn\rquote t swallow and wouldn\rquote t spit out.) He said, \ldblquote If you want her side, I could think of some arguments for you. She valued the religion of her ancestors who had been in the land long before the Hebrews came. The Hebrews had their own God, and, what\rquote s more, it was an exclusive God. They weren\rquote t content to worship Him themselves; they wanted everyone in reach to worship Him as well.\par
\ldblquote Jezebel was a conservative, sticking to the old beliefs against the new ones. After all, if the new beliefs had a higher moral content, the old ones were more emotionally satisfying. The fact that she killed priests just marks her as a child of her times. It was the usual method of proselytization in those days. If you read I Kings, you must remember that Elijah (my namesake this time) had a contest with 850 prophets of Baal to see which could bring down fire from heaven. Elijah won and promptly ordered the crowd of onlookers to kill the 850 Baalites. And they did.\rdblquote\par
Jessie bit her lip. \ldblquote What about Naboth\rquote s vineyard, Lije. Here was this Naboth not bothering anybody, except that he refused to sell the King his vineyard. So Jezebel arranged to have people perjure themselves and say that Naboth had committed blasphemy or something.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He was supposed to have blasphemed God and the king,\rdblquote  said Baley.\par
\ldblquote Yes. So they confiscated his property after they executed him.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That was wrong. Of course, in modern times, Naboth would have been handled quite easily. If the City wanted his property or even if one of the Medieval nations had wanted his property, the courts would have ordered him off, had him removed by force if necessary, and paid him whatever they considered a fair price. King Ahab didn\rquote t have that way out. Still, Jezebel\rquote s solution was wrong. The only excuse for her is that Ahab was sick and unhappy over the situation and she felt that her love for her husband came ahead of Naboth\rquote s welfare. I keep telling you, she was the model of a faithful wi--\rdblquote\par
Jessie flung herself away from him, red-faced and angry. \ldblquote I think you\rquote re mean and spiteful.\rdblquote\par
He looked at her with complete dismay. \ldblquote What have I done? What\rquote s the matter with you?\rdblquote\par
She left the apartment without answering and spent the evening and half the night at the subetheric video levels, traveling petulantly from showing to showing and using up a two-month supply of her quota allowance (and her husband\rquote s, to boot).\par
When she came back to a still wakeful Lije Baley, she had nothing further to say to him.\par
It occurred to Baley later, much later, that he had utterly smashed an important part of Jessie\rquote s life. Her name had signified something intriguingly wicked to her. It was a delightful makeweight for her prim, over-respectable past. It gave her an aroma of licentiousness, and she adored that.\par
But it was gone. She never mentioned her full name again, not to Lije, not to her friends, and maybe, for all Baley knew, not even to herself. She was Jessie and took to signing her name so.\par
As the days passed she began speaking to him again, and after a week or so their relationship was on the old footing and, with all subsequent quarrels, nothing ever reached that one bad spot of intensity. Only once was there even an indirect reference to the matter. It was in her eighth month of pregnancy. She had left her own position as dietitian\rquote s assistant in Section Kitchen A-23 and with unaccustomed time on her hands was amusing herself in speculation and preparation for the baby\rquote s birth.\par
She said, one evening, \ldblquote What about Bentley?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Pardon me, dear?\rdblquote  said Baley, looking up from a sheaf of work he had brought home with him. (With an additional mouth soon to feed and Jessie\rquote s pay stopped and his own promotions to the non-clerical levels as far off, seemingly, as ever, extra work was necessary.)\par
\ldblquote I mean if the baby\rquote s a boy. What about Bentley as a name?\rdblquote\par
Baley pulled down the corners of his mouth. \ldblquote Bentley Baley? Don\rquote t you think the names are too similar?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t know. It has a swing, I think. Besides, the child can always pick out a middle name to suit himself when he gets older.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, it\rquote s all right with me.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Are you sure? I mean ... Maybe you wanted him to be named Elijah?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And be called Junior? I don\rquote t think that\rquote s a good idea. He can name his son Elijah, if he wants to.\rdblquote\par
Then Jessie said, \ldblquote There\rquote s just one thing,\rdblquote  and stopped. After an interval, he looked up. \ldblquote What one thing?\rdblquote\par
She did not quite meet his eye, but she said, forcefully enough, \ldblquote Bentley isn\rquote t a Bible name, is it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Baley, \ldblquote I\rquote m quite sure it isn\rquote t.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All right, then. I don\rquote t want any Bible names.\rdblquote\par
And that was the only harking back that took place from that time to the day when Elijah Baley was coming home with Robot Daneel Olivaw, when he had been married for more than eighteen years and when his son Bentley Baley (middle name still unclose) was past sixteen.\par
Baley paused before the large double door on which there glowed in large letters PERSONAL-MEN. In smaller letters were written SUBSECTIONS 1A-1E. In still smaller letters, just above the key slit, it stated:\par
\par
\pard\qc\ldblquote In case of loss of key, communicate at once with 27-101-51.\rdblquote\par
\pard\fi216\qj\f1\par
\f0 A man inched past them, inserted an aluminum sliver into the key slit, and walked in. He closed the door behind him, making no attempt to hold it open for Baley. Had he done so, Baley would have been seriously offended. By strong custom men disregarded one another\rquote s presence entirely either within or just outside the Personals. Baley remembered one of the more interesting marital confidences to have been Jessie\rquote s telling him that the situation was quite different at Women\rquote s Personals.\par
She was always saying, \ldblquote I met Josephine Greely at Personal and she said ...\rdblquote\par
It was one of the penalties of civic advancement that when the Baleys were granted permission for the activation of the small washbowl in their bedroom, Jessie\rquote s social life suffered.\par
Baley said, without completely masking his embarrassment, \ldblquote Please wait out here, Daneel.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Do you intend washing?\rdblquote  asked R. Daneel.\par
Baley squirmed and thought: Damned robot! If they were briefing him on everything under steel, why didn\rquote t they teach him manners? I\rquote ll be responsible if he ever says anything like this to anyone else. He said, \ldblquote I\rquote ll shower. It gets crowded evenings. I\rquote ll lose time then. If I get it done now we\rquote ll have the whole evening before us.\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel\rquote s face maintained its repose. \ldblquote Is it part of the social custom that I wait outside?\rdblquote\par
Baley\rquote s embarrassment deepened. \ldblquote Why need you go in for--for no purpose.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, I understand you. Yes, of course. Nevertheless, Elijah, my hands grow dirty, too, and I will wash them.\rdblquote\par
He indicated his palms, holding them out before him. They were pink and plump, with the proper creases. They bore every mark of excellent and meticulous workmanship and were as clean as need be. Baley said, \ldblquote We have a washbasin in the apartment, you know.\rdblquote  He said it casually. Snobbery would be lost on a robot.\par
\ldblquote Thank you for your kindness. On the whole, however, I think it would be preferable to make use of this place. If I am to live with you men of Earth, it is best that I adopt as many of your customs and attitudes as I can.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Come on in, then.\rdblquote\par
The bright cheerfulness of the interior was a sharp contrast to the busy utilitarianism of most of the rest of the City, but this time the effect was lost on Baley\rquote s consciousness.\par
He whispered to Daneel, \ldblquote I may take up to half an hour or so. Wait for me.\rdblquote  He started away, then returned to add, \ldblquote And listen, don\rquote t talk to anybody and don\rquote t look at anybody. Not a word, not a glance! It\rquote s a custom.\rdblquote\par
He looked hurriedly about to make certain that his own small conversation had not been noted, was not being met by shocked glances. Nobody, fortunately, was in the antecorridor, and after all it was only the antecorridor.\par
He hurried down it, feeling vaguely dirty, past the common chambers to the private stalls. It had been five years now since he had been awarded one--large enough to contain a shower, a small laundry, and other necessities. It even had a small projector that could be keyed in for the news films.\par
\ldblquote A home away from home,\rdblquote  he had joked when it was first made available to him. But now, he often wondered how he would bear the adjustment back to the more Spartan existence of the common chambers if his stall privileges were ever canceled.\par
He pressed the button that activated the laundry and the smooth face of the meter lighted.\par
R. Daneel was waiting patiently when Baley returned with a scrubbed body, clean underwear, a freshened shirt, and, generally, a feeling of greater comfort.\par
\ldblquote No trouble?\rdblquote  Baley asked, when they were well outside the door and able to talk.\par
\ldblquote None at all, Elijah,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel.\par
Jessie was at the door, smiling nervously. Baley kissed her.\par
\ldblquote Jessie,\rdblquote  he mumbled, \ldblquote this is my new partner, Daneel Olivaw.\rdblquote\par
Jessie held out a hand, which R. Daneel took and released. She turned to her husband, then looked timidly at R. Daneel.\par
She said, \ldblquote Won\rquote t you sit down, Mr. Olivaw? I must talk to my husband on family matters. It\rquote ll take just a minute. I hope you won\rquote t mind.\rdblquote\par
Her hand was on Baley\rquote s sleeve. He followed her into the next room.\par
She said, in a hurried whisper, \ldblquote You aren\rquote t hurt, are you? I\rquote ve been so worried ever since the broadcast.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What broadcast?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It came through nearly an hour ago. About the riot at the shoe counter. They said two plain-clothes men stopped it. I knew you were coming home with a partner and this was right in our subsection and right when you were coming home and I thought they were making it better than it was and you were--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Please, Jessie. You see I\rquote m perfectly all right.\rdblquote\par
Jessie caught hold of herself with an effort. She said, shakily, \ldblquote Your partner isn\rquote t from your division, is he?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  replied Baley miserably. \ldblquote He\rquote s--a complete stranger.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote How do I treat him?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Like anybody else. He\rquote s just my partner, that\rquote s all.\rdblquote\par
He said it so unconvincingly, that Jessie\rquote s quick eyes narrowed. \ldblquote What\rquote s wrong?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Nothing. Come, let\rquote s go back into the living room. It\rquote ll begin to look queer.\rdblquote\par
Lije Baley felt a little uncertain about the apartment now. Until this very moment, he had felt no qualms. In fact, he had always been proud of it. It had three large rooms; the living room, for instance, was an ample fifteen feet by eighteen. There was a closet in each room. One of the main ventilation ducts passed directly by. It meant a little rumbling noise on rare occasions, but, on the other hand, assured first-rate temperature control and well-conditioned air. Nor was it too far from either Personal, which was a prime convenience.\par
But with the creature from worlds beyond space sitting in the midst of it, Baley was suddenly uncertain. The apartment seemed mean and cramped.\par
Jessie said, with a gaiety that was slightly synthetic, \ldblquote Have you and Mr. Olivaw eaten, Lije?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote As a matter of fact,\rdblquote  said Baley, quickly, \ldblquote Daneel will not be eating with us. I\rquote ll eat, though.\rdblquote\par
Jessie accepted the situation without trouble. With food supplies so narrowly controlled and rationing tighter than ever, it was good form to refuse another\rquote s hospitality.\par
She said, \ldblquote I hope you won\rquote t mind our eating, Mr. Olivaw. Lije, Bentley, and I generally eat at the Community kitchen. It\rquote s much more convenient and there\rquote s more variety, you see, and just between you and me, bigger helpings, too. But then, Lije and I do have permission to eat in our apartment three times a week if we want to--Lije is quite successful at the Bureau and we have very nice status--and I thought that just for this occasion, if you wanted to join us, we would have a little private feast of our own, though I do think that people who overdo their privacy privileges are just a bit anti-social, you know.\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel listened politely.\par
Baley said, with an undercover \ldblquote shushing\rdblquote  wiggle of his fingers, \ldblquote Jessie, I\rquote m hungry.\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel said, \ldblquote Would I be breaking a custom, Mrs. Baley, if I addressed you by your given name?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why, no, of course not.\rdblquote  Jessie folded a table out of the wall and plugged the plate warmer into the central depression on the table top. \ldblquote You just go right ahead and call me Jessie all you feel like--uh--Daneel.\rdblquote  She giggled.\par
Baley felt savage. The situation was getting rapidly more uncomfortable. Jessie thought R. Daneel a man. The thing would be someone to boast of and talk about in Women\rquote s Personal. He was good-looking in a wooden way, too, and Jessie was pleased with his deference. Anyone could see that.\par
Baley wondered about R. Daneel\rquote s impression of Jessie. She hadn\rquote t changed much in eighteen years, or at least not to Lije Baley. She was heavier, of course, and her figure had lost much of its youthful vigor. There were lines at the angles of the mouth and a trace of heaviness about her cheeks. Her hair was more conservatively styled and a dimmer brown than it had once been.\par
But that\rquote s all beside the point, thought Baley, somberly. On the Outer Worlds the women were tall and as slim and regal as the men. Or, at least, the book-films had them so and that must be the kind of women R. Daneel was used to.\par
But R. Daneel seemed quite unperturbed by Jessie\rquote s conversation, her appearance, or her appropriation of his name. He said, \ldblquote Are you sure that is proper? The name, Jessie, seems to be a diminutive. Perhaps its use is restricted to members of your immediate circle and I would be more proper if I used your full given name.\rdblquote\par
Jessie, who was breaking open the insulating wrapper surrounding the dinner ration, bent her head over the task in sudden concentration.\par
\ldblquote Just Jessie,\rdblquote  she said, tightly. \ldblquote Everyone calls me that. There\rquote s nothing else.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Very well, Jessie.\rdblquote\par
The door opened and a youngster entered cautiously. His eyes found R. Daneel almost at once.\par
\ldblquote Dad?\rdblquote  said the boy, uncertainly.\par
\ldblquote My son, Bentley,\rdblquote  said Baley, in a low voice. \ldblquote This is Mr. Olivaw, Ben.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He\rquote s your partner, huh, Dad? How d\rquote ya do, Mr. Olivaw.\rdblquote  Ben\rquote s eyes grew large and luminous. \ldblquote Say, Dad, what happened down in the shoe place? The newscast said--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t ask any questions now, Ben,\rdblquote  interposed Baley sharply.\par
Bentley\rquote s face fell and he looked toward his mother, who motioned him to a seat.\par
\ldblquote Did you do what I told you, Bentley?\rdblquote  she asked, when he sat down. Her hands moved caressingly over his hair. It was as dark as his father\rquote s and he was going to have his father\rquote s height, but all the rest of him was hers. He had Jessie\rquote s oval face, her hazel eyes, her light-hearted way of looking at life.\par
\ldblquote Sure, Mom,\rdblquote  said Bentley, hitching himself forward a bit to look into the double dish from which savory vapors were already rising.\par
\ldblquote What we got to eat? Not zymoveal again, Mom? Huh, Mom?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote There\rquote s nothing wrong with zymoveal,\rdblquote  said Jessie, her lips pressing together. \ldblquote Now, you just eat what\rquote s put before you and let\rquote s not have any comments.\rdblquote\par
It was quite obvious they were having zymoveal.\par
Baley took his own seat. He himself would have preferred something other than zymoveal, with its sharp flavor and definite aftertaste, but Jessie had explained her problem before this.\par
\ldblquote Well, I just can\rquote t, Lije,\rdblquote  she had said. \ldblquote I live right here on these levels all day and I can\rquote t make enemies or life wouldn\rquote t be bearable. They know I used to be assistant dietitian and if I just walked off with steak or chicken every other week when there\rquote s hardly anyone else on the floor that has private eating privileges even on Sunday, they\rquote d say it was pull or friends in the prep room. It would be talk, talk, talk, and I wouldn\rquote t be able to put my nose out the door or visit Personal in peace. As it is, zymoveal and protoveg are very good. They\rquote re well-balanced nourishment with no waste and, as a matter of fact, they\rquote re full of vitamins and minerals and everything anyone needs and we can have all the chicken we want when we eat in Community on the chicken Tuesdays.\rdblquote\par
Baley gave in easily. It was as Jessie said; the first problem of living is to minimize friction with the crowds that surround you on all sides. Bentley was a little harder to convince.\par
On this occasion, he said, \ldblquote Gee, Mom, why can\rquote t I use Dad\rquote s ticket and eat in Community myself? I\rquote d just as soon.\rdblquote\par
Jessie shook her head in annoyance and said, \ldblquote I\rquote m surprised at you, Bentley. What would people say if they saw you eating by yourself as though your own family weren\rquote t good enough for you or had thrown you out of the apartment?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, gosh, it\rquote s none of people\rquote s business.\rdblquote\par
Baley said, with a nervous edge in his voice, \ldblquote Do as your mother tells you, Bentley.\rdblquote\par
Bentley shrugged, unhappily.\par
R. Daneel said, suddenly; from the other side of the room, \ldblquote Have I the family\rquote s permission to view these book-films during your meal?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, sure,\rdblquote  said Bentley, slipping away from the table, a look of instant interest upon his face. \ldblquote They\rquote re mine. I got them from the library on special school permit. I\rquote ll get you my viewer. It\rquote s a pretty good one. Dad gave it to me for my last birthday.\rdblquote\par
He brought it to R. Daneel and said, \ldblquote Are you interested in robots, Mr. Olivaw?\rdblquote\par
Baley dropped his spoon and bent to pick it up.\par
R. Daneel said, \ldblquote Yes, Bentley. I am quite interested.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Then you\rquote ll like these. They\rquote re all about robots. I\rquote ve got to write an essay on them for school, so I\rquote m doing research. It\rquote s quite a complicated subject,\rdblquote  he said importantly. \ldblquote I\rquote m against them myself.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Sit down, Bentley,\rdblquote  said Baley, desperately, \ldblquote and don\rquote t bother Mr. Olivaw.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He\rquote s not bothering me, Elijah. I\rquote d like to talk to you about the problem, Bentley, another time. Your father and I will be very busy tonight.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Thanks, Mr. Olivaw.\rdblquote  Bentley took his seat and, with a look of distaste in his mother\rquote s direction, broke off a portion of the crumbly pink zymoveal with his fork.\par
Baley thought: Busy tonight?\par
Then, with a resounding shock, he remembered his job. He thought of a Spacer lying dead in Spacetown and realized that for hours he had been so involved with his own dilemma that he had forgotten the cold fact of murder.\par
\pard\keepn\pagebb\s1\sb240\sa60\qc\kerning32\b\f2\fs32 Chapter 5\par
\pard\keepn\s2\sb240\sa240\qc\kerning0\i\fs28 ANALYSIS OF A MURDER\par
\pard\fi216\qj\b0\i0\f0\fs24 Jessie said good-by to them. She was wearing a formal hat and a little jacket of keratofiber as she said, \ldblquote I hope you\rquote ll excuse me, Mr. Olivaw. I know you have a great deal to discuss with Lije.\rdblquote\par
She pushed her son ahead of her as she opened the door.\par
\ldblquote When will you be back, Jessie?\rdblquote  asked Baley.\par
She paused. \ldblquote When do you want me to be back?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well ... No use staying out all night. Why don\rquote t you come back your usual time? Midnight or so.\rdblquote  He looked doubtfully at R. Daneel.\par
R. Daneel nodded. \ldblquote I regret having to drive you from your home.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t worry about that, Mr. Olivaw. You\rquote re not driving me out at all. This is my usual evening out with the girls anyway. Come on, Ben.\rdblquote\par
The youngster was rebellious. \ldblquote Aw, why the dickens do I have to go, anyway. I\rquote m not going to bother them. Nuts!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Now, do as I say.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, why can\rquote t I go to the etherics along with you?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Because I\rquote m going with some friends and you\rquote ve got other things--\rdblquote\par
The door closed behind them.\par
And now the moment had come. Baley had put it off in his mind. lie had thought: First let\rquote s meet the robot and see what he\rquote s like. Then it was: Let\rquote s get him home. And then: Let\rquote s eat.\par
But now it was all over and there was no room for further delay. It was down at last to the question of murder, of interstellar complications, of possible raises in ratings, of possible disgrace. And he had no way of even beginning except to turn to the robot for help.\par
His fingernails moved aimlessly on the table, which had not been returned to its wall recess.\par
R. Daneel said, \ldblquote How secure are we against being overheard?\rdblquote\par
Baley looked up, surprised. \ldblquote No one would listen to what\rquote s proceeding in another man\rquote s apartment.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It is not your custom to eavesdrop?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It just isn\rquote t done, Daneel. You might as well suppose they\rquote d--I don\rquote t know--that they\rquote d look in your plate while you\rquote re eating.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Or that they would commit murder?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It is against your customs to kill, is it not, Elijah?\rdblquote\par
Baley felt anger rising. \ldblquote See here, if we\rquote re going to be partners, don\rquote t try to imitate Spacer arrogance. There\rquote s no room for it in you, R. Daneel.\rdblquote  He could not resist emphasizing the \ldblquote R.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I am sorry if I have hurt your feelings, Elijah. My intention was only to indicate that, since human beings are occasionally capable of murder in defiance of custom, they may be able to violate custom for the smaller impropriety of eavesdropping.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The apartment is adequately insulated,\rdblquote  said Baley, still frowning. \ldblquote You haven\rquote t heard anything from the apartments on any side of us, have you? Well, they won\rquote t hear us, either. Besides, why should anyone think anything of importance is going on here?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Let us not underestimate the enemy.\rdblquote\par
Baley shrugged. \ldblquote Let\rquote s get started. My information is sketchy, so I can spread out my hand without much trouble. I know that a man named Roj Nemennuh Sarton, a citizen of the planet Aurora, and a resident of Spacetown, has been murdered by person or persons unknown. I understand that it is the opinion of the Spacers that this is not an isolated event. Am I right?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You are quite right, Elijah.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote They tie it up with recent attempts to sabotage the Spacer-sponsored project of converting us to an integrated human/robot society on the model of the Outer Worlds, and assume the murder was the product of a well-organized terrorist group.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All right. Then to begin with, is this Spacer assumption necessarily true? Why can\rquote t the murder have been the work of an isolated fanatic? There is strong anti-robot sentiment on Earth, but there are no organized parties advocating violence of this sort.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Not openly, perhaps. No.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Even a secret organization dedicated to the destruction of robots and robot factories would have the common sense to realize that the worst thing they could do would be to murder a Spacer. It seems much more likely to have been the work of an unbalanced mind.\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel listened carefully, then said, \ldblquote I think the weight of probability is against the \lquote fanatic\rquote  theory. The person killed was too well chosen and the time of the murder too appropriate for anything but deliberate planning on the part of an organized group.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, then, you\rquote ve got more information than I have. Spill it!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Your phraseology is obscure, but I think I understand. I will have to explain some of the background to you. As seen from Spacetown, Elijah, relations with Earth are unsatisfactory.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Tough,\rdblquote  muttered Baley.\par
\ldblquote I have been told that when Spacetown was first established, it was taken for granted by most of our people that Earth would be willing to adopt the integrated society that has worked so well on the Outer Worlds. Even after the first riots, we thought that it was only a matter of your people getting over the first shock of novelty.\par
\ldblquote That has not proven to be the case. Even with the co-operation of the Terrestrial government and of most of the various City governments, resistance has been continuous and progress has been very slow. Naturally, this has been a matter of great concern to our people.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Out of altruism, I suppose,\rdblquote  said Baley.\par
\ldblquote Not entirely,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel, \ldblquote although it is good of you to attribute worthy motives to them. It is our common belief that a healthy and modernized Earth would be of great benefit to the whole Galaxy. At least, it is the common belief among our people at Spacetown. I must admit that there are strong elements opposed to them on the Outer Worlds.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What? Disagreement among the Spacers?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Certainly. There are some who think that a modernized Earth will be a dangerous and an imperialistic Earth. This is particularly true among the populations of those older worlds which are closer to Earth and have greater reason to remember the first few centuries of interstellar travel when their worlds were controlled, politically and economically, by Earth.\rdblquote\par
Baley sighed. \ldblquote Ancient history. Are they really worried? Are they still kicking at us for things that happened a thousand years ago?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Humans,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel, \ldblquote have their own peculiar makeup. They are not as reasonable, in many ways, as we robots, since their circuits are not as preplanned. I am told that this, too, has its advantages.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Perhaps it may,\rdblquote  said Baley, dryly.\par
\ldblquote You are in a better position to know,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel. \ldblquote In any case, continuing failure on Earth has strengthened the Nationalist parties on the Outer Worlds. They say that it is obvious that Earthmen are different from Spacers and cannot be fitted into the same traditions. They say that if we imposed robots on Earth by superior force, we would be loosing destruction on the Galaxy. One thing they never forget, you see, is that Earth\rquote s population is eight billions, while the total population of the fifty Outer Worlds combined is scarcely more than five and a half billions. Our people here, particularly Dr. Sarton--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He was a doctor?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote A Doctor of Sociology, specializing in robotics, and a very brilliant man.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I see. Go on.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote As I said, Dr. Sarton and the others realized that Spacetown and all it meant would not exist much longer if such sentiments on the Outer Worlds were allowed to grow by feeding on our continued failure. Dr. Sarton felt that the time had come to make a supreme effort to understand the psychology of the Earthman. It is easy to say that the Earth people are innately conservative and to speak tritely of \lquote the unchanging Earth\rquote  and \lquote the inscrutable Terrestrial mind,\rquote  but that is only evading the problem.\par
\ldblquote Dr. Sarton said it was ignorance speaking and that we could not dismiss the Earthman with a proverb or a bromide. He said the Spacers who were trying to remake Earth must abandon the isolation of Spacetown and mingle with Earthmen. They must live as they, think as they, be as they.\rdblquote\par
Baley said, \ldblquote The Spacers? Impossible.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You are quite right,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel. \ldblquote Despite his views, Dr. Sarton himself could not have brought himself to enter any of the Cities, and he knew it. He would have been unable to bear the hugeness and the crowds. Even if he had been forced inside at the point of a blaster, the externals would have weighed him down so that he could never have penetrated the inner truths for which he sought.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What about the way they\rquote re always worrying about disease?\rdblquote  demanded Baley. \ldblquote Don\rquote t forget that. I don\rquote t think there\rquote s one of them that would risk entering a City on that account alone.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote There is that, too. Disease in the Earthly sense is unknown on the Outer Worlds and the fear of the unknown is always morbid. Dr. Sarton appreciated all of this, but, nevertheless, he insisted on the necessity of growing to know the Earthman and his way of life intimately.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He seems to have worked himself into a corner.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Not quite. The objections to entering the City hold for human Spacers. Robot Spacers are another thing entirely.\rdblquote\par
Baley thought: I keep forgetting, damn it. Aloud, he said, \ldblquote Oh?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel. \ldblquote We are more flexible, naturally. At least in this respect. We can be designed for adaptation to an Earthly life. By being built into a particularly close similarity to the human externals, we could be accepted by Earthmen and allowed a closer view of their life.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And you yourself--\rdblquote  began Baley in sudden enlightenment.\par
\ldblquote Am just such a robot. For a year, Dr. Sarton had been working upon the design and construction of such robots. I was the first of his robots and so far the only one. Unfortunately, my education is not yet complete. I have been hurried into my role prematurely as a result of the murder.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Then not all Spacer robots are like you? I mean, some look more like robots and less like humans. Right?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why, naturally. The outward appearance is dependent on a robot\rquote s function. My own function requires a very manlike appearance, and I have it. Others are different, although all are humanoid. Certainly they are more humanoid than the distressingly primitive models I saw at the shoe counter. Are all your robots like that?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote More or less,\rdblquote  said Baley. \ldblquote You don\rquote t approve?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Of course not. It is difficult to accept a gross parody of the human form as an intellectual equal. Can your factories do no better?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m sure they can, Daneel. I think we just prefer to know when we\rquote re dealing with a robot and when we\rquote re not.\rdblquote  He stared directly into the robot\rquote s eyes as he said that. They were bright and moist, as a human\rquote s would be, but it seemed to Baley that their gaze was steady and did not flicker slightly from point to point as a man\rquote s would.\par
R. Daneel said, \ldblquote I am hopeful that in time I will grow to understand that point of view.\rdblquote\par
For a moment, Baley thought there was sarcasm in the sentence, then dismissed the possibility.\par
\ldblquote In any case,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel, \ldblquote Dr. Sarton saw clearly the fact that it was a case for C/Fe.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote See fee? What\rquote s that?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Just the chemical symbols for the elements carbon and iron, Elijah. Carbon is the basis of human life and iron of robot life. It becomes easy to speak of C/Fe when you wish to express a culture that combines the best of the two on an equal but parallel basis.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote See fee. Do you write it with a hyphen? Or how?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, Elijah. A diagonal line between the two is the accepted way. It symbolizes neither one nor the other, but a mixture of the two, without priority.\rdblquote\par
Against his will, Baley found himself interested. Formal education on Earth included virtually no information on Outer World history or sociology after the Great Rebellion that made them independent of the mother planet. The popular book-film romances, to be sure, had their stock Outer World characters: the visiting tycoon, choleric and eccentric; the beautiful heiress, invariably smitten by the Earthman\rquote s charms and drowning disdain in love; the arrogant Spacer rival, wicked and forever beaten. These were worthless pictures, since they denied even the most elementary and well-known truths: that Spacers never entered Cities and Spacer women virtually never visited Earth.\par
For the first time in his life, Baley was stirred by an odd curiosity. What was Spacer life really like?\par
He brought his mind back to the issue at hand with something of an effort. He said, \ldblquote I think I get what you\rquote re driving at. Your Dr. Sarton was attacking the problem of Earth\rquote s conversion to C/Fe from a new and promising angle. Our conservative groups or Medievalists, as they call themselves, were perturbed. They were afraid he might succeed. So they killed him. That\rquote s the motivation that makes it an organized plot and not an isolated outrage. Right?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I would put it about like that, Elijah. Yes.\rdblquote\par
Baley whistled thoughtfully under his breath. His long fingers tapped lightly against the table. Then he shook his head. \ldblquote It won\rquote t wash. It won\rquote t wash at all.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Pardon me. I do not understand you.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m trying to get the picture. An Earthman walks into Spacetown, walks up to Dr. Sarton, blasts him, and walks out. I just don\rquote t see it. Surely the entrance to Spacetown is guarded.\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel nodded. \ldblquote I think it is safe to say that no Earthman can possibly have passed through the entrance illegally.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Then where does that leave you?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It would leave us in a confusing position, Elijah, if the entrance were the only way of reaching Spacetown from New York City.\rdblquote\par
Baley watched his partner thoughtfully. \ldblquote I don\rquote t get you. It\rquote s the only connection between the two.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Directly between the two, yes.\rdblquote  R. Daneel waited a moment, then said, \ldblquote You do not follow me. Is that not so?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That is so. I don\rquote t get you at all.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, if it will not offend you, I will try to explain myself. May I have a piece of paper and a writer? Thank you. Look here, partner Elijah. I will draw a big circle and label it \lquote New York City.\rquote  Now, tangent to it, I will draw a small circle and label it \lquote Spacetown.\rquote  Here, where they touch, I draw an arrowhead and label it \lquote Barrier.\rquote  Now do you see no other connection?\rdblquote\par
Baley said, \ldblquote Of course not. There is no other connection.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote In a way,\rdblquote  said the robot, \ldblquote I am glad to hear you say this. It is in accordance with what I have been taught about Terrestrial ways of thinking. The barrier is the only direct connection. But both the City and Spacetown are open to the countryside in all directions. It is possible for a Terrestrial to leave the City at any of numerous exits and strike out cross country to Spacetown, where no barrier will stop him.\rdblquote\par
The tip of Baley\rquote s tongue touched his upper lip and for a moment stayed there. Then he said, \ldblquote Cross country?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Cross country! Alone?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Walking?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Undoubtedly walking. Walking would offer the least chance of detection. The murder took place early in the working day and the trip was undoubtedly negotiated in the hours before dawn.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Impossible! There isn\rquote t a man in the City who would do it. Leave the City? Alone?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Ordinarily, it would seem unlikely. Yes. We Spacers know that. It is why we guard only the entrance. Even in the Great Riot, your people attacked only at the barrier that then protected the entrance. Not one left the City.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, then?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But now we are dealing with an unusual situation. It is not the blind attack of a mob following the line of least resistance, but the organized attempt of a small group to strike, deliberately, at the unguarded point. It explains why, as you say, a Terrestrial could enter Spacetown, walk up to his victim, kill him, and walk away. The man attacked through a complete blind spot on our part.\rdblquote\par
Baley shook his head. \ldblquote It\rquote s too unlikely. Have your people done anything to check that theory?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, we have. Your Commissioner of Police was present almost at the time of the murder--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I know. He told me so.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That, Elijah, is another example of the timeliness of the murder. Your Commissioner has co-operated with Dr. Sarton in the past and he was the Earthman with whom Dr. Sarton planned to make initial arrangements concerning the infiltration of your city by R\rquote s such as myself. The appointment for that morning was to concern that. The murder, of course, stopped those plans, at least temporarily, and the fact that it happened when your own Commissioner of Police was actually within Spacetown made the entire situation more difficult and embarrassing for Earth, and for our own people, too.\par
\ldblquote But that is not what I started to say. Your Commissioner was present. We said to him, \lquote The man must have come cross country.\rquote  Like you, he said, \lquote Impossible,\rquote  or perhaps, \lquote Unthinkable.\rquote  He was quite disturbed, of course, and perhaps that may have made it difficult for him to see the essential point. Nevertheless, we forced him to begin checking that possibility almost at once.\rdblquote\par
Baley thought of the Commissioner\rquote s broken glasses and, even in the middle of somber thoughts, a corner of his mouth twitched. Poor Julius! Yes, he would be disturbed. Of course, there would be no way for Enderby to have explained the situation to the lofty Spacers, who looked upon physical disability as a peculiarly disgusting attribute of the non-genetically selected Earthmen. At least, he couldn\rquote t without losing face, and face was valuable to Police Commissioner Julius Enderby. Well, Earthmen had to stick together in some respects. The robot would never find out about Enderby\rquote s nearsightedness from Baley.\par
R. Daneel continued, \ldblquote One by one, the various exit points from the City were investigated. Do you know how many there are, Elijah?\rdblquote\par
Baley shook his head, then hazarded, \ldblquote Twenty?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Five hundred and two.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Originally, there were many more. Five hundred and two are all that remain functional. Your City represents a slow growth, Elijah. It was once open to the sky and people crossed from City to country freely.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Of course. I know that.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, when it was first enclosed, there were many exits left. Five hundred and two still remain. The rest are built over or blocked up. We are not counting, of course, the entrance points for air freight.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, what of the exit points?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It was hopeless. They are unguarded. We could find no official who was in charge or who considered them under his jurisdiction. It seemed as though no one even knew they existed. A man could have walked out of any of them at any time and returned at will. He would never have been detected.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Anything else? The weapon was gone, I suppose.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, yes.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Any clues of any sort?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote None. We have investigated the grounds surrounding Spacetown thoroughly. The robots on the truck farms were quite useless as possible witnesses. They are little more than automatic farm machinery, scarcely humanoid. And there were no humans.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Uh-huh. What next?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Having failed, so far, at one end, Spacetown, we will work at the other, New York City. It will be our duty to track down all possible subversive groups, to sift all dissident organizations--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote How much time do you intend to spend?\rdblquote  interrupted Baley.\par
\ldblquote As little as possible, as much as necessary.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Baley, thoughtfully, \ldblquote I wish you had another partner in this mess.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I do not,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel. \ldblquote The Commissioner spoke very highly of your loyalty and ability.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It was nice of him,\rdblquote  said Baley sardonically. He thought: Poor Julius. I\rquote m on his conscience and he tries hard.\par
\ldblquote We didn\rquote t rely entirely on him,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel. \ldblquote We checked your records. You have expressed yourself openly against the use of robots in your department.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh? Do you object?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Not at all. Your opinions are, obviously, your own. But it made it necessary for us to check your psychological profile very closely. We know that, although you dislike R\rquote s intensely, you will work with one if you conceive it to be your duty. You have an extraordinarily high loyalty aptitude and a respect for legitimate authority. It is what we need. Commissioner Enderby judged you well.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You have no personal resentment toward my anti-robot sentiments?\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel said, \ldblquote If they do not prevent you from working with me and helping me do what is required of me, how can they matter?\rdblquote\par
Baley felt stopped. He said, belligerently, \ldblquote Well, then, if I pass the test, how about you? What makes you a detective?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I do not understand you.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You were designed as an information-gathering machine. A manimitation to record the facts of human life for the Spacers.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That is a good beginning for an investigator, is it not? To be an information-gathering machine?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote A beginning, maybe. But it\rquote s not all there is, by a long shot.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote To be sure, there has been a final adjustment of my circuits.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote d be curious to hear the details of that, Daneel.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That is easy enough. A particularly strong drive has been inserted into my motivation banks; a desire for justice.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Justice!\rdblquote  cried Baley. The irony faded from his face and was replaced by a look of the most earnest distrust.\par
But R. Daneel turned swiftly in his chair and stared at the door. \ldblquote Someone is out there.\rdblquote\par
Someone was. The door opened and Jessie, pale and thin-lipped, walked in.\par
Baley was startled. \ldblquote Why, Jessie! Is anything wrong?\rdblquote\par
She stood there, eyes not meeting his. \ldblquote I\rquote m sorry. I had to ... Her voice trailed off.\par
\ldblquote Where\rquote s Bentley?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He\rquote s to stay the night in the Youth Hall.\rdblquote\par
Baley said, \ldblquote Why? I didn\rquote t tell you to do that.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You said your partner would stay the night. I felt he would need Bentley\rquote s room.\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel said, \ldblquote There was no necessity, Jessie.\rdblquote\par
Jessie lifted her eyes to R. Daneel\rquote s face, staring at it earnestly.\par
Baley looked at his fingertips, sick at what might follow, somehow unable to interpose. The momentary silence pressed thickly on his eardrums and then, far away, as though through folds of plastex, he heard his wife say, \ldblquote I think you are a robot, Daneel.\rdblquote\par
And R. Daneel replied, in a voice as calm as ever, \ldblquote I am.\rdblquote\par
\pard\keepn\pagebb\s1\sb240\sa60\qc\kerning32\b\f2\fs32 Chapter 6\par
\pard\keepn\s2\sb240\sa240\qc\kerning0\i\fs28 WHISPERS IN A BEDROOM\par
\pard\fi216\qj\b0\i0\f0\fs24 On the uppermost levels of some of the wealthiest subsections of the City are the natural Solariums, where a partition of quartz with a movable metal shield excludes the air but lets in the sunlight. There the wives and daughters of the City\rquote s highest administrators and executives may tan themselves. There a unique thing happens every evening.\par
Night falls.\par
In the rest of the City (including the UV-Solariums, where the millions, in strict sequence of allotted time, may occasionally expose themselves to the artificial wavelengths of arc lights) there are only the arbitrary cycles of hours.\par
The business of the City might easily continue in three eight-hour or four six-hour shifts, by \ldblquote day\rdblquote  and \ldblquote night\rdblquote  alike. Light and work could easily proceed endlessly. There are always civic reformers who periodically suggest such a thing in the interests of economy and efficiency.\par
The notion is never accepted.\par
Much of the earlier habits of Earthly society have been given up in the interests of that same economy and efficiency: space, privacy, even much of free will. They are the products of civilization, however, and not more than ten thousand years old.\par
The adjustment of sleep to night, however, is as old as man: a million years. The habit is not easy to give up. Although the evening is unseen, apartment lights dim as the hours of darkness pass and the City\rquote s pulse sinks. Though no one can tell noon from midnight by any cosmic phenomenon along the enclosed avenues of the City, mankind follows the mute partitionings of the hour hand.\par
The expressways empty, the noise of life sinks, the moving mob among the colossal alleys melts away; New York City lies in Earth\rquote s unnoticed shadow, and its population sleeps.\par
Elijah Baley did not sleep. He lay in bed and there was no light in his apartment, but that was as far as it went.\par
Jessie lay next to him, motionless in the darkness. He had not felt nor heard her move.\par
On the other side of the wall sat, stood, lay (Baley wondered which) R. Daneel Olivaw.\par
Baley whispered, \ldblquote Jessie!\rdblquote  Then again, \ldblquote Jessie!\rdblquote\par
The dark figure beside him stirred slightly under the sheet. \ldblquote What do you want?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Jessie, don\rquote t make it worse for me.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You might have told me.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote How could I? I was planning to, when I could think of a way. Jehoshaphat, Jessie--\rdblquote\par
Baley\rquote s voice returned to its whisper. \ldblquote How did you find out? Won\rquote t you tell me?\rdblquote\par
Jessie turned toward him. He could sense her eyes looking through the darkness at him.\par
\ldblquote Lije.\rdblquote  Her voice was scarcely more than a stirring of air. \ldblquote Can he hear us? That thing?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Not if we whisper.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote How do you know? Maybe he has special ears to pick up tiny sounds. Spacer robots can do all sorts of things.\rdblquote\par
Baley knew that. The pro-robot propaganda was forever stressing the miraculous feats of the Spacer robots, their endurance, their extra senses, their service to humanity in a hundred novel ways. Personally, he thought that approach defeated itself. Earthmen hated the robots all the more for their superiority.\par
He whispered, \ldblquote Not Daneel. They made him human-type on purpose. They wanted him to be accepted as a human being, so he must have only human senses.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote How do you know?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote If he had extra senses, there would be too much danger of his giving himself away as non-human by accident. He would do too much, know too much.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, maybe.\rdblquote\par
Silence fell again.\par
A minute passed and Baley tried a second time. \ldblquote Jessie, if you\rquote ll just let things be until--until ... Look, dear, it\rquote s unfair of you to be angry.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Angry? Oh, Lije, you fool. I\rquote m not angry. I\rquote m scared; I\rquote m scared clean to death.\rdblquote\par
She made a gulping sound and clutched at the neck of his pajamas. For a while, they clung together, and Baley\rquote s growing sense of injury evaporated into a troubled concern.\par
\ldblquote Why, Jessie? There\rquote s nothing to be worried about. He\rquote s harmless. I swear he is.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Can\rquote t you get rid of him, Lije?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You know I can\rquote t. It\rquote s Department business. How can I?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What kind of business, Lije? Tell me.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Now, Jessie, I\rquote m surprised at you.\rdblquote  He groped for her cheek in the darkness and patted it. It was wet. Using his pajama sleeve, he carefully wiped her eyes.\par
\ldblquote Now, look,\rdblquote  he said tenderly, \ldblquote you\rquote re being a baby.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Tell them at the Department to have someone else do it, whatever it is. Please, Lije.\rdblquote\par
Baley\rquote s voice hardened a bit. \ldblquote Jessie, you\rquote ve been a policeman\rquote s wife long enough to know an assignment is an assignment.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, why did it have to be you?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Julius Enderby--\rdblquote\par
She stiffened in his arms. \ldblquote I might have known. Why can\rquote t you tell Julius Enderby to have someone else do the dirty work just once. You stand for too much, Lije, and this is just--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All right, all right,\rdblquote  he said, soothingly.\par
She subsided, quivering.\par
Baley thought: She\rquote ll never understand.\par
Julius Enderby had been a fighting word with them since their engagement. Enderby had been two classes ahead of Baley at the City School of Administrative Studies. They had been friends. When Baley had taken his battery of aptitude tests and neuroanalysis and found himself in line for the police force, he found Enderby there ahead of him. Enderby had already moved into the plain-clothes division.\par
Baley followed Enderby, but at a continually greater distance. It was no one\rquote s fault, precisely. Baley was capable enough, efficient enough, but he lacked something that Enderby had. Enderby fit the administrative machine perfectly. He was one of those persons who was born for a hierarchy, who was just naturally comfortable in a bureaucracy. The Commissioner wasn\rquote t a great brain, and Baley knew it. He had his childish peculiarities, his intermittent rash of ostentatious Medievalism, for instance. But he was smooth with others; he offended no one; he took orders gracefully; he gave them with the proper mixture of gentleness and firmness. He even got along with the Spacers. He was perhaps over-obsequious to them (Baley himself could never have dealt with them for half a day without getting into a state of bristle; he was sure of that, even though he had never really spoken to a Spacer), but they trusted him, and that made him extremely useful to the City. So, in a Civil Service where smooth and sociable performance was more useful than an individualistic competence, Enderby went up the scale quickly, and was at the Commissioner level when Baley himself was nothing more than a C-5. Baley did not resent the contrast, though he was human enough to regret it. Enderby did not forget their earlier friendship and, in his queer way, tried to make up for his success by doing what he could for Baley.\par
The assignment of partnership with R. Daneel was an example of it.\par
It was tough and unpleasant, but there was no question that it carried within it the germs of tremendous advance. The Commissioner might have given the chance to someone else. His own talk, that morning, of needing a favor masked but did not hide that fact.\par
Jessie never saw things that way. On similar occasions in the past, she had said, \ldblquote It\rquote s your silly loyalty index. I\rquote m so tired of hearing everyone praise you for being so full of a sense of duty. Think of yourself once in a while. I notice the ones on top don\rquote t bring up the topic of their own loyalty index.\rdblquote\par
Baley lay in bed in a state of stiff wakefulness, letting Jessie calm down. He had to think. He had to be certain of his suspicions. Little things chased one another and fitted together in his mind. Slowly, they were building into a pattern.\par
He felt the mattress give as Jessie stirred.\par
\ldblquote Lije?\rdblquote  Her lips were at his ear.\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why don\rquote t you resign?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t be crazy.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote  She was suddenly almost eager. \ldblquote You can get rid of that horrible robot that way. Just walk in and tell Enderby you\rquote re through.\rdblquote\par
Baley said coldly, \ldblquote I can\rquote t resign in the middle of an important case. I can\rquote t throw the whole thing down the disposal tube just any time I feel like it. A trick like that means declassification for cause.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Even so. You can work your way up again. You can do it, Lije. There are a dozen places where you\rquote d fit into Service.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Civil Service doesn\rquote t take men who are declassified for cause. Manual labor is the only thing I can do; the only thing you could do. Bentley would lose all inherited status. For God\rquote s sake, Jessie, you don\rquote t know what it\rquote s like.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ve read about it. I\rquote m not afraid of it,\rdblquote  she mumbled.\par
\ldblquote You\rquote re crazy. You\rquote re plain crazy.\rdblquote  Baley could feel himself trembling. There was a familiar, flashing picture of his father in his mind\rquote s eye. His father, moldering away toward death.\par
Jessie sighed heavily.\par
Baley\rquote s mind turned savagely away from her. In desperation, it returned to the pattern it was constructing.\par
He said, tightly, \ldblquote Jessie, you\rquote ve got to tell me. How did you find out Daneel was a robot? What made you decide that?\rdblquote\par
She began, \ldblquote Well ...\rdblquote  and just ran down. It was the third time she had begun to explain and failed.\par
He crushed her hand in his, willing her to speak. \ldblquote Please, Jessie. What\rquote s frightening you?\rdblquote\par
She said, \ldblquote I just guessed he was a robot, Lije.\rdblquote\par
He said, \ldblquote There wasn\rquote t anything to make you guess that, Jessie. You didn\rquote t think he was a robot before you left, now did you?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No-o, but I got to thinking ...\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Come on, Jessie. What was it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well-- Look, Lije, the girls were talking in the Personal. You know how they are. Just talking about everything.\rdblquote\par
Women! thought Baley.\par
\ldblquote Anyway,\rdblquote  said Jessie. \ldblquote The rumor is all over town. It must be.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All over town?\rdblquote  Baley felt a quick and savage touch of triumph, or nearly that. Another piece in place!\par
\ldblquote It was the way they sounded. They said there was talk about a Spacer robot loose in the City. He was supposed to look just like a man and to be working with the police. They even asked me about it. They laughed and said, \lquote Does your Lije know anything about it, Jessie?\rquote  and I laughed, and said, \lquote Don\rquote t be silly!\rquote\par
\ldblquote Then we went to the etherics and I got to thinking about your new partner. Do you remember those pictures you brought home, the ones Julius Enderby took in Spacetown, to show me what Spacers looked like? Well, I got to thinking that\rquote s what your partner looked like. It just came to me that that\rquote s what he looked like and I said to myself, oh, my God, someone must\rquote ve recognized him in the shoe department and he\rquote s with Lije and I just said I had a headache and I ran--\rdblquote\par
Baley said, \ldblquote Now, Jessie, stop, stop. Get hold of yourself. Now why are you afraid? You\rquote re not afraid of Daneel himself. You faced up to him when you came home. You faced up to him fine. So--\rdblquote\par
He stopped speaking. He sat up in bed, eyes uselessly wide in the darkness.\par
He felt his wife move against his side. His hand leaped, found her lips and pressed against them. She heaved against his grip, her hands grasping his wrist and wrenching, but he leaned down against her the more heavily.\par
Then, suddenly, he released her. She whimpered.\par
He said, huskily, \ldblquote Sorry, Jessie. I was listening.\rdblquote\par
He was getting out of bed, pulling warm Plastofilm over the soles of his feet.\par
\ldblquote Lije, where are you going? Don\rquote t leave me.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s all right. I\rquote m just going to the door.\rdblquote\par
The Plastofilm made a soft, shuffling noise as he circled the bed. He cracked the door to the living room and waited a long moment. Nothing happened. It was so quiet, he could hear the thin whistle of Jessie\rquote s breath from their bed. He could hear the dull rhythm of blood in his ears.\par
Baley\rquote s hand crept through the opening of the door, snaking out to the spot he needed no light to find. His fingers closed upon the knob that controlled the ceiling illumination. He exerted the smallest pressure he could and the ceiling gleamed dimly, so dimly that the lower half of the living room remained in semidusk.\par
He saw enough, however. The main door was closed and the living room lay lifeless and quiet.\par
He turned the knob back into the off position and moved back to bed.\par
It was all he needed. The pieces fit. The pattern was complete. Jessie pleaded with him. \ldblquote Lije, what\rquote s wrong?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Nothing\rquote s wrong, Jessie. Everything\rquote s all right. He\rquote s not here.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The robot? Do you mean he\rquote s gone? For good?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, no. He\rquote ll be back. And before he does, answer my question.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What question?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What are you afraid of?\rdblquote  Jessie said nothing.\par
Baley grew more insistent. \ldblquote You said you were scared to death.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Of him.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, we went through that. You weren\rquote t afraid of him and, besides, you know quite well a robot cannot hurt a human being.\rdblquote\par
Her words came slowly. \ldblquote I thought if everyone knew he was a robot there might be a riot. We\rquote d be killed.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why kill us?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You know what riots are like.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote They don\rquote t even know where the robot is, do they?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote They might find out.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And that\rquote s what you\rquote re afraid of, a riot?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Sh!\rdblquote  He pressed Jessie down to the pillow.\par
Then he put his lips to her ear. \ldblquote He\rquote s come back. Now listen and don\rquote t say a word. Everything\rquote s fine. He\rquote ll be gone in the morning and he won\rquote t be back. There\rquote ll be no riot, nothing.\rdblquote\par
He was almost contented as he said that, almost completely contented. He felt he could sleep.\par
He thought again: No riot, nothing. And no declassification. And just before he actually fell asleep, he thought: Not even a murder investigation. Not even that. The whole thing\rquote s solved ...\par
He slept.\par
\pard\keepn\pagebb\s1\sb240\sa60\qc\kerning32\b\f2\fs32 Chapter 7\par
\pard\keepn\s2\sb240\sa240\qc\kerning0\i\fs28 EXCURSION INTO SPACETOWN\par
\pard\fi216\qj\b0\i0\f0\fs24 Police Commissioner Julius Enderby polished his glasses with exquisite care and placed them upon the bridge of his nose.\par
Baley thought: It\rquote s a good trick. Keeps you busy while you\rquote re thinking what to say, and it doesn\rquote t cost money the way lighting up a pipe does.\par
And because the thought had entered his mind, he drew out his pipe and dipped into his pinched store of rough-cut. One of the few luxury crops still grown on Earth was tobacco, and its end was visibly approaching. Prices had gone up, never down, in Baley\rquote s lifetime; quotas down, never up.\par
Enderby, having adjusted his glasses, felt for the switch at one end of his desk and flicked his door into one-way transparency for a moment. \ldblquote Where is he now, by the way?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He told me he wanted to be shown through the Department, and I let Jack Tobin do the honors.\rdblquote  Baley lit his pipe and tightened its baffle carefully. The Commissioner, like most non-indulgers, was petty about tobacco smoke.\par
\ldblquote I hope you didn\rquote t tell him Daneel was a robot.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Of course I didn\rquote t.\rdblquote\par
The Commissioner did not relax. One hand remained aimlessly busy with the automatic calendar on his desk.\par
\ldblquote How is it?\rdblquote  he asked, without looking at Baley.\par
\ldblquote Middling rough.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m sorry, Lije.\rdblquote\par
Baley said, firmly, \ldblquote You might have warned me that he looked completely human.\rdblquote\par
The Commissioner looked surprised. \ldblquote I didn\rquote t?\rdblquote  Then, with sudden petulance, \ldblquote Damn it, you should have known. I wouldn\rquote t have asked you to have him stay at your house if he looked like R. Sammy. Now would I?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I know, Commissioner, but I\rquote d never seen a robot like that and you had. I didn\rquote t even know such things were possible. I just wish you\rquote d mentioned it, that\rquote s all.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Look, Lije, I\rquote m sorry. I should have told you. You\rquote re right. It\rquote s just that this job, this whole deal, has me so on edge that half the time I\rquote m just snapping at people for no reason. He, I mean this Daneel thing, is a new-type robot. It\rquote s still in the experimental stage.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote So he explained himself.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh. Well, that\rquote s it, then.\rdblquote\par
Baley tensed a little. This was it, now. He said, casually, teeth clenched on pipestem. \ldblquote R. Daneel has arranged a trip to Spacetown for me.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote To Spacetown!\rdblquote  Enderby looked up with instant indignation. \ldblquote Yes. It\rquote s the logical next move, Commissioner. I\rquote d like to see the scene of the crime, ask a few questions.\rdblquote\par
Enderby shook his head decidedly. \ldblquote I don\rquote t think that\rquote s a good idea, Lije. We\rquote ve gone over the ground. I doubt there\rquote s anything new to be learned. And they\rquote re strange people. Kid gloves! They\rquote ve got to be handled with kid gloves. You don\rquote t have the experience.\rdblquote\par
He put a plump hand to his forehead and added, with unexpected fervor, \ldblquote I hate them.\rdblquote\par
Baley inserted hostility into his voice. \ldblquote Damn it, the robot came here and I should go there. It\rquote s bad enough sharing a front seat with a robot; I hate to take a back seat. Of course, if you don\rquote t think I\rquote m capable of running this investigation, Commissioner--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It isn\rquote t that, Lije. It\rquote s not you, it\rquote s the Spacers. You don\rquote t know what they\rquote re like.\rdblquote\par
Baley deepened his frown. \ldblquote Well, then, Commissioner, suppose you come along.\rdblquote  His right hand rested on his knee, and two of his fingers crossed automatically as he said that.\par
The Commissioner\rquote s eyes widened. \ldblquote No, Lije. I won\rquote t go there. Don\rquote t ask me to.\rdblquote  He seemed visibly to catch hold of his runaway words. More quietly, he said, with an unconvincing smile, \ldblquote Lots of work here, you know. I\rquote m days behind.\rdblquote\par
Baley regarded him thoughtfully. \ldblquote I tell you what, then. Why not get into it by trimension later on. Just for a while, you understand. In case I need help.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, yes. I suppose I can do that.\rdblquote  He sounded unenthusiastic.\par
\ldblquote Good.\rdblquote  Baley looked at the wall clock, nodded, and got up. \ldblquote I\rquote ll be in touch with you.\rdblquote\par
Baley looked back as he left the office, keeping the door open for part of an additional second. He saw the Commissioner\rquote s head begin bending down toward the crook of one elbow as it rested on the desk. The plain-clothes man could almost swear he heard a sob.\par
Jehoshaphat! he thought, in outright shock.\par
He paused in the common room and sat on the corner of a nearby desk, ignoring its occupant, who looked up, murmured a casual greeting, and returned to his work.\par
Baley unclipped the baffle from the bowl of the pipe and blew into it. He inverted the pipe itself over the desk\rquote s small ash vacuum and let the powdery white tobacco ash vanish. He looked regretfully at the empty pipe, readjusted the baffle, and put it away. Another pipeful gone forever!\par
He reconsidered what had just taken place. In one way, Enderby had not surprised him. He had expected resistance to any attempt on his own part to enter Spacetown. He had heard the Commissioner talk often enough about the difficulties of dealing with Spacers, about the dangers of allowing any but experienced negotiators to have anything to do with them, even over trifles.\par
He had not expected, however, to have the Commissioner give in so easily. He had supposed, at the very least, that Enderby would have insisted on accompanying him. The pressure of other work was meaningless in the face of the importance of this problem.\par
And that was not what Baley wanted. He wanted exactly what he had gotten. He wanted the Commissioner to be present by trimensional personification so that he could witness the proceedings from a point of safety.\par
Safety was the key word. Baley would need a witness that could not be put out of the way immediately. He needed that much as the minimum guarantee of his own safety.\par
The Commissioner had agreed to that at once. Baley remembered the parting sob, or ghost of one, and thought: Jehoshaphat, the man\rquote s into this past his depth.\par
A cheerful, slurring voice sounded just at Baley\rquote s shoulder and Baley started.\par
\ldblquote What the devil do you want?\rdblquote  he demanded savagely.\par
The smile on R. Sammy\rquote s face remained foolishly fixed. \ldblquote Jack says to tell you Daneel is ready, Lije.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All right. Now get out of here.\rdblquote\par
He frowned at the robot\rquote s departing back. There was nothing so irritating as having that clumsy metal contraption forever making free with your front name. He\rquote d complained about that when R. Sammy first arrived and the Commissioner had shrugged his shoulders and said, \ldblquote You can\rquote t have it both ways, Lije. The public insists that City robots be built with a strong friendship circuit. All right, then. He is drawn to you. He calls you by the friendliest name he knows.\rdblquote\par
Friendship circuit! No robot built, of any type, could possibly hurt a human being. That was the First Law of Robotics:\par
\pard\li1440\ri1440\sb120\sa120\qj\fs20\ldblquote A robot may not injure a human being, or, through inaction, allow a human being to come to harm.\rdblquote\par
\pard\fi216\qj\fs24 No positronic brain was ever built without that injunction driven so deeply into its basic circuits that no conceivable derangement could displace it. There was no need for specialized friendship circuits.\par
Yet the Commissioner was right. The Earthman\rquote s distrust for robots was something quite irrational and friendship circuits had to be incorporated, just as all robots had to be made smiling. On Earth, at any rate.\par
R. Daneel, now, never smiled.\par
Sighing, Baley rose to his feet. He thought: Spacetown, next stop-- or, maybe, last stop!\par
The police forces of the City, as well as certain high officials, could still make use of individual squad cars along the corridors of the City and even along the ancient underground motorways that were barred to foot traffic. There were perennial demands on the part of the Liberals that these motorways be converted to children\rquote s playgrounds, to new shopping areas, or to expressway or localway extensions.\par
The strong pleas of \ldblquote Civic safety!\rdblquote  remained unvanquished, however. In cases of fires too large to be handled by local devices, in cases of massive breakdowns in power lines or ventilators, most of all in cases of serious riot, there had to be some means whereby the forces of the City could be mobilized at the stricken point in a hurry. No substitute for the motorways existed or could exist.\par
Baley had traveled along a motorway several times before in his life, but its indecent emptiness always depressed him. It seemed a million miles from the warm, living pulsation of the City. It stretched out like a blind and hollow worm before his eyes as he sat at the controls of the squad car. It opened continuously into new stretches as he moved around this gentle curve or that. Behind him, he knew without looking, another blind and hollow worm continually contracted and closed. The motorway was well lit, but lighting was meaningless in the silence and emptiness.\par
R. Daneel did nothing to break that silence or fill that emptiness. He looked straight ahead, as unimpressed by the empty motorway as by the bulging expressway.\par
In one sounding moment, to the tune of a wild whine of the squad car\rquote s siren, they popped out of the motorway and curved gradually into the vehicular lane of a City corridor.\par
The vehicular lanes were still conscientiously marked down each major corridor in reverence for one vestigial portion of the past. There were no vehicles any longer, except for squad cars, fire engines, and maintenance trucks, and pedestrians used the lanes in complete self-assurance. They scattered in indignant hurry before the advance of Baley\rquote s squealing car.\par
Baley, himself, drew a freer breath as noise surged in about him, but it was an interval only. In less than two hundred yards they turned into the subdued corridors that led to Spacetown Entrance.\par
They were expected. The guards obviously knew R. Daneel by sight and, although themselves human, nodded to him without the least self-consciousness.\par
One approached Baley and saluted with perfect, if frigid, military courtesy. He was tall and grave, though not the perfect specimen of Spacer physique that R. Daneel was.\par
He said, \ldblquote Your identification card, if you please, sir.\rdblquote\par
It was inspected quickly but thoroughly. Baley noticed that the guard wore flesh-colored gloves and had an all but unnoticeable filter in each nostril.\par
The guard saluted again and returned the card. He said, \ldblquote There is a small Men\rquote s Personal here which we would be pleased to have you use if you wish to shower.\rdblquote\par
It was in Baley\rquote s mind to deny the necessity, but R. Daneel plucked gently at his sleeve, as the guard stepped back to his place.\par
R. Daneel said, \ldblquote It is customary, partner Elijah, for City dwellers to shower before entering Spacetown. I tell you this since I know you have no desire, through lack of information on this matter, to render yourself or ourselves uncomfortable. It is also advisable for you to attend to any matters of personal hygiene you may think advisable. There will be no facilities within Spacetown for that purpose.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No facilities!\rdblquote  said Baley, strenuously. \ldblquote But that\rquote s impossible.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I mean, of course,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel, \ldblquote none for use by City dwellers.\rdblquote\par
Baley\rquote s face filled with a clearly hostile astonishment.\par
R. Daneel said, \ldblquote I regret the situation, but it is a matter of custom.\rdblquote\par
Wordlessly, Baley entered the Personal. He felt, rather than saw, R. Daneel entering behind him.\par
He thought: Checking on me? Making sure I wash the City dust off myself?\par
For a furious moment, he reveled in the thought of the shock he was preparing for Spacetown. It seemed to him suddenly minor that he might, in effect, be pointing a blaster at his own chest.\par
The Personal was small, but it was well appointed and antiseptic in its cleanliness. There was a trace of sharpness in the air. Baley sniffed at it, momentarily puzzled.\par
Then he thought: Ozone! They\rquote ve got ultraviolet radiation flooding the place.\par
A little sign blinked on and off several times, then remained steadily lit. It said, \ldblquote Visitor will please remove all clothing, including shoes, and place it in the receptacle below.\rdblquote\par
Baley acquiesced. He unhitched his blaster and blaster strap and recircled it about his naked waist. It felt heavy and uncomfortable.\par
The receptacle closed and his clothing was gone. The lighted sign blanked out. A new sign flashed ahead.\par
It said: \ldblquote Visitor will please tend to personal needs, then make use of the shower indicated by arrow.\rdblquote\par
Baley felt like a machine tool being shaped by long-distance force edges on an assembly line.\par
His first act upon entering the small shower cubicle was to draw up the moisture-proof flap on his blaster holster and clip it down firmly all about. He knew by long-standing test that he could still draw and use it in less than five seconds.\par
There was no knob or hook on which to hang his blaster. There was not even a visible shower head. He placed it in a corner away from the cubicle\rquote s entrance door.\par
Another sign flashed: \ldblquote Visitor will please hold arms directly out from his body and stand in the central circle with feet in the indicated positions.\rdblquote\par
As he placed his feet in the small depressions allowed for them, the sign blanked out. As it did so, a stinging, foaming spray hit him from ceiling, floor, and four walls. He felt the water welling up even beneath the soles of his feet. For a full minute it lasted, his skin reddening under the combined force of the heat and pressure and his lungs gasping for air in the warm dampness. There followed another minute of cool, low-pressure spray, and then finally a minute of warm air that left him dry and refreshed.\par
He picked up his blaster and blaster strap and found that they, too, were dry and warm. He strapped them on and stepped out of the cubicle in time to see R. Daneel emerge from a neighboring shower. Of course! R. Daneel was not a City dweller, but he had accumulated City dust.\par
Quite automatically, Baley looked away. Then, with the thought that, after all, R. Daneel\rquote s customs were not City customs, he forced his unwilling eyes back for one moment. His lips quirked in a tiny smile. R. Daneel\rquote s resemblance to humanity was not restricted to his face and hands but had been carried out with painstaking accuracy over the entire body.\par
Baley stepped forward in the direction he had been traveling continuously since entering the Personal. He found his clothes waiting for him, neatly folded. They had a warm, clean odor to them.\par
A sign said, \ldblquote Visitor will please resume his clothing and place his hand in the indicated depression.\rdblquote\par
Baley did so. He felt a definite tingling in the ball of his middle finger as he laid it down upon the clean, milky surface. He lifted his hand hastily and found a little drop of blood oozing out. As he watched, it stopped flowing.\par
He shook it off and pinched the finger. No more blood was flowing even then.\par
Obviously, they were analyzing his blood. He felt a definite pang of anxiety. His own yearly routine examination by Department doctors, he felt sure, was not carried on with the thoroughness or, perhaps, with the knowledge of these cold robot-makers from outer space. He was not sure he wanted too probing an inquiry into the state of his health.\par
The time of waiting seemed long to Baley, but when the light flashed again, it said simply, \ldblquote Visitor will proceed.\rdblquote\par
Baley drew a long breath of relief. He walked onward and stepped through an archway. Two metal rods closed in before him and, written in luminous air, were the words: \ldblquote Visitor is warned to proceed no further.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What the devil--\rdblquote  called out Baley, forgetting in his anger the fact that he was still in the Personal.\par
R. Daneel\rquote s voice was in his ear. \ldblquote The sniffers have detected a power source, I imagine. Are you carrying your blaster, Elijah?\rdblquote\par
Baley whirled, his face a deep crimson. He tried twice, then managed to croak out, \ldblquote A police officer has his blaster on him or in easy reach at all times, on duty and off.\rdblquote\par
It was the first time he had spoken in a Personal, proper, since he was ten years old. That had been in his uncle Boris\rquote s presence and had merely been an automatic complaint when he stubbed his toe. Uncle Boris had beaten him well when he reached home and had lectured him strongly on the necessities of public decency.\par
R. Daneel said, \ldblquote No visitor may be armed. It is our custom, Elijah. Even your Commissioner leaves his blaster behind on all visits.\rdblquote\par
Under almost any other circumstances, Baley would have turned on his heel and walked away, away from Spacetown and away from that robot. Now, however, he was almost mad with desire to go through with his exact plan and have his revenge to the brim in that way. This, he thought, was the unobtrusive medical examination that had replaced the more detailed one of the early days. He could well understand, he could understand to overflowing, the indignation and anger that had led to the Barrier Riots of his youth.\par
In black anger, Baley unhitched his blaster belt. R. Daneel took it from him and placed it within a recess in the wall. A thin metal plate slithered across it.\par
\ldblquote If you will put your thumb in the depression,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel, \ldblquote only your thumb will open it later on.\rdblquote\par
Baley felt undressed, far more so, in fact, than he had felt in the shower. He stepped across the point at which the rods had lately barred him, and, finally, out of the Personal.\par
He was back in a corridor again, but there was an element of strangeness about it. Up ahead, the light had an unfamiliar quality to it. He felt a whiff of air against his face and, automatically, he thought a squad car had passed.\par
R. Daneel must have read his uneasiness in his face. He said, \ldblquote You are essentially in open air now, Elijah. It is unconditioned.\rdblquote\par
Baley felt faintly sick. How could the Spacers be so rigidly careful of a human body, merely because it came from the City, and then breathe the dirty air of the open fields? He tightened his nostrils, as though by pulling them together he could the more effectively screen the ingoing air.\par
R. Daneel said, \ldblquote I believe you will find that open air is not deleterious to human health.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All right,\rdblquote  said Baley, faintly.\par
The air currents hit annoyingly against his face. They were gentle enough, but they were erratic. That bothered him.\par
Worse came. The corridor opened into blueness and as they approached its end, strong white light washed down. Baley had seen sunlight. He had been in a natural Solarium once in the line of duty. But there, protecting glass had enclosed the place and the sun\rquote s own image had been refracted into a generalized glow. Here, all was open.\par
Automatically, he looked up at the sun, then turned away. His dazzled eyes blinked and watered.\par
A Spacer was approaching. A moment of misgiving struck Baley.\par
R. Daneel, however, stepped forward to greet the approaching man with a handshake. The Spacer turned to Baley and said, \ldblquote Won\rquote t you come with me, sir? I am Dr. Han Fastolfe.\rdblquote\par
Things were better inside one of the domes. Baley found himself goggling at the size of the rooms and the way in which space was so carelessly distributed, but was thankful for the feel of the conditioned air.\par
Fastolfe said, sitting down and crossing his long legs, \ldblquote I\rquote m assuming that you prefer conditioning to unobstructed wind.\rdblquote\par
He seemed friendly enough. There were fine wrinkles on his forehead and a certain flabbiness to the skin below his eyes and just under his chin. His hair was thinning, but showed no signs of gray. His large ears stood away from his head, giving him a humorous and homely appearance that comforted Baley.\par
Early that morning, Baley had looked once again at those pictures of Spacetown that Enderby had taken. R. Daneel had just arranged the Spacetown appointment and Baley was absorbing the notion that he was to meet Spacers in the flesh. Somehow that was considerably different from speaking to them across miles of carrier wave, as he had done on several occasions before.\par
The Spacers in those pictures had been, generally speaking, like those that were occasionally featured in the book-films: tall, redheaded, grave, coldly handsome. Like R. Daneel Olivaw, for instance.\par
R. Daneel named the Spacers for Baley and when Baley suddenly pointed and said, in surprise, \ldblquote That isn\rquote t you, is it?\rdblquote  R. Daneel answered, \ldblquote No, Elijah, that is my designer, Dr. Sarton.\rdblquote\par
He said it unemotionally.\par
\ldblquote You were made in your maker\rquote s image?\rdblquote  asked Baley, sardonically, but there was no answer to that and, in truth, Baley scarcely expected one. The Bible, as he knew, circulated only to the most limited extent on the Outer Worlds.\par
And now Baley looked at Han Fastolfe, a man who deviated very noticeably from the Spacer norm in looks, and the Earthman felt a pronounced gratitude for that fact.\par
\ldblquote Won\rquote t you accept food?\rdblquote  asked Fastolfe.\par
He indicated the table that separated himself and R. Daneel from the Earthman. It bore nothing but a bowl of varicolored spheroids. Baley felt vaguely startled. He had taken them for table decorations.\par
R. Daneel explained. \ldblquote These are the fruits of natural plant life grown on Aurora. I suggest you try this kind. It is called an apple and is reputed to be pleasant.\rdblquote\par
Fastolfe smiled. \ldblquote R. Daneel does not know this by personal experience, of course, but he is quite right.\rdblquote\par
Baley brought an apple to his mouth. Its surface was red and green. It was cool to the touch and had a faint but pleasant odor. With an effort, he bit into it and the unexpected tartness of the pulpy contents hurt his teeth.\par
He chewed it gingerly. City dwellers ate natural food, of course, whenever rations allowed it. He himself had eaten natural meat and bread often. But such food had always been processed in some way. It had been cooked or ground, blended or compounded. Fruit, now, properly speaking, should come in the form of sauce or preserve. What he was holding now must have come straight from the dirt of a planet\rquote s soil.\par
He thought: I hope they\rquote ve washed it at least.\par
Again he wondered at the spottiness of Spacer notions concerning cleanliness.\par
Fastolfe said, \ldblquote Let me introduce myself a bit more specifically. I am in charge of the investigation of the murder of Dr. Sarton at the Spacetown end as Commissioner Enderby is at the City end. If I can help you in any way, I stand ready to do so. We are as eager for a quiet solution of the affair and prevention of future incidents of the sort as any of you City men can be.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Thank you, Dr. Fastolfe,\rdblquote  said Baley. \ldblquote Your attitude is appreciated.\rdblquote\par
So much, he thought, for the amenities. He bit into the center of the apple and hard, dark little ovoids popped into his mouth. He spat automatically. They flew out and fell to the ground. One would have struck Fastolfe\rquote s leg had not the Spacer moved it hastily.\par
Baley reddened, started to bend.\par
Fastolfe said, pleasantly, \ldblquote It is quite all right, Mr. Baley. Just leave them, please.\rdblquote\par
Baley straightened again. He put the apple down gingerly. He had the uncomfortable feeling that once he was gone, the lost little objects would be found and picked up by suction; the bowl of fruit would be burnt or discarded far from Spacetown; the very room they were sitting in would be sprayed with viricide.\par
He covered his embarrassment with brusqueness. He said, \ldblquote I would like to ask permission to have Commissioner Enderby join our conference by trimensional personification.\rdblquote\par
Fastolfe\rquote s eyebrows raised. \ldblquote Certainly, if you wish it. Daneel, would you make the connection?\rdblquote\par
Baley sat in stiff discomfort until the shiny surface of the large parallel piped in one corner of the room dissolved away to show Commissioner Julius Enderby and part of his desk. At that moment, the discomfort eased and Baley felt nothing short of love for that familiar figure, and a longing to be safely back in that office with him, or anywhere in the City, for that matter. Even in the least prepossessing portion of the Jersey yeast-vat districts.\par
Now that he had his witness, Baley saw no reason for delay. He said, \ldblquote I believe I have penetrated the mystery surrounding the death of Dr. Sarton.\rdblquote\par
Out of the corner of his eye, he saw Enderby springing to his feet and grabbing wildly (and successfully) at his flying spectacles. By standing, the Commissioner thrust his head out of the limits of the trimensic receiver and was forced to sit down again, red-faced and speechless.\par
In a much quieter way, Dr. Fastolfe, head inclined to one side, was as startled. Only R. Daneel was unmoved.\par
\ldblquote Do you mean,\rdblquote  said Fastolfe, \ldblquote that you know the murderer?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Baley, \ldblquote I mean there was no murder.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What!\rdblquote  screamed Enderby.\par
\ldblquote One moment, Commissioner Enderby,\rdblquote  said Fastolfe, raising a hand. His eyes held Baley\rquote s and he said, \ldblquote Do you mean that Dr. Sarton is alive?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, sir, and I believe I know where he is.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Where?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Right there,\rdblquote  said Baley, and pointed firmly at R. Daneel Olivaw.\par
