\pard\keepn\s2\sb240\sa240\qc\kerning0\i\fs28 DEBATE OVER A ROBOT\par
\pard\fi216\qj\b0\i0\f0\fs24 At the moment, Baley was most conscious of the thud of his own pulse. He seemed to be living in a moment of suspended time. R. Daneel\rquote s expression was, as always, empty of emotion. Han Fastolfe wore a look of well-bred astonishment on his face and nothing more. It was Commissioner Julius Enderby\rquote s reaction that most concerned Baley, however. The trimensic receiver out of which his face stared did not allow of perfect reproduction. There was always that tiny flicker and that not-quite-ideal resolution. Through that imperfection and through the further masking of the Commissioner\rquote s spectacles, Enderby\rquote s eyes were unreadable.\par
Baley thought: Don\rquote t go to pieces on me, Julius. I need you.\par
He didn\rquote t really think that Fastolfe would act in haste or under emotional impulse. He had read somewhere once that Spacers had no religion, but substituted, instead, a cold and phlegmatic intellectualism raised to the heights of a philosophy. He believed that and counted on it. They would make a point of acting slowly and then only on the basis of reason.\par
If he were alone among them and had said what he had said, he was certain that he would never have returned to the City. Cold reason would have dictated that. The Spacers\rquote  plans were worth more to them, many times over, than the life of a City dweller. There would be some excuse made to Julius Enderby. Maybe they would present his corpse to the Commissioner, shake their heads, and speak of an Earthman conspiracy having struck again. The Commissioner would believe them. It was the way he was built. If he hated Spacers, it was a hatred based on fear. He wouldn\rquote t dare disbelieve them.\par
That was why he had to be an actual witness of events, a witness, moreover, safely out of reach of the Spacers\rquote  calculated safety measures.\par
The Commissioner said, chokingly, \ldblquote Lije, you\rquote re all wrong. I saw Dr. Sarton\rquote s corpse.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You saw the charred remnants of something you were told was Dr. Sarton\rquote s corpse,\rdblquote  retorted Baley, boldly. He thought grimly of the Commissioner\rquote s broken glasses. That had been an unexpected favor for the Spacers.\par
\ldblquote No, no, Lije. I knew Dr. Sarton well and his head was undamaged. It was he.\rdblquote  The Commissioner put his hand to his glasses uneasily, as though he, too, remembered, and added, \ldblquote I looked at him closely, very closely.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote How about this one, Commissioner?\rdblquote  asked Baley, pointing to R. Daneel again. \ldblquote Doesn\rquote t he resemble Dr. Sarton?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, the way a statue would.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote An expressionless attitude can be assumed, Commissioner. Suppose that were a robot you had seen blasted to death. You say you looked closely. Did you look closely enough to see whether the charred surface at the edge of the blast was really decomposed organic tissue or a deliberately introduced layer of carbonization over fused metal.\rdblquote\par
The Commissioner looked revolted. He said, \ldblquote You\rquote re being ridiculous.\rdblquote\par
Baley turned to the Spacer. \ldblquote Are you willing to have the body exhumed for examination, Dr. Fastolfe?\rdblquote\par
Dr. Fastolfe smiled. \ldblquote Ordinarily, I would have no objection, Mr. Baley, but I\rquote m afraid we do not bury our dead. Cremation is a universal custom among us.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Very convenient,\rdblquote  said Baley.\par
\ldblquote Tell me, Mr. Baley,\rdblquote  said Dr. Fastolfe, \ldblquote just how did you arrive at this very extraordinary conclusion of yours?\rdblquote\par
Baley thought: He isn\rquote t giving up. He\rquote ll brazen it out, if he can. He said, \ldblquote It wasn\rquote t difficult. There\rquote s more to imitating a robot than just putting on a frozen expression and adopting a stilted style of conversation. The trouble with you men of the Outer Worlds is that you\rquote re too used to robots. You\rquote ve gotten to accept them almost as human beings. You\rquote ve grown blind to the differences. On Earth, it\rquote s different. We\rquote re very conscious of what a robot is.\par
\ldblquote Now in the first place, R. Daneel is too good a human to be a robot. My first impression of him was that he was a Spacer. It was quite an effort for me to adjust myself to his statement that he was a robot. And of course, the reason for that was that he was a Spacer and wasn\rquote t a robot.\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel interrupted, without any sign of self-consciousness at being himself so intimately the topic of debate. He said, \ldblquote As I told you, partner Elijah, I was designed to take a temporary place in a human society. The resemblance to humanity is purposeful.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Even,\rdblquote  asked Baley, \ldblquote down to the painstaking duplication of those portions of the body which, in the ordinary course of events, would always be covered by clothes? Even to the duplication of organs which, in a robot, would have no conceivable function?\rdblquote\par
Enderby said suddenly, \ldblquote How did you find that out?\rdblquote\par
Baley reddened. \ldblquote I couldn\rquote t help noticing in the--in the Personal.\rdblquote\par
Enderby looked shocked.\par
Fastolfe said, \ldblquote Surely you understand that a resemblance must be complete if it is to be useful. For our purposes, half measures are as bad as nothing at all.\rdblquote\par
Baley asked abruptly, \ldblquote May I smoke?\rdblquote\par
Three pipefuls in one day was a ridiculous extravagance, but he was riding a rolling torrent of recklessness and needed the release of tobacco. After all, he was talking back to Spacers. He was going to force their lies down their own throats.\par
Fastolfe said, \ldblquote I\rquote m sorry, but I\rquote d prefer that you didn\rquote t.\rdblquote\par
It was a \ldblquote preference\rdblquote  that had the force of a command. Baley felt that. He thrust back the pipe, the bowl of which he had already taken into his hand in anticipation of automatic permission.\par
Of course not, he thought bitterly. Enderby didn\rquote t warn me, because he doesn\rquote t smoke himself, but it\rquote s obvious. It follows. They don\rquote t smoke on their hygienic Outer Worlds, or drink, or have any human vices. No wonder they accept robots in their damned--what did R. Daneel call it?--C/Fe society? No wonder R. Daneel can play the robot as well as he does. They\rquote re all robots out there to begin with.\par
He said, \ldblquote The too complete resemblance is just one point out of a number. There was a near riot in my section as I was taking him home.\rdblquote  (He had to point. He could not bring himself to say either R. Daneel or Dr. Sarton.) \ldblquote It was he that stopped the trouble and he did it by pointing a blaster at the potential rioters.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Good Lord,\rdblquote  said Enderby, energetically, \ldblquote the report stated that it was you--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I know, Commissioner,\rdblquote  said Baley. \ldblquote The report was based on information that I gave. I didn\rquote t want to have it on the record that a robot had threatened to blast men and women.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, no. Of course not.\rdblquote  Enderby was quite obviously horrified. He leaned forward to look at something that was out of the range of the trimensic receiver.\par
Baley could guess what it was. The Commissioner was checking the power gauge to see if the transmitter were being tapped.\par
\ldblquote Is that a point in your argument?\rdblquote  asked Fastolfe.\par
\ldblquote It certainly is. The First Law of Robotics states that a robot cannot harm a human being.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But R. Daneel did no harm.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote True. He even stated afterward that he wouldn\rquote t have fired under any circumstances. Still, no robot I ever heard of could have violated the spirit of the First Law to the extent of threatening to blast a man, even if he really had no intention to do so.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I see. Are you a robotics expert, Mr. Baley?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, sir. But I\rquote ve had a course in general robotics and in positronic analysis. I\rquote m not completely ignorant.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s nice,\rdblquote  said Fastolfe, agreeably, \ldblquote but you see, I am a robotics expert, and I assure you that the essence of the robot mind lies in a completely literal interpretation of the universe. It recognizes no spirit in the First Law, only the letter. The simple models you have on Earth may have their First Law so overlaid with additional safeguards that, to be sure, they may well be incapable of threatening a human. An advanced model such as R. Daneel is another matter. If I gather the situation correctly, Daneel\rquote s threat was necessary to prevent a riot. It was intended then to prevent harm to human beings. He was obeying the First Law, not defying it.\rdblquote\par
Baley squirmed inwardly, but maintained a tight external calm. It would go hard, but he would match this Spacer at his own game.\par
He said, \ldblquote You may counter each point separately, but they add up just the same. Last evening in our discussion of the so-called murder, this alleged robot claimed that he had been converted into a detective by the installation of a new drive into his positronic circuits. A drive, if you please, for justice.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll vouch for that,\rdblquote  said Fastolfe. \ldblquote It was done to him three days ago under my own supervision.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote A drive for justice? Justice, Dr. Fastolfe, is an abstraction. Only a human being can use the term.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote If you define \lquote justice\rquote  in such a way that it is an abstraction, if you say that it is the rendering of each man his due, that it is adhering to the right, or anything of the sort, I grant you your argument, Mr. Baley. A human understanding of abstractions cannot be built into a positronic brain in the present state of our knowledge.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You admit that, then--as an expert in robotics?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Certainly. The question is, what did R. Daneel mean by using the term \lquote justice\rquote ?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote From the context of our conversation, he meant what you and I and any human being would mean, but what no robot could mean.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why don\rquote t you ask him, Mr. Baley, to define the term?\rdblquote\par
Baley felt a certain loss of confidence. He turned to R. Daneel. \ldblquote Well?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, Elijah?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What is your definition of justice?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Justice, Elijah, is that which exists when all the laws are enforced.\rdblquote\par
Fastolfe nodded. \ldblquote A good definition, Mr. Baley, for a robot. The desire to see all laws enforced has been built into R. Daneel, now. Justice is a very concrete term to him since it is based on law enforcement, which is in turn based upon the existence of specific and definite laws. There is nothing abstract about it. A human being can recognize the fact that, on the basis of an abstract moral code, some laws may be bad ones and their enforcement unjust. What do you say, R. Daneel?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote An unjust law,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel evenly, \ldblquote is a contradiction in terms.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote To a robot it is, Mr. Baley. So you see, you mustn\rquote t confuse your justice and R. Daneel\rquote s.\rdblquote\par
Baley turned to R. Daneel sharply and said, \ldblquote You left my apartment last night.\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel replied, \ldblquote I did. If my leaving disturbed your sleep, I am sorry.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Where did you go?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote To the Men\rquote s Personal.\rdblquote\par
For a moment, Baley was staggered. It was the answer he had already decided was the truth, but he had not expected it to be the answer R. Daneel would give. He felt a little more of his certainty oozing away, yet he held firmly on his track. The Commissioner was watching, his lensed eyes flicking from one to the other as they spoke. Baley couldn\rquote t back down now, no matter what sophistries they used against him. He had to hold to his point.\par
He said, \ldblquote On reaching my section, he insisted on entering Personal with me. His excuse was a poor one. During the night, he left to visit Personal again as he has just admitted. If he were a man, I\rquote d say he had every reason and right to do so. Obviously. As a robot, however, the trip was meaningless. The conclusion can only be that he is a man.\rdblquote\par
Fastolfe nodded. He seemed not in the least put out. He said, \ldblquote This is most interesting. Suppose we ask Daneel why he made his trip to Personal last night.\rdblquote\par
Commissioner Enderby leaned forward. \ldblquote Please, Dr. Fastolfe,\rdblquote  he muttered, \ldblquote it is not proper to--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You need not be concerned, Commissioner,\rdblquote  said Fastolfe, his thin lips curving back in something that looked like a smile but wasn\rquote t, \ldblquote I am certain that Daneel\rquote s answer will not offend your sensibilities or those of Mr. Baley. Won\rquote t you tell us, Daneel?\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel said, \ldblquote Elijah\rquote s wife, Jessie, left the apartment last night on friendly terms with me. It was quite obvious that she had no reason for thinking me to be other than human. She returned to the apartment knowing I was a robot. The obvious conclusion is that the information to that effect exists outside the apartment. It followed that my conversation with Elijah last night had been overheard. In no other way could the secret of my true nature have become common knowledge.\par
\ldblquote Elijah told me that the apartments were well insulated. We spoke together in low voices. Ordinary eavesdropping would not do. Still, it was known that Elijah is a policeman. If a conspiracy exists within the City sufficiently well organized to have planned the murder of Dr. Sarton, they may well have been aware that Elijah had been placed in charge of the murder investigation. It would fall within the realm of possibility then, even of probability, that his apartment had been spybeamed.\par
\ldblquote I searched the apartment as well as I could after Elijah and Jessie had gone to bed, but could find no transmitter. This complicated matters. A focused duo-beam could do the trick even in the absence of a transmitter, but that requires rather elaborate equipment.\par
\ldblquote Analysis of the situation led to the following conclusion. The one place where a City dweller can do almost anything without being disturbed or questioned is in the Personals. He could even set up a duo-beam. The custom of absolute privacy in the Personals is very strong and other men would not even look at him. The Section Personal is quite close to Elijah\rquote s apartment, so that the distance factor is not important. A suitcase model could be used. I went to the Personal to investigate.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And what did you find?\rdblquote  asked Baley quickly.\par
\ldblquote Nothing, Elijah. No sign of a duo-beam.\rdblquote\par
Dr. Fastolfe said, \ldblquote Well, Mr. Baley, does this sound reasonable to you?\rdblquote\par
But Baley\rquote s uncertainty was gone, now. He said, \ldblquote Reasonable as far as it goes, perhaps, but it stops short of perfection by a hell of a way. What he doesn\rquote t know is that my wife told me where she got the information and when. She learned he was a robot shortly after she left the house. Even then, the rumor had been circulating for hours. So the fact that he was a robot could not have leaked out through spying on our last evening\rquote s conversation.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Nevertheless,\rdblquote  said Dr. Fastolfe, \ldblquote his action last night of going to the Personal stands explained, I think.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But something is brought up that is not explained,\rdblquote  retorted Baley, heatedly. \ldblquote When, where, and how was the leak? How did the news get about that there was a Spacer robot in the City? As far as I know, only two of us knew about the deal, Commissioner Enderby and myself, and we told no one. --Commissioner, did anyone else in the Department know?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said Enderby, anxiously. \ldblquote Not even the Mayor. Only we, and Dr. Fastolfe.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And he,\rdblquote  added Baley, pointing.\par
\ldblquote I?\rdblquote  asked R. Daneel.\par
\ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I was with you at all times, Elijah.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You were not,\rdblquote  cried Baley, fiercely. \ldblquote I was in Personal for half an hour or more before we went to my apartment. During that time, we two were completely out of contact with one another. It was then that you got in touch with your group in the City.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What group?\rdblquote  asked Fastolfe.\par
And \ldblquote What group?\rdblquote  echoed Commissioner Enderby almost simultaneously.\par
Baley rose from his chair and turned to the trimensic receiver. \ldblquote Commissioner, I want you to listen closely to this. Tell me if it doesn\rquote t all fall into a pattern. A murder is reported and by a curious coincidence it happens just as you are entering Spacetown to keep an appointment with the murdered man. You are shown the corpse of something supposed to be human, but the corpse has since been disposed of and is not available for close examination.\par
\ldblquote The Spacers insist an Earthman did the killing, even though the only way they can make such an accusation stick is to suppose that a City man had left the City and cut cross country to Spacetown alone and at night. You know damn well how unlikely that is.\par
\ldblquote Next they send a supposed robot into the City; in fact, they insist on sending him. The first thing the robot does is to threaten a crowd of human beings with a blaster. The second is to set in motion the rumor that there is a Spacer robot in the City. In fact, the rumor is so specific that Jessie told me it was known that he was working with the police. That means that before long it will be known that it was the robot who handled the blaster. Maybe even now the rumor is spreading across the yeast-vat country and down the Long Island hydroponic plants that there\rquote s a killer robot on the loose.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote This is impossible. Impossible!\rdblquote  groaned Enderby.\par
\ldblquote No, it isn\rquote t. It\rquote s exactly what\rquote s happening, Commissioner. Don\rquote t you see it? There\rquote s a conspiracy in the City, all right, but it\rquote s run from Spacetown. The Spacers want to be able to report a murder. They want riots. They want an assault on Spacetown. The worse things get, the better the incident--and Spacer ships come down and occupy the Cities of Earth.\rdblquote\par
Fastolfe said, mildly, \ldblquote We had an excuse in the Barrier Riots of twenty-five years ago.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You weren\rquote t ready then. You are now.\rdblquote  Baley\rquote s heart was pounding madly.\par
\ldblquote This is quite a complicated plot you\rquote re attributing to us, Mr. Baley. If we wanted to occupy Earth, we could do so in much simpler fashion.\par
\ldblquote Maybe not, Dr. Fastolfe. Your so-called robot told me that public opinion concerning Earth is by no means unified on your Outer Worlds. I think he was telling the truth at that time, anyway. Maybe an outright occupation wouldn\rquote t sit well with the people at home. Maybe an incident is an absolute necessity. A good shocking incident.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Like a murder, eh? Is that it? You\rquote ll admit it would have to be a pretended murder. You won\rquote t suggest, I hope, that we\rquote d really kill one of ourselves for the sake of an incident.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You built a robot to look like Dr. Sarton, blasted the robot, and showed the remains to Commissioner Enderby.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And then,\rdblquote  said Dr. Fastolfe, \ldblquote having used R. Daneel to impersonate Dr. Sarton in the false murder, we have to use Dr. Sarton to impersonate R. Daneel in the false investigation of the false murder.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Exactly. I am telling you this in the presence of a witness who is not here in the flesh and whom you cannot blast out of existence and who is important enough to be believed by the City government and by Washington itself. We will be prepared for you and we know what your intentions are. If necessary, our government will report directly to your people, expose the situation for exactly what it is. I doubt if this sort of interstellar rape will be tolerated.\rdblquote\par
Fastolfe shook his head. \ldblquote Please, Mr. Baley, you are being unreasonable. Really, you have the most astonishing notions. Suppose now, just quietly suppose, that R. Daneel is really R. Daneel. Suppose he is actually a robot. Wouldn\rquote t it follow that the corpse Commissioner Enderby saw was really Dr. Sarton? It would be scarcely reasonable to believe that the corpse were still another robot. Commissioner Enderby witnessed R. Daneel under construction and can vouch for the fact that only one existed.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote If it comes to that,\rdblquote  said Baley, stubbornly, \ldblquote the Commissioner is not a robotics expert. You might have had a dozen such robots.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Stick to the point, Mr. Baley. What if R. Daneel is really R. Daneel? Would not the entire structure of your reasoning fall to the ground? Would you have any further basis for your belief in this completely melodramatic and implausible interstellar plot you have constructed?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote If he is a robot! I say he is human.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yet you haven\rquote t really investigated the problem, Mr. Baley,\rdblquote  said Fastolfe. \ldblquote To differentiate a robot, even a very humanoid robot, from a human being, it isn\rquote t necessary to make elaborately shaky deductions from little things he says and does. For instance, have you tried sticking a pin into R. Daneel?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote  Baley\rquote s mouth fell open.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s a simple experiment. There are others perhaps not quite so simple. His skin and hair look real, but have you tried looking at them under adequate magnification. Then again, he seems to breathe, particularly when he is using air to talk, but have you noticed that his breathing is irregular, that minutes may go by during which he has no breath at all. You might even have trapped some of his expired air and measured the carbon dioxide content. You might have tried to draw a sample of blood. You might have tried to detect a pulse in his wrist, or a heartbeat under his shirt. Do you see what I mean, Mr. Baley?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s just talk,\rdblquote  said Baley, uneasily. \ldblquote I\rquote m not going to be bluffed. I might have tried any of those things, but do you suppose this alleged robot would have let me bring a hypodermic to him, or a stethoscope or a microscope?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Of course. I see your point,\rdblquote  said Fastolfe. He looked at R. Daneel and gestured slightly.\par
R. Daneel touched the cuff of his right shirt sleeve and the diamagnetic seam fell apart the entire length of his arm. A smooth, sinewy, and apparently entirely human limb lay exposed. Its short, bronze hairs, both in quantity and distribution, were exactly what one would expect of a human being.\par
Baley said, \ldblquote So?\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel pinched the ball of his right middle finger with the thumb and forefinger of his left hand. Exactly what the details of the manipulation that followed were, Baley could not see.\par
But, just as the fabric of the sleeve had fallen in two when the diamagnetic field of its seam had been interrupted, so now the arm itself fell in two.\par
There, under a thin layer of fleshlike material, was the dull blue gray of stainless steel rods, cords, and joints.\par
\ldblquote Would you care to examine Daneel\rquote s workings more closely, Mr. Baley?\rdblquote  asked Dr. Fastolfe politely.\par
Baley could scarcely hear the remark for the buzzing in his ears and for the sudden jarring of the Commissioner\rquote s high-pitched and hysterical laughter.\par
