\pard\keepn\s2\sb240\sa240\qc\kerning0\i\fs28 ELUCIDATION BY A SPACER\par
\pard\fi216\qj\b0\i0\f0\fs24 The minutes passed and the buzzing grew louder and drowned out the laughter. The dome and all it contained wavered and Baley\rquote s time sense wavered, too.\par
At least, he found himself sitting in an unchanged position but with a definite feeling of lost time. The Commissioner was gone; the trimensic receiver was milky and opaque; and R. Daneel sat at his side, pinching up the skin of Baley\rquote s bared upper arm. Baley could see, just beneath the skin, the small thin darkness of a hypo-sliver. It vanished as he watched, soaking and spreading away into the intercellular fluid, from that into the blood stream and the neighboring cells, from that into all the cells of his body.\par
His grip on reality heightened.\par
\ldblquote Do you feel better, partner Elijah?\rdblquote  asked R. Daneel.\par
Baley did. He pulled at his arm and the robot let him take it away. He rolled down his sleeve and looked about. Dr. Fastolfe sat where he had been, a small smile softening the homeliness of his face.\par
Baley said, \ldblquote Did I black out?\rdblquote\par
Dr. Fastolfe said, \ldblquote In a way, yes. You received a sizable shock, I\rquote m afraid.\rdblquote\par
It came back to Baley quite clearly. He seized R. Daneel\rquote s nearer arm quickly, forcing up the sleeve as far as it would go, exposing the wrist. The robot\rquote s flesh felt soft to his fingers, but underneath was the hardness of something more than bone.\par
R. Daneel let his arm rest easily in the plain-clothes man\rquote s grip. Baley stared at it, pinching the skin along the median line. Was there a faint seam?\par
It was logical, of course, that there should be. A robot, covered with synthetic skin, and deliberately made to look human, could not be repaired in the ordinary fashion. A chest plate could not be unriveted for the purpose. A skull could not be hinged up and outward. Instead, the various parts of the mechanical body would have to be put together along a line of micromagnetic fields. An arm, a head, an entire body, must fall in two at the proper touch, then come together again at a contrary touch.\par
Baley looked up. \ldblquote Where\rquote s the Commissioner?\rdblquote  he mumbled, hot with mortification.\par
\ldblquote Pressing business,\rdblquote  said Dr. Fastolfe. \ldblquote I encouraged him to leave, I\rquote m afraid. I assured him we would take care of you.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You\rquote ve taken care of me quite nicely already, thank you,\rdblquote  said Baley, grimly. \ldblquote I think our business is done.\rdblquote\par
He lifted himself erect on tired joints. He felt an old man, very suddenly. Too old to start over again. He needed no deep insight to foresee that future.\par
The Commissioner would be half frightened and half furious. He would face Baley whitely, taking his glasses off to wipe them every fifteen seconds. His soft voice (Julius Enderby almost never shouted) would explain carefully that the Spacers had been mortally offended.\par
\ldblquote You can\rquote t talk to Spacers that way, Lije. They won\rquote t take it.\rdblquote  (Baley could hear Enderby\rquote s voice very plainly down to the finest shade of intonation.) \ldblquote I warned you. No saying how much damage you\rquote ve done. I can see your point, mind you. I see what you were trying to do. If they were Earthmen, it would be different. I\rquote d say yes, chance it. Run the risk. Smoke them out. But Spacers! You might have told me, Lije. You might have consulted me. I know them. I know them inside and out.\rdblquote\par
And what would Baley be able to say? That Enderby was exactly the man he couldn\rquote t tell. That the project was one of tremendous risk and Enderby a man of tremendous caution. That it had been Enderby himself who had pointed up the supreme dangers of either outright failure or of the wrong kind of success. That the one way of defeating declassification was to show that guilt lay in Spacetown itself ...\par
Enderby would say, \ldblquote There\rquote ll have to be a report on this, Lije. There\rquote ll be all sorts of repercussions. I know the Spacers. They\rquote ll demand your removal from the case, and it\rquote ll have to be that way. You understand that, Lije, don\rquote t you? I\rquote ll try to make it easy on you. You can count on that. I\rquote ll protect you as far as I can, Lije.\rdblquote\par
Baley knew that would be exactly true. The Commissioner would protect him, but only as far as he could, not to the point, for instance, of infuriating further an angry Mayor.\par
He could hear the Mayor, too. \ldblquote Damn it, Enderby, what is all this? Why wasn\rquote t I consulted? Who\rquote s running the City? Why was an unauthorized robot allowed inside the City? And just what the devil did this Baley ...\rdblquote\par
If it came to a choice between Baley\rquote s future in the Department and the Commissioner\rquote s own, what possible result could Baley expect? He could find no reasonable way of blaming Enderby.\par
The least he could expect was demotion, and that was bad enough. The mere act of living in a modern City insured the bare possibility of existence, even for those entirely declassified. How bare that possibility was he knew only too well.\par
It was the addition of status that brought the little things: a more comfortable seat here, a better cut of meat there, a shorter wait in line at the other place. To the philosophical mind, these items might seem scarcely worth any great trouble to acquire.\par
Yet no one, however philosophical, could give up those privileges, once acquired, without a pang. That was the point.\par
What a trifling addition to the convenience of the apartment an activated washbasin was when for thirty years previously the trip to Personal had been an automatic and unregarded one. How useless it was even as a device to prove \ldblquote status\rdblquote  when it was considered the height of ill form to parade \ldblquote status.\rdblquote  Yet were the washbasin to be deactivated, how humiliating and unbearable would each added trip to Personal be! How yearningly attractive the memory of the bedroom shave! How filled with a sense of lost luxury!\par
It was fashionable for modern political writers to look back with a smug disapproval at the \ldblquote fiscalism\rdblquote  of Medieval times, when economy was based on money. The competitive struggle for existence, they said, was brutal. No truly complex society could be maintained because of the strains introduced by the eternal \ldblquote fight-for-the-buck.\rdblquote  (Scholars had varying interpretations of the word \ldblquote buck,\rdblquote  but there was no dispute over the meaning as a whole.)\par
By contrast, modern \ldblquote civism\rdblquote  was praised highly as efficient and enlightened.\par
Maybe so. There were historical novels both in the romantic and the sensational tradition, and the Medievalists thought \ldblquote fiscalism\rdblquote  had bred such things as individualism and initiative.\par
Baley wouldn\rquote t commit himself, but now he wondered sickly if ever a man fought harder for that buck, whatever it was, or felt its loss more deeply, than a City dweller fought to keep from losing his Sunday night option on a chicken drumstick--a real-flesh drumstick from a once-living bird.\par
Baley thought: Not me so much. There\rquote s Jessie and Ben.\par
Dr. Fastolfe\rquote s voice broke in upon his thoughts. \ldblquote Mr. Baley, do you hear me?\rdblquote\par
Baley blinked. \ldblquote Yes?\rdblquote  How long had he been standing there like a frozen fool?\par
\ldblquote Won\rquote t you sit down, sir? Having taken care of the matter on your mind, you may now be interested in some films we have taken of the scene of the crime and of the events immediately following.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, thank you. I have business in the City.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Surely the case of Dr. Sarton comes first.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Not with me. I imagine I\rquote m off the case already.\rdblquote  Suddenly, he boiled over. \ldblquote Damn it, if you could prove R. Daneel was a robot, why didn\rquote t you do it at once? Why did you make such a farce of it all?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote My dear Mr. Baley, I was very interested in your deductions. As for being off the case, I doubt it. Before the Commissioner left, I made a special point of asking that you be retained. I believe he will co-operate.\rdblquote\par
Baley sat down, not entirely voluntarily. He said, sharply, \ldblquote Why?\rdblquote  Dr. Fastolfe crossed his legs and sighed. \ldblquote Mr. Baley, in general I have met two kinds of City dwellers, rioters and politicians. Your Commissioner is useful to us, but he is a politician. He tells us what we want to hear. He handles us, if you know what I mean. Now you came here and boldly accused us of tremendous crimes and tried to prove your case. I enjoyed the process. I found it a hopeful development.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote How hopeful?\rdblquote  asked Baley sardonically.\par
\ldblquote Hopeful enough. You are someone I can deal with frankly. Last night, Mr. Baley, R. Daneel reported to me by shielded subether. Some things about you interested me very much. For instance, there was the point concerning the nature of the book-films in your apartment.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What about them?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote A good many dealt with historical and archaeological subjects. It makes it appear that you are interested in human society and that you know a little about its evolution.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Even policemen can spend their free time on book-films, if they so choose.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Quite. I\rquote m glad of your choice in viewing matter. It will help me in what I am trying to do. In the first place, I want to explain, or try to, the exclusivism of the men of the Outer Worlds. We live here in Spacetown; we don\rquote t enter the City; we mingle with you City dwellers only in a very rigidly limited fashion. We breathe the open air, but when we do, we wear filters. I sit here now with filters in my nostrils, gloves on my hands, and a fixed determination to come no closer to you than I can help. Why do you suppose that is?\rdblquote\par
Baley said, \ldblquote There\rquote s no point in guessing.\rdblquote  Let him talk now.\par
\ldblquote If you guessed as some of your people do, you would say that it was because we despised the men of Earth and refused to lose caste by allowing their shadow to fall upon us. That is not so. The true answer is really quite obvious. The medical examination you went through, as well as the cleansing procedures, were not matters of ritual. They were dictated by necessity.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Disease?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, disease. My dear Mr. Baley, the Earthmen who colonized the Outer Worlds found themselves on planets entirely free of Terrestrial bacteria and viruses. They brought in their own, of course, but they also brought with them the latest medical and microbiological techniques. They had a small community of micro-organisms to deal with and no intermediate hosts. There were no mosquitoes to spread malaria, no snails to spread schistosomiasis. Disease agents were wiped out and symbiotic bacteria allowed to grow. Gradually, the Outer Worlds became disease-free. Naturally, as time went on, entrance requirements for immigrant Earthmen were made more and more rigorous, since less and less could the Outer Worlds endure the possible introduction of disease.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You\rquote ve never been sick, Dr. Fastolfe?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Not with a parasitic disease, Mr. Baley. We are all liable to degenerative diseases such as atheroschlerosis, of course, but I have never had what you would call a cold. If I were to contract one, I might die of it. I\rquote ve built up no resistance to it whatsoever. That\rquote s what\rquote s wrong with us here in Spacetown. Those of us who come here run a definite risk. Earth is riddled with diseases to which we have no defense, no natural defense. You yourself are carrying the germs of almost every known disease. You are not aware of it, since you keep them all under control at almost all times through the antibodies your body has developed over the years. I, myself, lack the antibodies. Do you wonder that I come no closer to you? Believe me, Mr. Baley, I act aloof only in self-defense.\rdblquote\par
Baley said, \ldblquote If this is so, why isn\rquote t the fact made known on Earth? I mean, that it is not just queasiness on your part, but a defense against an actual physical danger.\rdblquote\par
The Spacer shook his head. \ldblquote We are few, Mr. Baley, and are disliked as foreigners anyway. We maintain our own safety on the basis of a rather shaky prestige as a superior class of being. We cannot afford to lose face by admitting that we are afraid to approach an Earthman. Not at least until there is a better understanding between Earthmen and Spacers.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote There won\rquote t be, on present terms. It\rquote s your supposed superiority that we--they hate you for.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It is a dilemma. Don\rquote t think we aren\rquote t aware of it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Does the Commissioner know of this?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We have never explained it to him flatly, as I have just done to you. He may guess it, however. He is quite an intelligent man.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote If he guessed it, he might have told me,\rdblquote  Baley said reflectively.\par
Dr. Fastolfe lifted his eyebrows. \ldblquote If he had, then you wouldn\rquote t have considered the possibility of R. Daneel being a human Spacer. Is that it?\rdblquote\par
Baley shrugged slightly, tossing the matter to one side.\par
But Dr. Fastolfe went on, \ldblquote That\rquote s quite true, you know. Putting the psychological difficulties to one side, the terrible effect of the noise and crowds upon us, the fact remains that for one of us to enter the City is the equivalent of a death sentence. It is why Dr. Sarton initiated his project of humanoid robots. They were substitute men, designed to enter the City instead of us--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes. R. Daneel explained this to me.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Do you disapprove?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Look,\rdblquote  said Baley, \ldblquote since we\rquote re talking to one another so freely, let me ask a question in simple words. Why have you Spacers come to Earth anyway? Why don\rquote t you leave us alone?\rdblquote\par
Dr. Fastolfe said, with obvious surprise, \ldblquote Are you satisfied with life on Earth?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We get along.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, but for how long will that continue? Your population goes up continuously; the available calories meet the needs only as a result of greater and greater effort. Earth is in a blind alley, man.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We get along,\rdblquote  repeated Baley stubbornly.\par
\ldblquote Barely. A City like New York must spend every ounce of effort getting water in and waste out. The nuclear power plants are kept going by uranium supplies that are constantly more difficult to obtain even from the other planets of the system, and the supply needed goes up steadily. The life of the City depends every moment on the arrival of wood pulp for the yeast vats and minerals for the hydroponic plants. Air must be circulated unceasingly. The balance is a very delicate one in a hundred directions, and growing more delicate each year. What would happen to New York if the tremendous flow of input and outgo were to be interrupted for even a single hour?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It never has been.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Which is no security for the future. In primitive times, individual population centers were virtually self-supporting, living on the produce of neighboring farms. Nothing but immediate disaster, a flood or a pestilence or crop failure, could harm them. As the centers grew and technology improved, localized disasters could be overcome by drawing on help from distant centers, but at the cost of making ever larger areas interdependent. In Medieval times, the open cities, even the largest, could subsist on food stores and on emergency supplies of all sorts for a week at least. When New York first became a City, it could have lived on itself for a day. Now it cannot do so for an hour. A disaster that would have been uncomfortable ten thousand years ago, merely serious a thousand years ago, and acute a hundred years ago would now be surely fatal.\rdblquote\par
Baley moved restlessly in his chair. \ldblquote I\rquote ve heard all this before. The Medievalists want an end to Cities. They want us to get back to the soil and to natural agriculture. Well, they\rquote re mad; we can\rquote t. There are too many of us and you can\rquote t go backward in history, only forward. Of course, if emigration to the Outer Worlds were not restricted--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You know why it must be restricted.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Then what is there to do? You\rquote re tapping a dead power line.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What about emigration to new worlds? There are a hundred billion stars in the Galaxy. It is estimated that there are a hundred million planets that are inhabitable or can be made inhabitable.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s ridiculous.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why?\rdblquote  asked Dr. Fastolfe, with vehemence. \ldblquote Why is the suggestion ridiculous? Earthmen have colonized planets in the past. Over thirty of the fifty Outer Worlds, including my native Aurora, were directly colonized by Earthmen. Is colonization no longer possible?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well ...\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No answer? Let me suggest that if it is no longer possible, it is because of the development of City culture on Earth. Before the Cities, human life on Earth wasn\rquote t so specialized that they couldn\rquote t break loose and start all over on a raw world. They did it thirty times. But now, Earthmen are all so coddled, so enwombed in their imprisoning caves of steel, that they are caught forever. You, Mr. Baley, won\rquote t even believe that a City dweller is capable of crossing country to get to Spacetown. Crossing space to get to a new world must represent impossibility squared to you. Civism is ruining Earth, sir.\rdblquote\par
Baley said angrily, \ldblquote And if it does? How does it concern you people? It\rquote s our problem. We\rquote ll solve it. If not, it\rquote s our own particular road to hell.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Better your own road to hell than another\rquote s road to heaven, eh? I know how you must feel. It is not pleasant to listen to the preaching of a stranger. Yet I wish your people could preach to us, for we, too, have a problem, one that is quite analogous to yours.\rdblquote\par
Baley smiled crookedly. \ldblquote Overpopulation?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Analogous, not identical. Ours is underpopulation. How old would you say I was?\rdblquote\par
The Earthman considered for a moment and then deliberately overestimated. \ldblquote Sixty, I\rquote d say.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote A hundred and sixty, you should say.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote A hundred and sixty-three next birthday, to be exact. There\rquote s no trick to that. I\rquote m using the Standard Earth year as the unit. If I\rquote m fortunate, if I take care of myself, most of all, if I catch no disease on Earth, I may double that age. Men on Aurora have been known to live over three hundred and fifty years. And life expectancy is still increasing.\rdblquote\par
Baley looked to R. Daneel (who throughout the conversation had been listening in stolid silence), as though he were seeking confirmation.\par
He said, \ldblquote How is that possible?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote In an underpopulated society, it is practical to concentrate study on gerontology, to do research on the aging process. In a world such as yours, a lengthened life expectancy would be disastrous. You couldn\rquote t afford the resulting rise in population. On Aurora, there is room for tricentenarians. Then, of course, a long life becomes doubly and triply precious.\par
\ldblquote If you were to die now, you would lose perhaps forty years of your life, probably less. If I were to die, I would lose a hundred fifty years, probably more. In a culture such as ours, then, individual life is of prime importance. Our birth rate is low and population increase is rigidly controlled. We maintain a definite robot/man ratio designed to maintain the individual in the greatest comfort. Logically, developing children are carefully screened for physical and mental defects before being allowed to mature.\rdblquote\par
Baley interrupted. \ldblquote You mean you kill them if they don\rquote t--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote If they don\rquote t measure up. Quite painlessly, I assure you. The notion shocks you, just as the Earthman\rquote s uncontrolled breeding shocks us.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We\rquote re controlled, Dr. Fastolfe. Each family is allowed so many children.\rdblquote\par
Dr. Fastolfe smiled tolerantly. \ldblquote So many of any kind of children; not so many healthy children. And even so, there are many illegitimates and your population increases.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Who\rquote s to judge which children should live?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s rather complicated and not to be answered in a sentence. Some day we may talk it out in detail.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, where\rquote s your problem? You sound satisfied with your society.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It is stable. That\rquote s the trouble. It is too stable.\rdblquote\par
Baley said, \ldblquote Nothing pleases you. Our civilization is at the ragged edge of chaos, according to you, and your own is too stable.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It is possible to be too stable. No Outer World has colonized a new planet in two and a half centuries. There is no prospect for colonization in the future. Our lives in the Outer Worlds are too long to risk and too comfortable to upset.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t know about that, Dr. Fastolfe. You\rquote ve come to Earth. You risk disease.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, I do. There are some of us, Mr. Baley, who feel that the future of the human race is even worth the possible loss of an extended lifetime. Too few of us, I am sorry to say.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All right. We\rquote re coming to the point. How is Spacetown helping matters?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote In trying to introduce robots here on Earth, we\rquote re doing our best to upset the balance of your City economy.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s your way of helping?\rdblquote  Baley\rquote s lips quivered. \ldblquote You mean you\rquote re creating a growing group of displaced and declassified men on purpose?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Not out of cruelty or callousness, believe me. A group of displaced men, as you call them, are what we need to serve as a nucleus for colonization. Your ancient America was discovered by ships fitted out with men from the prisons. Don\rquote t you see that the City\rquote s womb has failed the displaced man. He has nothing to lose and worlds to gain by leaving Earth.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But it isn\rquote t working.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, it isn\rquote t,\rdblquote  said Dr. Fastolfe, sadly. \ldblquote There is something wrong. The resentment of the Earthman for the robot blocks things. Yet those very robots can accompany humans, smooth the difficulties of initial adjustment to a raw world, make colonization practical.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Then what? More Outer Worlds?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No. The Outer Worlds were established before Civism had spread over Earth, before the Cities. The new colonies will be built by humans who have the City background plus the beginnings of a C/Fe culture. It will be a synthesis, a crossbreeding. As it stands now, Earth\rquote s own structure must go ricketing down in the near future, the Outer Worlds will slowly degenerate and decay in a somewhat further future, but the new colonies will be a new and healthy strain, combining the best of both cultures. By their reaction upon the older worlds, including Earth, we ourselves may gain new life.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t know. It\rquote s all misty, Dr. Fastolfe.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s a dream, yes. Think about it.\rdblquote  Abruptly the Spacer rose to his feet. \ldblquote I have spent more time with you than I intended. In fact, more time than our health ordinances allow. You will excuse me?\rdblquote\par
Baley and R. Daneel left the dome. Sunlight, at a different angle, somewhat yellower, washed down upon them once again. In Baley, there was a vague wonder whether sunlight might not seem different on another world. Less harsh and brazen perhaps. More acceptable. Another world? The ugly Spacer with the prominent ears had filled his mind with queer imaginings. Did the doctors of Aurora once look at the child Fastolfe and wonder if he ought to be allowed to mature? Wasn\rquote t he too ugly? Or did their criteria include physical appearance at all? When did ugliness become a deformity and what deformities.\par
But when the sunlight vanished and they entered the first door that led to the Personal, the mood became harder to maintain.\par
Baley shook his head with exasperation. It was all ridiculous. Forcing Earthmen to emigrate, to set up a new society! It was nonsense! What were these Spacers really after?\par
He thought about it and came to no conclusion.\par
Slowly, their squad car rolled down the vehicular lane. Reality was surging all about Baley. His blaster was a warm and comfortable weight against his hip. The noise and vibrant life of the City was just as warm, just as comfortable.\par
For a moment, as the City closed in, his nose tingled to a slight and fugitive pungence.\par
He thought wonderingly: The City smells.\par
He thought of the twenty million human beings crammed into the steel walls of the great cave and for the first time in his life he smelled them with nostrils that had been washed clean by outdoor air.\par
He thought: Would it be different on another world? Less people and more air-cleaner?\par
But the afternoon roar of the City was all around them, the smell faded and was gone, and he felt a little ashamed of himself.\par
He let the drive rod in slowly and tapped a larger share of the beamed power. The squad car accelerated sharply as it slanted down into the empty motorway.\par
\ldblquote Daneel,\rdblquote  he said.\par
\ldblquote Yes, Elijah.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why was Dr. Fastolfe telling me all he did?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It seems probable to me, Elijah, that he wished to impress you with the importance of the investigation. We are not here just to solve a murder, but to save Spacetown and with it, the future of the human race.\rdblquote\par
Baley said dryly, \ldblquote I think he\rquote d have been better off if he\rquote d let me see the scene of the crime and interview the men who first found the body.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I doubt if you could have added anything, Elijah. We have been quite thorough.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Have you? You\rquote ve got nothing. Not a clue. Not a suspect.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, you are right. The answer must be in the City. To be accurate, though, we did have one suspect.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What? You said nothing of this before.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I did not feel it to be necessary, Elijah. Surely it is obvious to you that one suspect automatically existed.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Who? In the devil\rquote s name, who?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The one Earthman who was on the scene. Commissioner Julius Enderby.\rdblquote\par
\pard\keepn\pagebb\s1\sb240\sa60\qc\kerning32\b\f2\fs32 Chapter 10\par
\pard\keepn\s2\sb240\sa240\qc\kerning0\i\fs28 AFTERNOON OF A PLAIN-CLOTHES MAN\par
\pard\fi216\qj\b0\i0\f0\fs24 The squad car veered to one side, halted against the impersonal concrete wall of the motorway. With the humming of its motor stopped, the silence was dead and thick.\par
Baley looked at the robot next to him and said in an incongruously quiet voice, \ldblquote What?\rdblquote\par
Time stretched while Baley waited for an answer. A small and lonesome vibration rose and reached a minor peak, then faded. It was the sound of another squad car, boring its way past them on some unknown errand, perhaps a mile away. Or else it was a fire car hurrying along toward its own appointment with combustion.\par
A detached portion of Baley\rquote s mind wondered if any one man any longer knew all the motorways that twisted about in New York City\rquote s bowels. At no time in the day or night could the entire motorway system be completely empty, and yet there must be individual passages that no man had entered in years. With sudden, devastating clarity, he remembered a short story he had viewed as a youngster.\par
It concerned the motorways of London and began, quietly enough, with a murder. The murderer fled toward a prearranged hideout in the corner of a motorway in whose dust his own shoeprints had been the only disturbance for a century. In that abandoned hole, he could wait in complete safety till the search died.\par
But he took a wrong turning and in the silence and loneness of those twisting corridors he swore a mad and blaspheming oath that, in spite of the Trinity and all the saints, he would yet reach his haven. From that time on, no turning was right. He wandered through an unending maze from the Brighton Sector on the Channel to Norwich and from Coventry to Canterbury. He burrowed endlessly beneath the great City of London from end to end of its sprawl across the southeastern corner of Medieval England. His clothes were rags and his shoes ribbons, his strength wore down but never left him. He was tired, tired, but unable to stop. He could only go on and on with only wrong turnings ahead of him.\par
Sometimes he heard the sound of passing cars, but they were always in the next corridor, and however fast he rushed (for he would gladly have given himself up by then) the corridors he reached were always empty. Sometimes he saw an exit far ahead that would lead to the City\rquote s life and breath, but it always glimmered further away as he approached until he would turn-and it would be gone.\par
Occasionally, Londoners on official business through the underground would see a misty figure limping silently toward them, a semitransparent arm lifted in pleading, a mouth open and moving, but soundless. As it approached, it would waver and vanish.\par
It was a story that hid lost the attributes of ordinary fiction and had entered the realm of folklore. The \ldblquote Wandering Londoner\rdblquote  had become a familiar phrase to all the world.\par
In the depths of New York City, Baley remembered the story and stirred uneasily.\par
R. Daneel spoke and there was a small echo to his voice. He said, \ldblquote We may be overheard.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Down here? Not a chance. Now what about the Commissioner?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He was on the scene, Elijah. He is a City dweller. He was inevitably a suspect.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Was! Is he still a suspect?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No. His innocence was quickly established. For one thing, there was no blaster in his possession. There could not very well be one. He had entered Spacetown in the usual fashion; that was quite certain; and, as you know, blasters are removed as a matter of course.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Was the murder weapon found at all, by the way?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, Elijah. Every blaster in Spacetown was checked and none had been fired for weeks. A check of the radiation chambers was quite conclusive.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Then whoever had committed the murder had either hidden the weapon so well--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It could not have been hidden anywhere in Spacetown. We were quite thorough.\rdblquote\par
Baley said impatiently, \ldblquote I\rquote m trying to consider all possibilities. It was either hidden or it was carried away by the murderer when he left.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Exactly.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And if you admit only the second possibility, then the Commissioner is cleared.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes. As a precaution, of course, he was cerebroanalyzed.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote By cerebroanalysis, I mean the interpretation of the electromagnetic fields of the living brain cells.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh,\rdblquote  said Baley, unenlightened. \ldblquote And what does that tell you?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It gives us information concerning the temperamental and emotional makeup of an individual. In the case of Commissioner Enderby, it told us that he was incapable of killing Dr. Sarton. Quite incapable.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  agreed Baley. \ldblquote He isn\rquote t the type. I could have told you that.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It is better to have objective information. Naturally, all our people in Spacetown allowed themselves to be cerebroanalyzed as well.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All incapable, I suppose.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No question. It is why we know that the murderer must be a City dweller.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, then, all we have to do is pass the whole City under your cute little process.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It would not be very practical, Elijah. There might be millions temperamentally capable of the deed.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Millions,\rdblquote  grunted Baley, thinking of the crowds of that long ago day who had screamed at the dirty Spacers, and of the threatening and slobbering crowds outside the shoe store the night before.\par
He thought: Poor Julius. A suspect!\par
He could hear the Commissioner\rquote s voice describing the period after the discovery of the body: \ldblquote It was brutal, brutal.\rdblquote  No wonder he broke his glasses in shock and dismay. No wonder he did not want to return to Spacetown. \ldblquote I hate them,\rdblquote  he had ground out between his teeth..\par
Poor Julius. The man who could handle Spacers. The man whose greatest value to the City lay in his ability to get along with them. How much did that contribute to his rapid promotions?\par
No wonder the Commissioner had wanted Baley to take over. Good old loyal, close-mouthed Baley. College chum! He would keep quiet if he found out about that little incident. Baley wondered how cerebroanalysis was carried out. He imagined huge electrodes, busy pantographs skidding inklines across graphed paper, self-adjusting gears clicking into place now and then.\par
Poor Julius. If his state of mind were as appalled as it almost had a right to be, he might already be seeing himself at the end of his career with a forced letter of resignation in the hands of the Mayor.\par
The squad car slanted up into the sublevels of City Hall.\par
It was 14:30 when Baley arrived back at his desk. The Commissioner was out. R. Sammy, grinning, did not know where the Commissioner was.\par
Baley spent some time thinking. The fact that he was hungry didn\rquote t register.\par
At 15:20 R. Sammy came to his desk and said, \ldblquote The Commissioner is in now, Lije.\rdblquote\par
Baley said, \ldblquote Thanks.\rdblquote\par
For once he listened to R. Sammy without being annoyed. R. Sammy, after all, was a kind of relation to R. Daneel, and R. Daneel obviously wasn\rquote t a person--or thing, rather--to get annoyed with. Baley wondered how it would be on a new planet with men and robots starting even in a City culture. He considered the situation quite dispassionately.\par
The Commissioner was going through some documents as Baley entered, stopping occasionally to make notations.\par
He said, \ldblquote That was a fairly giant-size blooper you pulled out in Spacetown.\rdblquote\par
It flooded back strongly. The verbal duel with Fastolfe.\par
His long face took on a lugubrious expression of chagrin. \ldblquote I\rquote ll admit I did, Commissioner. I\rquote m sorry.\rdblquote\par
Enderby looked up. His expression was keen through his glasses. He seemed more himself than at any time these thirty hours. He said, \ldblquote No real matter. Fastolfe didn\rquote t seem to mind, so we\rquote ll forget it. Unpredictable, these Spacers. You don\rquote t deserve your luck, Lije. Next time you talk it over with me before you make like a one-man subether hero,\rdblquote\par
Baley nodded. The whole thing rolled off his shoulders. He had tried a grandstand stunt and it hadn\rquote t worked. Okay. He was a little surprised that he could be so casual about it, but there it was.\par
He said, \ldblquote Look, Commissioner. I want to have a two-man apartment assigned to Daneel and myself. I\rquote m not taking him home tonight.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s all this?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The news is out that he\rquote s a robot. Remember? Maybe nothing will happen, but if there is a riot, I don\rquote t want my family in the middle of it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Nonsense, Lije. I\rquote ve had the thing checked. There\rquote s no such rumor in the City.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Jessie got the story somewhere, Commissioner.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, there\rquote s no organized rumor. Nothing dangerous. I\rquote ve been checking this ever since I got off the trimensic at Fastolfe\rquote s dome. It was why I left. I had to track it down, naturally, and fast. Anyway, here are the reports. See for yourself. There\rquote s Doris Gillid\rquote s report. She went through a dozen Women\rquote s Personals in different parts of the City. You know Doris. She\rquote s a competent girl. Well, nothing showed. Nothing showed anywhere.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Then how did Jessie get the rumor, Commissioner?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It can be explained. R. Daneel made a show of himself in the shoe store. Did he really pull a blaster, Lije, or were you stretching it a little?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He really pulled one. Pointed it, too.\rdblquote\par
Commissioner Enderby shook his head. \ldblquote All right. Someone recognized him. As a robot, I mean.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Hold on,\rdblquote  said Baley, indignantly. \ldblquote You can\rquote t tell him for a robot.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Could you? I couldn\rquote t.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What does that prove? We\rquote re no experts. Suppose there was a technician out of the Westchester robot factories in the crowd. A professional. A man who has spent his life building and designing robots. He notices something queer about R. Daneel. Maybe in the way he talks or holds himself. He speculates about it. Maybe he tells his wife. She tells a few friends. Then it dies. It\rquote s too improbable. People don\rquote t believe it. Only it got to Jessie before it died.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Maybe,\rdblquote  said Baley, doubtfully. \ldblquote But how about an assignment to a bachelor room for two, anyway?\rdblquote\par
The Commissioner shrugged, lifted the intercom. After a while, he said, \ldblquote Section Q-27 is all they can do. It\rquote s not a very good neighborhood.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It\rquote ll do,\rdblquote  said Baley.\par
\ldblquote Where\rquote s R. Daneel now, by the way?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He\rquote s at our record files. He\rquote s trying to collect information on Medievalist agitators.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Good Lord, there are millions.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I know, but it keeps him happy.\rdblquote\par
Baley was nearly at the door, when he turned, half on impulse, and said, \ldblquote Commissioner, did Dr. Sarton ever talk to you about Spacetown\rquote s program? I mean, about introducing the C/Fe culture?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The what?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Introducing robots.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Occasionally.\rdblquote  The Commissioner\rquote s tone was not one of any particular interest.\par
\ldblquote Did he ever explain what Spacetown\rquote s point was?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, improve health, raise the standard of living. The usual talk; it didn\rquote t impress me. Oh, I agreed with him. I nodded my head and all that. What could I do? It\rquote s just a matter of humoring them and hoping they\rquote ll keep within reason in their notions. Maybe some day ...\rdblquote\par
Baley waited but he didn\rquote t say what maybe--some--day might bring.\par
Baley said, \ldblquote Did he ever mention anything about emigration?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Emigration! Never. Letting an Earthman into an Outer World is like finding a diamond asteroid in the rings of Saturn.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I mean emigration to new worlds.\rdblquote\par
But the Commissioner answered that one with a simple stare of incredulousness.\par
Baley chewed that for a moment, then said with sudden bluntness, \ldblquote What\rquote s cerebroanalysis, Commissioner? Ever hear of it?\rdblquote\par
The Commissioner\rquote s round face didn\rquote t pucker; his eyes didn\rquote t blink. He said evenly, \ldblquote No, what\rquote s it supposed to be?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Nothing. Just picked it up.\rdblquote\par
He left the office and at his desk continued thinking. Certainly, the Commissioner wasn\rquote t that good an actor. Well, then.\par
At 16:05 Baley called Jessie and told her he wouldn\rquote t be home that night nor probably any night for a while. It took a while after that to disengage her.\par
\ldblquote Lije, is there trouble? Are you in danger?\rdblquote\par
A policeman is always in a certain amount of danger, he explained lightly. It didn\rquote t satisfy her. \ldblquote Where will you be staying?\rdblquote\par
He didn\rquote t tell her. \ldblquote If you\rquote re going to be lonely tonight,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote stay at your mother\rquote s.\rdblquote  He broke connections abruptly, which was probably just as well.\par
At 16:20 he made a call to Washington. It took a certain length of time to reach the man he wanted and an almost equally long time to convince him he ought to make an air trip to New York the next day. By 16:40, he had succeeded.\par
At 16:55 the Commissioner left, passing him with an uncertain smile. The day shift left en masse. The sparser population that filled the offices in the evening and through the night made its way in and greeted him in varied tones of surprise.\par
R. Daneel came to his desk with a sheaf of papers.\par
\ldblquote And those are?\rdblquote  asked Baley.\par
\ldblquote A list of men and women who might belong to a Medievalist organization.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote How many does the list include?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Over a million,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel. \ldblquote These are just part of them.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Do you expect to check them all, Daneel?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Obviously that would be impractical, Elijah.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You see, Daneel, almost all Earthmen are Medievalists in one way or another. The Commissioner, Jessie, myself. Look at the Commissioner\rquote s--\rdblquote  (He almost said, \ldblquote spectacles,\rdblquote  then remembered that Earthmen must stick together and that the Commissioner\rquote s face must be protected in the figurative as well as the literal sense.) He concluded, lamely, \ldblquote eye ornaments.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel, \ldblquote I had noticed them, but thought it indelicate, perhaps, to refer to them. I have not seen such ornaments on other City dwellers.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It is a very old-fashioned sort of thing.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Does it serve a purpose of any sort?\rdblquote\par
Baley said, abruptly, \ldblquote How did you get your list?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It was a machine that did it for me. Apparently, one sets it for a particular type of offense and it does the rest. I let it scan all disorderly conduct cases involving robots over the past twenty-five years. Another machine scanned all City newspapers over an equal period for the names of those involved in unfavorable statements concerning robots or men of the Outer Worlds. It is amazing what can be done in three hours. The machine even eliminated the names of non-survivors from the lists.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You are amazed? Surely you\rquote ve got computers on the Outer Worlds?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Of many sorts, certainly. Very advanced ones. Still, none are as massive and complex as the ones here. You must remember, of course, that even the largest Outer World scarcely has the population of one of your Cities and extreme complexity is not necessary.\rdblquote\par
Baley said, \ldblquote Have you ever been on Aurora?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel, \ldblquote I was assembled here on Earth.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Then how do you know about Outer World computers?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But surely that is obvious, partner Elijah. My data store is drawn from that of the late Dr. Sarton. You may take it for granted that it is rich in factual material concerning the Outer Worlds.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I see. Can you eat, Daneel?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I am nuclear-powered. I had thought you were aware of that.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m perfectly aware of it. I didn\rquote t ask if you needed to eat. I asked if you could eat. If you could put food in your mouth, chew it, and swallow it. I should think that would be an important item in seeming to be a man.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I see your point. Yes, I can perform the mechanical operations of chewing and swallowing. My capacity is, of course, quite limited, and I would have to remove the ingested material from what you might call my stomach sooner or later.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All right. You can regurgitate, or whatever you do, in the quiet of our room tonight. The point is that I\rquote m hungry. I\rquote ve missed lunch, damn it, and I want you with me when I eat. And you can\rquote t sit there and not eat without attracting attention. So if you can eat, that\rquote s what I want to hear. Let\rquote s go!\rdblquote\par
Section kitchens were the same all over the City. What\rquote s more, Baley had been in Washington, Toronto, Los Angeles, London, and Budapest in the way of business, and they had been the same there, too. Perhaps it had been different in Medieval times when languages had varied and dietaries as well. Nowadays, yeast products were just the same from Shanghai to Tashkent and from Winnipeg to Buenos Aires; and English might not be the \ldblquote English\rdblquote  of Shakespeare or Churchill, but it was the final potpourri that was current over all the continents and, with some modification, on the Outer Worlds as well.\par
But language and dietary aside, there were the deeper similarities. There was always that particular odor, undefinable but completely characteristic of \ldblquote kitchen.\rdblquote  There was the waiting triple line moving slowly in, converging at the door and splitting up again, right, left, center. There was the rumble of humanity, speaking and moving, and the sharper clatter of plastic on plastic. There was the gleam of simulated wood, highly polished, highlights on glass, long tables, the touch of steam in the air.\par
Baley inched slowly forward as the line moved (with all possible staggering of meal hours, a wait of at least ten minutes was almost unavoidable) and said to R. Daneel in sudden curiosity, \ldblquote Can you smile?\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel, who had been gazing at the interior of the kitchen with cool absorption, said, \ldblquote I beg your pardon, Elijah.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m just wondering, Daneel. Can you smile?\rdblquote  He spoke in a casual whisper.\par
R. Daneel smiled. The gesture was sudden and surprising. His lips curled back and the skin about either end folded. Only the mouth smiled, however. The rest of the robot\rquote s face was untouched.\par
Baley shook his head. \ldblquote Don\rquote t bother, R. Daneel. It doesn\rquote t do a thing for you.\rdblquote\par
They were at the entrance. Person after person thrust his metal food tag through the appropriate slot and had it scanned. Click--click--click-- Someone once calculated that a smoothly running kitchen could allow the entrance of two hundred persons a minute, the tags of each one being fully scanned to prevent kitchen-jumping, meal-jumping, and ration-stretching. They had also calculated how long a waiting line was necessary for maximum efficiency and how much time was lost when any one person required special treatment.\par
It was therefore always a calamity to interrupt that smooth click-click by stepping to the manual window, as Baley and R. Daneel did, in order to thrust a special-permit pass at the official in charge.\par
Jessie, filled with the knowledge of an assistant dietitian, had explained it once to Baley.\par
\ldblquote It upsets things completely,\rdblquote  she had said. \ldblquote It throws off consumption figures and inventory estimates. It means special checks. You have to match slips with all the different Section kitchens to make sure the balance isn\rquote t too unbalanced, if you know what I mean. There\rquote s a separate balance sheet to be made out each week. Then if anything goes wrong and you\rquote re overdrawn, it\rquote s always your fault. It\rquote s never the fault of the City Government for passing out special tickets to everybody and his kid sister. Oh, no. And when we have to say that free choice is suspended for the meal, don\rquote t the people in line make a fuss. It\rquote s always the fault of the people behind the counter ...\rdblquote\par
Baley had the story in the fullest detail and so he quite understood the dry and poisonous look he received from the woman behind the window. She made a few hurried notes. Home Section, occupation, reason for meal displacement (\ldblquote official business,\rdblquote  a very irritating reason indeed, but quite irrefutable). Then she folded the slip with firm motions of her fingers and pushed it into a slot. A computer seized it, devoured the contents, and digested the information.\par
She turned to R. Daneel.\par
Baley let her have the worst. He said, \ldblquote My friend is out-of-City.\rdblquote\par
The woman looked finally and completely outraged. She said, \ldblquote Home City, please.\rdblquote\par
Baley intercepted the ball for Daneel once again. \ldblquote All records are to be credited to the Police Department. No details necessary. Official business.\rdblquote\par
The woman brought down a pad of slips with a jerk of her arm and filled in the necessary matter in dark-light code with practiced pressings of the first two fingers of her right hand.\par
She said, \ldblquote How long will you be eating here?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Till further notice,\rdblquote  said Baley.\par
\ldblquote Press fingers here,\rdblquote  she said, inverting the information blank.\par
Baley had a short qualm as R. Daneel\rquote s even fingers with their glistening nails pressed downward. Surely, they wouldn\rquote t have forgotten to supply him with fingerprints.\par
The woman took the blank away and fed it into the all-consuming machine at her elbow. It belched nothing back and Baley breathed more easily.\par
She gave them little metal tags that were in the bright red that meant \ldblquote temporary.\rdblquote\par
She said, \ldblquote No free choices. We\rquote re short this week. Take table DF.\rdblquote\par
They made their way toward DF.\par
R. Daneel said, \ldblquote I am under the impression that most of your people eat in kitchens such as these regularly.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes. Of course, it\rquote s rather gruesome eating in a strange kitchen. There\rquote s no one about whom you know. In your own kitchen, it\rquote s quite different. You have your own seat which you occupy all the time. You\rquote re with your family, your friends. Especially when you\rquote re young, mealtimes are the bright spot of the day.\rdblquote  Baley smiled in brief reminiscence.\par
Table DF was apparently among those reserved for transients. Those already seated watched their plates uneasily and did not talk with one another. They looked with sneaking envy at the laughing crowds at the other tables.\par
There is no one so uncomfortable, thought Baley, as the man eating out-of-Section. Be it ever so humble, the old saying went, there\rquote s no place like home-kitchen. Even the food tastes better, no matter how many chemists are ready to swear it to be no different from the food in Johannesburg.\par
He sat down on a stool and R. Daneel sat down next to him.\par
\ldblquote No free choice,\rdblquote  said Baley, with a wave of his fingers, \ldblquote so just close the switch there and wait.\rdblquote\par
It took two minutes. A disc slid back in the table top and a dish lifted.\par
\ldblquote Mashed potatoes, zymoveal sauce, and stewed apricots. Oh, well,\rdblquote  said Baley.\par
A fork and two slices of whole yeast bread appeared in a recess just in front of the low railing that went down the long center of the table.\par
R. Daneel said in a low voice, \ldblquote You may help yourself to my serving, if you wish.\rdblquote\par
For a moment, Baley was scandalized. Then he remembered and mumbled, \ldblquote That\rquote s bad manners. Go on. Eat.\rdblquote\par
Baley ate industriously but without the relaxation that allows complete enjoyment. Carefully, he flicked an occasional glance at R. Daneel. The robot ate with precise motions of his jaws. Too precise. It didn\rquote t look quite natural.\par
Strange! Now that Baley knew for a fact that R. Daneel was in truth a robot, all sorts of little items showed up clearly. For instance, there was no movement of an Adam\rquote s apple when R. Daneel swallowed.\par
Yet he didn\rquote t mind so much. Was he getting used to the creature? Suppose people started afresh on a new world (how that ran through his mind ever since Dr. Fastolfe had put it there); suppose Bentley, for instance, were to leave Earth; could he get so he didn\rquote t mind working and living alongside robots? Why not? The Spacers themselves did it.\par
R. Daneel said, \ldblquote Elijah, is it bad manners to watch another man while he is eating?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote If you mean stare directly at him, of course. That\rquote s only common sense, isn\rquote t it? A man has a right to his privacy. Ordinary conversation is entirely in order, but you don\rquote t peer at a man while he\rquote s swallowing.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I see. Why is it then that I count eight people watching us closely, very closely?\rdblquote\par
Baley put down his fork. He looked about as though he were searching for the salt-pinch dispenser. \ldblquote I see nothing out of the ordinary.\rdblquote\par
But he said it without conviction. The mob of diners was only a vast conglomeration of chaos to him. And when R. Daneel turned his impersonal brown eyes upon him, Baley suspected uncomfortably that those were not eyes he saw, but scanners capable of noting, with photographic accuracy and in split seconds of time, the entire panorama.\par
\ldblquote I am quite certain,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel, calmly.\par
\ldblquote Well, then, what of it? It\rquote s crude behavior, but what does it prove?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I cannot say, Elijah, but is it coincidence that six of the watchers were in the crowd outside the shoe store last night?\rdblquote\par
