\pard\keepn\s2\sb240\sa240\qc\kerning0\i\fs28 WORDS FROM AN EXPERT\par
\pard\fi216\qj\b0\i0\f0\fs24 Elijah Baley looked up as Commissioner Julius Enderby entered the office. He nodded wearily.\par
The Commissioner looked at the clock and grunted, \ldblquote Don\rquote t tell me you\rquote ve been here all night!\rdblquote\par
Baley said, \ldblquote I won\rquote t.\rdblquote\par
The Commissioner said in a low voice, \ldblquote Any trouble last night?\rdblquote  Baley shook his head.\par
The Commissioner said, \ldblquote I\rquote ve been thinking that I could be minimizing the possibility of riots. If there\rquote s anything to--\rdblquote\par
Baley said tightly, \ldblquote For God\rquote s sake, Commissioner, if anything happened, I\rquote d tell you. There was no trouble of any sort.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All right.\rdblquote  The Commissioner moved away, passing beyond the door that marked off the unusual privacy that became his exalted position.\par
Baley looked after him and thought: He must have slept last night.\par
Baley bent to the routine report he was trying to write as a cover-up for the real activities of the last two days, but the words he had tapped out by finger touch blurred and danced. Slowly, he became aware of an object standing by his desk.\par
He lifted his head. \ldblquote What do you want?\rdblquote\par
It was R. Sammy. Baley thought: Julius\rquote s private flunky. It pays to be a Commissioner.\par
R. Sammy said through his fatuous grin, \ldblquote The Commissioner wants to see you, Lije. He says right away.\rdblquote\par
Baley waved his hand. \ldblquote He just saw me. Tell him I\rquote ll be in later.\rdblquote\par
R. Sammy said, \ldblquote He says right away.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All right. All right. Go away.\rdblquote\par
The robot backed away, saying, \ldblquote The Commissioner wants to see you right away, Lije. He says right away.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Jehoshaphat,\rdblquote  said Baley between his teeth. \ldblquote I\rquote m going. I\rquote m going.\rdblquote  He got up from his desk, headed for the office, and R. Sammy was silent.\par
Baley said as he entered, \ldblquote Damn it, Commissioner, don\rquote t send that thing after me, will you?\rdblquote\par
But the Commissioner only said, \ldblquote Sit down, Lije. Sit down.\rdblquote  Baley sat down and stared. Perhaps he had done old Julius an injustice. Perhaps the man hadn\rquote t slept after all. He looked fairly beat.\par
The Commissioner was tapping the paper before him. \ldblquote There\rquote s a record of a call you made to a Dr. Gerrigel at Washington by insulated beam.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s right, Commissioner.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote There\rquote s no record of the conversation, naturally, since it was insulated. What\rquote s it all about?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m after background information.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote He\rquote s a roboticist, isn\rquote t he?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s right.\rdblquote\par
The Commissioner put out a lower lip and suddenly looked like a child about to pout. \ldblquote But what\rquote s the point? What kind of information are you after?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m not sure, Commissioner. I just have a feeling that in a case like this, information on robots might help.\rdblquote  Baley clamped his mouth shut after that. He wasn\rquote t going to be specific, and that was that.\par
\ldblquote I wouldn\rquote t, Lije. I wouldn\rquote t. I don\rquote t think it\rquote s wise.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s your objection, Commissioner?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The fewer the people who know about all this, the better.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll tell him as little as I can. Naturally.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I still don\rquote t think it\rquote s wise.\rdblquote\par
Baley was feeling just sufficiently wretched to lose patience.\par
He said, \ldblquote Are you ordering me not to see him?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No. No. You do as you see fit. You\rquote re heading this investigation. Only ...\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Only what?\rdblquote\par
The Commissioner shook his head. \ldblquote Nothing. --Where is he? You know who I mean.\rdblquote\par
Baley did. He said, \ldblquote Daneel\rquote s still at the files.\rdblquote\par
The Commissioner paused a long moment, then said, \ldblquote We\rquote re not making much progress, you know.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We\rquote re not making any so far. Still, things may change.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All right, then,\rdblquote  said the Commissioner, but he didn\rquote t look as though he really thought it were all right.\par
R. Daneel was at Baley\rquote s desk, when the latter returned.\par
\ldblquote Well, and what have you got?\rdblquote  Baley asked gruffly.\par
\ldblquote I have completed my first, rather hasty, search through the files, partner Elijah, and I have located two of the people who tried to track us last night and who, moreover, were at the shoe store during the former incident.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Let\rquote s see.\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel placed the small, stamp-size cards before Baley. They were mottled with the small dots that served as code. The robot also produced a portable decoder and placed one of the cards into an appropriate slot. The dots possessed electrical conduction properties different from that of the card as a whole. The electric field passing through the card was therefore distorted in a highly specific manner and in response to that specification the three-by-six screen above the decoder was filled with words. Words which, uncoded, would have filled several sheets of standard size report paper. Words, moreover, which could not possibly be interpreted by anyone not in possession of an official police decoder.\par
Baley read through the material stolidly. The first person was Francis Clousarr, age thirty-three at time of arrest two years before; cause of arrest, inciting to riot; employee at New York Yeast; home address, so-and-so; parentage, so-and-so; hair, eyes, distinguishing marks, educational history, employment history, psychoanalytic profile, physical profile, data here, data there, and finally reference to a photo in the rogues\rquote  gallery.\par
\ldblquote You checked the photograph?\rdblquote  asked Baley. \ldblquote Yes, Elijah.\rdblquote\par
The second person was Gerhard Paul. Baley glanced at the material on that card and said, \ldblquote This is all no good.\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel said, \ldblquote I am sure that cannot be so. If there is an organization of Earthmen who are capable of the crime we are investigating, these are members. Is that not an obvious likelihood? Should they then not be questioned?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote We\rquote d get nothing out of them.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote They were there, both at the shoe store and in the kitchen. They cannot deny it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Just being there\rquote s no crime. Besides which, they can deny it. They can just say they weren\rquote t there. It\rquote s as simple as that. How can we prove they\rquote re lying?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I saw them.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s no proof,\rdblquote  said Baley, savagely. \ldblquote No court, if it ever came to that, would believe that you could remember two faces in a blur of a million.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It is obvious that I can.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Sure. Tell them what you are. As soon as you do that, you\rquote re no witness. Your kind have no status in any court of law on Earth.\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel said, \ldblquote I take it, then, that you have changed your mind.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What do you mean?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yesterday, in the kitchen, you said there was no need to arrest them. You said that as long as I remembered their faces, we could arrest them at any time.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, I didn\rquote t think it through,\rdblquote  said Baley. \ldblquote I was crazy. It can\rquote t be done.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Not even for psychological reasons? They would not know we had no legal proof of their complicity in conspiracy.\rdblquote\par
Baley said, tensely, \ldblquote Look, I am expecting Dr. Gerrigel of Washington in half an hour. Do you mind waiting till he\rquote s been here and gone? Do you mind?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I will wait,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel.\par
Anthony Gerrigel was a precise and very polite man of middle height, who looked far from being one of the most erudite roboticists on Earth. He was nearly twenty minutes late, it turned out, and quite apologetic about it. Baley, white with an anger born of apprehension, shrugged off the apologies gracelessly. He checked his reservation on Conference Room D, repeated his instructions that they were not to be disturbed on any account for an hour, and led Dr. Gerrigel and R. Daneel down the corridor, up a ramp, and through a door that led to one of the spy-beam-insulated chambers.\par
Baley checked the walls carefully before sitting down, listening to the soft burr of the pulsometer in his hand, waiting for any fading of the steady sound which would indicate a break, even a small one, in the insulation. He turned it on the ceiling, floor, and, with particular care, on the door. There was no break.\par
Dr. Gerrigel smiled a little. He looked like a man who never smiled more than a little. He was dressed with a neatness that could only be described as fussy. His iron-gray hair was smoothed carefully back and his face looked pink and freshly washed. He sat with a posture of prim stiffness as though repeated maternal advice in his younger years concerning the desirability of good posture had rigidified his spine forever.\par
He said to Baley, \ldblquote You make this all seem very formidable.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s quite important, Doctor. I need information about robots that only you can give me, perhaps. Anything we say here, of course, is top secret and the City will expect you to forget it all when you leave.\rdblquote  Baley looked at his watch.\par
The little smile on the roboticist\rquote s face winked away. He said, \ldblquote Let me explain why I am late.\rdblquote  The matter obviously weighed upon him. \ldblquote I decided not to go by air. I get airsick.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s too bad,\rdblquote  said Baley. He put away the pulsometer, after checking its standard settings to make last-minute certain that there was nothing wrong with it, and sat down.\par
\ldblquote Or at least not exactly airsick, but nervous. A mild agoraphobia. It\rquote s nothing particularly abnormal, but there it is. So I took the expressways.\rdblquote\par
Baley felt a sudden sharp interest. \ldblquote Agoraphobia?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I make it sound worse than it is,\rdblquote  the roboticist said at once. \ldblquote It\rquote s just the feeling you get in a plane. Have you ever been in one, Mr. Baley?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Several times.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Then you must know what I mean. It\rquote s that feeling of being surrounded by nothing; of being separated from--from empty air by a mere inch of metal. It\rquote s very uncomfortable.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote So you took the expressway?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All the way from Washington to New York?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, I\rquote ve done it before. Since they built the Baltimore-Philadelphia tunnel, it\rquote s quite simple.\rdblquote\par
So it was. Baley had never made the trip himself, but he was perfectly aware that it was possible. Washington, Baltimore, Philadelphia, and New York had grown, in the last two centuries, to the point where all nearly touched. The Four-City Area was almost the official name for the entire stretch of coast, and there were a considerable number of people who favored administrational consolidation and the formation of a single super-City. Baley disagreed with that, himself. New York City by itself was almost too large to be handled by a centralized government. A larger City, with over fifty million population, would break down under its own weight.\par
\ldblquote The trouble was,\rdblquote  Dr. Gerrigel was saying, \ldblquote that I missed a connection in Chester Sector, Philadelphia, and lost time. That, and a little difficulty in getting a transient room assignment, ended by making me late.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t worry about that, Doctor. What you say, though, is interesting. In view of your dislike for planes, what would you say to going outside City limits on foot, Dr. Gerrigel?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote For what reason?\rdblquote  He looked startled and more than a little apprehensive.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s just a rhetorical question. I\rquote m not suggesting that you really should. I want to know how the notion strikes you, that\rquote s all.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It strikes me very unpleasantly.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Suppose you had to leave the City at night and walk cross country for half a mile or more.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I--I don\rquote t think I could be persuaded to.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No matter how important the necessity?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote If it were to save my life or the lives of my family, I might try. ...\rdblquote  He looked embarrassed. \ldblquote May I ask the point of these questions, Mr. Baley?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll tell you. A serious crime has been committed, a particularly disturbing murder. I\rquote m not at liberty to give you the details. There is a theory, however, that the murderer, in order to commit the crime, did just what we were discussing; he crossed open country at night and alone. I was just wondering what kind of man could do that.\rdblquote\par
Dr. Gerrigel shuddered. \ldblquote No one I know. Certainly not I. Of course, among millions I suppose you could find a few hardy individuals.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But you wouldn\rquote t say it was a very likely thing for a human being to do?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No. Certainly not likely.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote In fact, if there\rquote s any other explanation for the crime, any other conceivable explanation, it should be considered.\rdblquote\par
Dr. Gerrigel looked more uncomfortable than ever as he sat bolt upright with his well-kept hands precisely folded in his lap. \ldblquote Do you have an alternate explanation in mind?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes. It occurs to me that a robot, for instance, would have no difficulty at all in crossing open country.\rdblquote\par
Dr. Gerrigel stood up. \ldblquote Oh, my dear sir!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s wrong?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You mean a robot may have committed the crime?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Murder? Of a human being?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes. Please sit down, Doctor.\rdblquote\par
The roboticist did as he was told. He said, \ldblquote Mr. Baley, there are two acts involved: walking cross country, and murder. A human being could commit the latter easily, but would find difficulty in doing the former. A robot could do the former easily, but the latter act would be completely impossible. If you\rquote re going to replace an unlikely theory by an impossible one--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Impossible is a hell of a strong word, Doctor.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You\rquote ve heard of the First Law of Robotics, Mr. Baley?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Sure. I can even quote it: A robot may not injure a human being, or, through inaction, allow a human being to come to harm.\rdblquote  Baley suddenly pointed a finger at the roboticist and went on, \ldblquote Why can\rquote t a robot be built without the First Law? What\rquote s so sacred about it?\rdblquote\par
Dr. Gerrigel looked startled, then tittered, \ldblquote Oh, Mr. Baley.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, what\rquote s the answer?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Surely, Mr. Baley, if you even know a little about robotics, you must know the gigantic task involved, both mathematically and electronically, in building a positronic brain.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I have an idea,\rdblquote  said Baley. He remembered well his visit to a robot factory once in the way of business. He had seen their library of book-films, long ones, each of which contained the mathematical analysis of a single type of positronic brain. It took more than an hour for the average such film to be viewed at standard scanning speed, condensed though its symbolisms were. And no two brains were alike, even when prepared according to the most rigid specifications. That, Baley understood, was a consequence of Heisenberg\rquote s Uncertainty Principle. This meant that each film had to be supplemented by appendices involving possible variations.\par
Oh, it was a job, all right. Baley wouldn\rquote t deny that.\par
Dr. Gerrigel said, \ldblquote Well, then, you must understand that a design for a new type of positronic brain, even one where only minor innovations are involved, is not the matter of a night\rquote s work. It usually involves the entire research staff of a moderately sized factory and takes anywhere up to a year of time. Even this large expenditure of work would not be nearly enough if it were not that the basic theory of such circuits has already been standardized and may be used as a foundation for further elaboration. The standard basic theory involves the Three Laws of Robotics: the First Law, which you\rquote ve quoted; the Second Law, which states, \lquote A robot must obey the orders given it by human beings except where such orders would conflict with the First Law,\rquote  and the Third Law, which states, \lquote A robot must protect its own existence as long as such protection does not conflict with the First or Second Law.\rquote  Do you understand?\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel, who, to all appearances, had been following the conversation with close attention, broke in. \ldblquote If you will excuse me, Elijah, I would like to see if I follow Dr. Gerrigel. What you imply, sir, is that any attempt to build a robot, the working of whose positronic brain is not oriented about the Three Laws, would require first the setting up of a new basic theory and that this, in turn, would take many years.\rdblquote\par
The roboticist looked very gratified. \ldblquote That is exactly what I mean.\rdblquote\par
Mr. Baley waited a moment, then carefully introduced R. Daneel: \ldblquote This is Daneel Olivaw, Dr. Gerrigel.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Good day, Mr. Olivaw.\rdblquote  Dr. Gerrigel extended his hand and shook Daneel\rquote s. He went on, \ldblquote It is my estimation that it would take fifty years to develop the basic theory of a non-Asenion positronic brain--that is, one in which the basic assumptions of the Three Laws are disallowed--and bring it to the point where robots similar to modern models could be constructed.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And this has never been done?\rdblquote  asked Baley. \ldblquote I mean, Doctor, that we\rquote ve been building robots for several thousand years. In all that time, hasn\rquote t anybody or any group had fifty years to spare?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Certainly,\rdblquote  said the roboticist, \ldblquote but it is not the sort of work that anyone would care to do.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I find that hard to believe. Human curiosity will undertake anything.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It hasn\rquote t undertaken the non-Asenion robot. The human race, Mr. Baley, has a strong Frankenstein complex.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote A what?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s a popular name derived from a Medieval novel describing a robot that turned on its creator. I never read the novel myself. But that\rquote s beside the point. What I wish to say is that robots without the First Law are simply not built.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And no theory for it even exists?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Not to my knowledge, and my knowledge,\rdblquote  he smiled self-consciously, \ldblquote is rather extensive.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And a robot with a First Law built in could not kill a man?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Never. Unless such killing were completely accidental or unless it were necessary to save the lives of two or more men. In either case, the positronic potential built up would ruin the brain past recovery.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All right,\rdblquote  said Baley. \ldblquote All this represents the situation on Earth. Right?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes. Certainly.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What about the Outer Worlds?\rdblquote\par
Some of Dr. Gerrigel\rquote s self-assurance seemed to ooze away. \ldblquote Oh dear, Mr. Baley, I couldn\rquote t say of my own knowledge, but I\rquote m sure that if non-Asenion positronic brains were ever designed or if the mathematical theory were worked out, we\rquote d hear of it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Would we? Well, let me follow up another thought in my mind, Dr. Gerrigel. I hope you don\rquote t mind.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No. Not at all.\rdblquote  He looked helplessly first at Baley, then at R. Daneel. \ldblquote After all, if it is as important as you say, I\rquote m glad to do all I can.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Thank you, Doctor. My question is, why humanoid robots? I mean that I\rquote ve been taking them for granted all my life, but now it occurs to me that I don\rquote t know the reason for their existence. Why should a robot have a head and four limbs? Why should he look more or less like a man?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You mean, why shouldn\rquote t he be built functionally, like any other machine?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Right,\rdblquote  said Baley. \ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote\par
Dr. Gerrigel smiled a little. \ldblquote Really, Mr. Baley, you are born too late. The early literature of robotics is riddled with a discussion of that very matter and the polemics involved were something frightful. If you would like a very good reference to the disputations among the functionalists and anti-functionalists, I can recommend Hanford\rquote s \lquote History of Robotics.\rquote  Mathematics is kept to a minimum. I think you\rquote d find it very interesting.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll look it up,\rdblquote  said Baley, patiently. \ldblquote Meanwhile, could you give me an idea?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The decision was made on the basis of economics. Look here, Mr. Baley, if you were supervising a farm, would you care to buy a tractor with a positronic brain, a reaper, a harrow, a milker, an automobile, and so on, each with a positronic brain; or would you rather have ordinary unbrained machinery with a single positronic robot to run them all. I warn you that the second alternative represents only a fiftieth or a hundredth the expense.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But why the human form?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Because the human form is the most successful generalized form in all nature. We are not a specialized animal, Mr. Baley, except for our nervous systems and a few odd items. If you want a design capable of doing a great many widely various things, all fairly well, you could do no better than to imitate the human form. Besides that, our entire technology is based on the human form. An automobile, for instance, has its controls so made as to be grasped and manipulated most easily by human hands and feet of a certain size and shape, attached to the body by limbs of a certain length and joints of a certain type. Even such simple objects as chairs and tables or knives and forks are designed to meet the requirements of human measurements and manner of working. It is easier to have robots imitate the human shape than to redesign radically the very philosophy of our tools.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I see. That makes sense. Now isn\rquote t it true, Doctor, that the roboticists of the Outer World manufacture robots that are much more humanoid than our Own?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I believe that is true.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Could they manufacture a robot so humanoid that it would pass for human under ordinary conditions?\rdblquote\par
Dr. Gerrigel lifted his eyebrows and considered that. \ldblquote I think they could, Mr. Baley. It would be terribly expensive. I doubt that the return could be profitable.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Do you suppose,\rdblquote  went on Baley, relentlessly, \ldblquote that they could make a robot that would fool you into thinking it was human?\rdblquote\par
The roboticist tittered. \ldblquote Oh, my dear Mr. Baley. I doubt that. Really. There\rquote s more to a robot than just his appear--\rdblquote\par
Dr. Gerrigel froze in the middle of the word. Slowly, he turned to R. Daneel, and his pink face went very pale.\par
\ldblquote Oh, dear me,\rdblquote  he whispered. \ldblquote Oh, dear me.\rdblquote\par
He reached out one hand and touched R. Daneel\rquote s cheek gingerly. R. Daneel did not move away but gazed at the roboticist calmly.\par
\ldblquote Dear me,\rdblquote  said Dr. Gerrigel, with what was almost a sob in his voice, \ldblquote you are a robot.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It took you a long time to realize that,\rdblquote  said Baley, dryly.\par
\ldblquote I wasn\rquote t expecting it. I never saw one like this. Outer World manufacture?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  said Baley.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s obvious now. The way he holds himself. The manner of his speaking. It is not a perfect imitation, Mr. Baley.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s pretty good though, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, it\rquote s marvelous. I doubt that anyone could recognize the imposture at sight. I am very grateful to you for having me brought face to face with him. May I examine him?\rdblquote  The roboticist was on his feet, eager.\par
Baley put out a hand. \ldblquote Please, Doctor. In a moment. First, the matter of the murder, you know.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Is that real, then?\rdblquote  Dr. Gerrigel was bitterly disappointed and showed it. \ldblquote I thought perhaps that was just a device to keep my mind engaged and to see how long I could be fooled by--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It is not a device, Dr. Gerrigel. Tell me, now, in constructing a robot as humanoid as this one, with the deliberate purpose of having it pass as human, is it not necessary to make its brain possess properties as close to that of the human brain as possible?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Certainly.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Very well. Could not such a humanoid brain lack the First Law? Perhaps it is left out accidentally. You say the theory is unknown. The very fact that it is unknown means that the constructors might set up a brain without the First Law. They would not know what to avoid.\rdblquote\par
Dr. Gerrigel was shaking his head vigorously. \ldblquote No. No. Impossible.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Are you sure? We can test the Second Law, of course. --Daneel, let me have your blaster.\rdblquote\par
Baley\rquote s eyes never left the robot. His own hand, well to one side, gripped his own blaster tightly.\par
R. Daneel said calmly, \ldblquote Here it is, Elijah,\rdblquote  and held it out, butt first.\par
Baley said, \ldblquote A plain-clothes man must never abandon his blaster, but a robot has no choice but to obey a human.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Except, Mr. Baley,\rdblquote  said Dr. Gerrigel, \ldblquote when obedience involves breaking the First Law.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Do you know, Doctor, that Daneel drew his blaster on an unarmed group of men and women and threatened to shoot?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But I did not shoot,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel.\par
\ldblquote Granted, but the threat was unusual in itself, wasn\rquote t it, Doctor?\rdblquote  Dr. Gerrigel bit his lip. \ldblquote I\rquote d need to know the exact circumstances to judge. It sounds unusual.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Consider this, then. R. Daneel was on the scene at the time of the murder, and if you omit the possibility of an Earthman having moved across open country, carrying a weapon with him, Daneel and Daneel alone of all the persons on the scene could have hidden the weapon.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Hidden the weapon?\rdblquote  asked Dr. Gerrigel.\par
\ldblquote Let me explain. The blaster that did the killing was not found. The scene of the murder was searched minutely and it was not found. Yet it could not have vanished like smoke. There is only one place it could have been, only one place they would not have thought to look.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Where, Elijah?\rdblquote  asked R. Daneel.\par
Baley brought his blaster into view, held its barrel firmly in the robot\rquote s direction.\par
\ldblquote In your food sac,\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote In your food sac, Daneel!\rdblquote\par
\pard\keepn\pagebb\s1\sb240\sa60\qc\kerning32\b\f2\fs32 Chapter 13\par
\pard\keepn\s2\sb240\sa240\qc\kerning0\i\fs28 SHIFT TO THE MACHINE\par
\pard\fi216\qj\b0\i0\f0\fs24\ldblquote That is not so,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel, quietly.\par
\ldblquote Yes? We\rquote ll let the Doctor decide. Dr. Gerrigel?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Mr. Baley?\rdblquote  The roboticist, whose glance had been alternating wildly between the plain-clothes man and the robot as they spoke, let it come to rest upon the human being.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ve asked you here for an authoritative analysis of this robot. I can arrange to have you use the laboratories of the City Bureau of Standards. If you need any piece of equipment they don\rquote t have, I\rquote ll get it for you. What I want is a quick and definite answer and hang the expense and trouble.\rdblquote\par
Baley rose. His words had emerged calmly enough, but he felt a rising hysteria behind them. At the moment, he felt that if he could only seize Dr. Gerrigel by the throat and choke the necessary statements out of him, he would forgo all science.\par
He said, \ldblquote Well, Dr. Gerrigel?\rdblquote\par
Dr. Gerrigel tittered nervously and said, \ldblquote My dear Mr. Baley, I won\rquote t need a laboratory.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote  asked Baley apprehensively. He stood there, muscles tense, feeling himself twitch.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s not difficult to test the First Law. I\rquote ve never had to, you understand, but it\rquote s simple enough.\rdblquote\par
Baley pulled air in through his mouth and let it out slowly. He said, \ldblquote Would you explain what you mean? Are you saying that you can test him here?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, of course. Look, Mr. Baley, I\rquote ll give you an analogy. If I were a Doctor of Medicine and had to test a patient\rquote s blood sugar, I\rquote d need a chemical laboratory. If I needed to measure his basal metabolic rate, or test his cortical function, or check his genes to pinpoint a congenital malfunction, I\rquote d need elaborate equipment. On the other hand, I could check whether he were blind by merely passing my hand before his eyes and I could test whether he were dead by merely feeling for his pulse.\par
\ldblquote What I\rquote m getting at is that the more important and fundamental the property being tested, the simpler the needed equipment. It\rquote s the same in a robot. The First Law is fundamental. It affects everything. If it were absent, the robot could not react properly in two dozen obvious ways.\rdblquote\par
As he spoke, he took out a flat, black object which expanded into a small book-viewer. He inserted a well-worn spool into the receptacle. He then took out a stop watch and a series of white, plastic slivers that fitted together to form something that looked like a slide rule with three independent movable scales. The notations upon it struck no chord of familiarity to Baley.\par
Dr. Gerrigel tapped his book-viewer and smiled a little, as though the prospect of a bit of field work cheered him.\par
He said, \ldblquote It\rquote s my Handbook of Robotics. I never go anywhere without it. It\rquote s part of my clothes.\rdblquote  He giggled self-consciously.\par
He put the eyepiece of the viewer to his eyes and his finger dealt delicately with the controls. The viewer whirred and stopped, whirred and stopped.\par
\ldblquote Built-in index,\rdblquote  the roboticist said, proudly, his voice a little muffled because of the way in which the viewer covered his mouth. \ldblquote I constructed it myself. It saves a great deal of time. But then, that\rquote s not the point now, is it? Let\rquote s see. Umm, won\rquote t you move your chair near me, Daneel.\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel did so. During the roboticist\rquote s preparations, he had watched closely and unemotionally.\par
Baley shifted his blaster.\par
What followed confused and disappointed him. Dr. Gerrigel proceeded to ask questions and perform actions that seemed without meaning, punctuated by references to his triple slide rule and occasionally to the viewer.\par
At one time, he asked, \ldblquote If I have two cousins, five years apart in age, and the younger is a girl, what sex is the older?\rdblquote\par
Daneel answered (inevitably, Baley thought), \ldblquote It is impossible to say on the information given.\rdblquote\par
To which Dr. Gerrigel\rquote s only response, aside from a glance at his stop watch, was to extend his right hand as far as he could sideways and to say, \ldblquote Would you touch the tip of my middle finger with the tip of the third finger of your left hand?\rdblquote\par
Daneel did that promptly and easily.\par
In fifteen minutes, not more, Dr. Gerrigel was finished. He used his slide rule for a last silent calculation, then disassembled it with a series of snaps. He put away his stop watch, withdrew the Handbook from the viewer, and collapsed the latter.\par
\ldblquote Is that all?\rdblquote  said Baley, frowning.\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s all.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But it\rquote s ridiculous. You\rquote ve asked nothing that pertains to the First Law.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, my dear Mr. Baley, when a doctor hits your knee with a little rubber mallet and it jerks, don\rquote t you accept the fact that it gives information concerning the presence or absence of some degenerative nerve disease? When he looks closely at your eyes and considers the reaction of your iris to light, are you surprised that he can tell you something concerning your possible addiction to the use of certain alkaloids?\rdblquote\par
Baley said, \ldblquote Well, then? What\rquote s your decision?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Daneel is fully equipped with the First Law!\rdblquote  The roboticist jerked his head in a sharp affirmative.\par
\ldblquote You can\rquote t be right,\rdblquote  said Baley huskily.\par
Baley would not have thought that Dr. Gerrigel could stiffen into a rigidity that was greater than his usual position. He did so, however, visibly. The man\rquote s eyes grew narrow and hard.\par
\ldblquote Are you teaching me my job?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t mean you\rquote re incompetent,\rdblquote  said Baley. He put out a large, pleading hand. \ldblquote But couldn\rquote t you be mistaken? You\rquote ve said yourself nobody knows anything about the theory of non-Asenion robots. A blind man could read by using Braille or a sound-scriber. Suppose you didn\rquote t know that Braille or sound-scribing existed. Couldn\rquote t you, in all honesty, say that a man had eyes because he knew the contents of a certain book-film, and be mistaken?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes,\rdblquote  the roboticist grew genial again, \ldblquote I see your point. But still a blind man could not read by use of his eyes and it is that which I was testing, if I may continue the analogy. Take my word for it, regardless of what a non-Asenion robot could or could not do, it is certain that R. Daneel is equipped with First Law.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Couldn\rquote t he have falsified his answers?\rdblquote  Baley was floundering, and knew it.\par
\ldblquote Of course not. That is the difference between a robot and a man. A human brain, or any mammalian brain, cannot be completely analyzed by any mathematical discipline now known. No response can therefore be counted upon as a certainty. The robot brain is completely analyzable, or it could not be constructed. We know exactly what the responses to given stimuli must be. No robot can truly falsify answers. The thing you call falsification just doesn\rquote t exist in the robot\rquote s mental horizon.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Then let\rquote s get down to cases. R. Daneel did point a blaster at a crowd of human beings. I saw that. I was there. Granted that he didn\rquote t shoot, wouldn\rquote t the First Law still have forced him into a kind of neurosis? It didn\rquote t, you know. He was perfectly normal afterward.\rdblquote\par
The roboticist put a hesitant hand to his chin. \ldblquote That is anomalous.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Not at all,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel, suddenly. \ldblquote Partner Elijah, would you look at the blaster that you took from me?\rdblquote\par
Baley looked down upon the blaster he held cradled in his left hand.\par
\ldblquote Break open the charge chamber,\rdblquote  urged R. Daneel. \ldblquote Inspect it.\rdblquote  Baley weighed his chances, then slowly put his own blaster on the table beside him. With a quick movement, he opened the robot\rquote s blaster.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s empty,\rdblquote  he said, blankly.\par
\ldblquote There is no charge in it,\rdblquote  agreed R. Daneel. \ldblquote If you will look closer, you will see that there has never been a charge in it. The blaster has no ignition bud and cannot be used.\rdblquote\par
Baley said, \ldblquote You held an uncharged blaster on the crowd?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I had to have a blaster or fail in my role as plain-clothes man,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel. \ldblquote Yet to carry a charged and usable blaster might have made it possible for me to hurt a human being by accident, a thing which is, of course, unthinkable. I would have explained this at the time, but you were angry and would not listen.\rdblquote\par
Baley stared bleakly at the useless blaster in his hand and said in a low voice, \ldblquote I think that\rquote s all, Dr. Gerrigel. Thank you for helping out.\rdblquote\par
Baley sent out for lunch, but when it came (yeast-nut cake and a rather extravagant slice of fried chicken on cracker) he could only stare at it.\par
Round and round went the currents of his mind. The lines on his long face were etched in deep gloom.\par
He was living in an unreal world, a cruel, topsy-turvy world.\par
How had it happened? The immediate past stretched behind him like a misty improbable dream dating back to the moment he had stepped into Julius Enderby\rquote s office and found himself suddenly immersed in a nightmare of murder and robotics.\par
Jehoshaphat! It had begun only fifty hours before.\par
Persistently, he had sought the solution in Spacetown. Twice he had accused R. Daneel, once as a human being in disguise, and once as an admitted and actual robot, each time as a murderer. Twice the accusation had been bent back and broken.\par
He was being driven back. Against his will he was forced to turn his thoughts into the City, and since last night he dared not. Certain questions battered at his conscious mind, but he would not listen; he felt he could not. If he heard them, he couldn\rquote t help but answer them and, oh God, he didn\rquote t want to face the answers.\par
\ldblquote Lije! Lije!\rdblquote  A hand shook Baley\rquote s shoulder roughly.\par
Baley stirred and said, \ldblquote What\rquote s up, Phil?\rdblquote\par
Philip Norris, Plain-clothes man C-5, sat down, put his hands on his knees, and leaned forward, peering at Baley\rquote s face. \ldblquote What happened to you? Been living on knockout drops lately? You were sitting there with your eyes open and, near as I could make out, you were dead.\rdblquote\par
He rubbed his thinning, pale blond hair, and his close-set eyes appraised Baley\rquote s cooling lunch greedily. \ldblquote Chicken!\rdblquote  he said. \ldblquote It\rquote s getting so you can\rquote t get it without a doctor\rquote s prescription.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Take some,\rdblquote  said Baley, listlessly.\par
Decorum won out and Norris said, \ldblquote Oh, well, I\rquote m going out to eat in a minute. You keep it. --Say, what\rquote s doing with the Commish?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\par
Norris attempted a casual attitude, but his hands were restless. He said, \ldblquote Go on. You know what I mean. You\rquote ve been living with him ever since he got back. What\rquote s up? A promotion in the works?\rdblquote\par
Baley frowned and felt reality return somewhat at the touch of office politics. Norris had approximately his own seniority and he was bound to watch most assiduously for any sign of official preference in Baley\rquote s direction.\par
Baley said, \ldblquote No promotion. Believe me. It\rquote s nothing. Nothing. And if it\rquote s the Commissioner you\rquote re wanting, I wish I could give him to you. Jehoshaphat! Take him!\rdblquote\par
Norris said, \ldblquote Don\rquote t get me wrong. I don\rquote t care if you get promoted. I just mean that if you\rquote ve got any pull with the Commish, how about using it for the kid?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What kid?\rdblquote\par
There was no need of any answer to that. Vincent Barrett, the youngster who had been moved out of his job to make room for R. Sammy, was shuffling up from an unnoticed corner of the room. A skull cap turned restlessly in his hands and the skin over his high cheekbones moved as he tried to smile.\par
\ldblquote Hello, Mr. Baley.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Oh, hello, Vince. How\rquote re you doing?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Not so good, Mr. Baley.\rdblquote\par
He was looking about hungrily. Baley thought: He looks lost, half dead--declassified.\par
Then, savagely, his lips almost moving with the force of his emotion, he thought: But what does he want from me?\par
He said, \ldblquote I\rquote m sorry, kid.\rdblquote  What else was there to say?\par
\ldblquote I keep thinking--maybe something has turned up.\rdblquote\par
Norris moved in close and spoke into Baley\rquote s ear. \ldblquote Someone\rquote s got to stop this sort of thing. They\rquote re going to move out Chenlow now.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Haven\rquote t you heard?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, I haven\rquote t. Damn it, he\rquote s a C-3. He\rquote s got ten years behind him.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I grant that. But a machine with legs can do his work. Who\rquote s next?\rdblquote\par
Young Vince Barrett was oblivious to the whispers. He said out of the depths of his own thinking, \ldblquote Mr. Baley?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, Vince?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You know what they say? They say Lynane Millane, the subethenics dancer, is really a robot.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s silly.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Is it? They say they can make robots look just like humans; with a special plastic skin, sort of.\rdblquote\par
Baley thought guiltily of R. Daneel and found no words. He shook his head.\par
The boy said, \ldblquote Do you suppose anyone will mind if I just walk around. It makes me feel better to see the old place.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Go ahead, kid.\rdblquote\par
The youngster wandered off. Baley and Norris watched him go.\par
Norris said, \ldblquote It looks as though the Medievalists are right.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You mean back to the soil? Is that it, Phil?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No. I mean about the robots. Back to the soil. Huh! Old Earth has an unlimited future. We don\rquote t need robots, that\rquote s all.\rdblquote\par
Baley muttered, \ldblquote Eight billion people and the uranium running out! What\rquote s unlimited about it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What if the uranium does run out. We\rquote ll import it. Or we\rquote ll discover other nuclear processes. There\rquote s no way you can stop mankind, Lije. You\rquote ve got to be optimistic about it and have faith in the old human brain. Our greatest resource is ingenuity and we\rquote ll never run out of that, Lije.\rdblquote\par
He was fairly started now. He went on, \ldblquote For one thing, we can use sunpower and that\rquote s good for billions of years. We can build space stations inside Mercury\rquote s orbit to act as energy accumulators. We\rquote ll transmit energy to Earth by direct beam.\rdblquote\par
This project was not new to Baley. The speculative fringe of science had been playing with the notion for a hundred and fifty years at least. What was holding it up was the impossibility so far of projecting a beam tight enough to reach fifty million miles without dispersal to uselessness. Baley said as much.\par
Norris said, \ldblquote When it\rquote s necessary, it\rquote ll be done. Why worry?\rdblquote\par
Baley had the picture of an Earth of unlimited energy. Population could continue to increase. The yeast farms could expand, hydroponic culture intensify. Energy was the only thing indispensable. The raw minerals could be brought in from the uninhabited rocks of the System. If ever water became a bottleneck, more could be brought in from the moons of Jupiter. Hell, the oceans could be frozen and dragged out into Space where they could circle Earth as moonlets of ice. There they would be, always available for use, while the ocean bottoms would represent more land for exploitation, more room to live. Even carbon and oxygen could be maintained and increased on Earth through utilization of the methane atmosphere of Titan and the frozen oxygen of Umbriel.\par
Earth\rquote s population could reach a trillion or two. Why not? There was a time when the current population of eight billion would have been viewed as impossible. There was a time when a population of a single billion would have been unthinkable. There had always been prophets of Malthusian doom in every generation since Medieval times and they had always proven wrong.\par
But what would Fastolfe say? A world of a trillion? Surely! But they would be dependent on imported air and water and upon an energy supply from complicated storehouses fifty million miles away. How incredibly unstable that would be. Earth would be, and remain, a feather\rquote s weight away from complete catastrophe at the slightest failure of any part of the System-wide mechanism.\par
Baley said, \ldblquote I think it would be easier to ship off some of the surplus population, myself.\rdblquote  It was more an answer to the picture he had himself conjured up than to anything Norris had said.\par
\ldblquote Who\rquote d have us?\rdblquote  said Norris with a bitter lightness.\par
\ldblquote Any uninhabited planet.\rdblquote\par
Norris rose, patted Baley on the shoulder. \ldblquote Lije, you eat your chicken, and recover. You must be living on knockout pills.\rdblquote  He left, chuckling.\par
Baley watched him leave with a humorless twist to his mouth. Norris would spread the news and it would be weeks before the humor boys of the office (every office has them) would lay off. But at least it got him off the subject of young Vince, of robots, of declassification.\par
He sighed as he put a fork into the now cold and somewhat stringy chicken.\par
Baley finished the last of the yeast-nut and it was only then that R. Daneel left his own desk (assigned him that morning) and approached.\par
Baley eyed him uncomfortably. \ldblquote Well?\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel said, \ldblquote The Commissioner is not in his office and it is not known when he\rquote ll be back. I\rquote ve told R. Sammy we will use it and that he is to allow no one but the Commissioner to enter.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What are we going to use it for?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Greater privacy. Surely you agree that we must plan our next move. After all, you do not intend to abandon the investigation, do you?\rdblquote\par
That was precisely what Baley most longed to do, but obviously, he could not say so. He rose and led the way to Enderby\rquote s office.\par
Once in the office, Baley said, \ldblquote All right, Daneel. What is it?\rdblquote  The robot said, \ldblquote Partner Elijah, since last night, you are not yourself. There is a definite alteration in your mental aura.\rdblquote\par
A horrible thought sprang full-grown into Baley\rquote s mind. He cried, \ldblquote Are you telepathic?\rdblquote\par
It was not a possibility he would have considered at a less disturbed moment.\par
\ldblquote No. Of course not,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel.\par
Baley\rquote s panic ebbed. He said, \ldblquote Then what the devil do you mean by talking about my mental aura?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It is merely an expression I use to describe a sensation that you do not share with me.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What sensation?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It is difficult to explain, Elijah. You will recall that I was originally designed to study human psychology for our people back in Spacetown.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, I know. You were adjusted to detective work by the simple installation of a justice-desire circuit.\rdblquote  Baley did not try to keep the sarcasm out of his voice.\par
\ldblquote Exactly, Elijah. But my original design remains essentially unaltered. I was constructed for the purpose of cerebroanalysis.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote For analyzing brain waves?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why, yes. It can be done by field-measurements without the necessity of direct electrode contact, if the proper receiver exists. My mind is such a receiver. Is that principle not applied on Earth?\rdblquote\par
Baley didn\rquote t know. He ignored the question and said, cautiously, \ldblquote If you measure the brain waves, what do you get out of it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Not thoughts, Elijah. I get a glimpse of emotion and most of all, I can analyze temperament, the underlying drives and attitudes of a man. For instance, it was I who was able to ascertain that Commissioner Enderby was incapable of killing a man under the circumstances prevailing at the time of the murder.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And they eliminated him as a suspect on your say-so.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes. It was safe enough to do so. I am a very delicate machine in that respect.\rdblquote\par
Again a thought struck Baley. \ldblquote Wait! Commissioner Enderby didn\rquote t know he was being cerebroanalyzed, did he?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote There was no necessity of hurting his feelings.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I mean you just stood there and looked at him. No machinery. No electrodes. No needles and graphs.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Certainly not. I am a self-contained unit.\rdblquote\par
Baley bit his lower lip in anger and chagrin. It had been the one remaining inconsistency, the one loophole through which a forlorn stab might yet be made in an attempt to pin the crime on Spacetown.\par
R. Daneel had stated that the Commissioner had been cerebroanalyzed and one hour later the Commissioner himself had, with apparent candor, denied any knowledge of the term. Certainly no man could have undergone the shattering experience of electroencephalographic measurements by electrode and graph under the suspicion of murder without an unmistakable impression of what cerebroanalysis must be.\par
But now that discrepancy had evaporated. The Commissioner had been cerebroanalyzed and had never known it. R. Daneel told the truth; so had the Commissioner.\par
\ldblquote Well,\rdblquote  said Baley, sharply, \ldblquote what does cerebroanahysis tell you about me?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You are disturbed.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That\rquote s a great discovery, isn\rquote t it? Of course, I\rquote m disturbed.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Specifically, though, your disturbance is due to a clash between motivations within you. On the one hand your devotion to the principles of your profession urges you to look deeply into this conspiracy of Earthmen who lay siege to us last night. Another motivation, equally strong, forces you in the opposite direction. This much is clearly written in the electric field of your cerebral cells.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote My cerebral cells, nuts,\rdblquote  said Baley, feverishly. \ldblquote Look, I\rquote ll tell you why there\rquote s no point in investigating your so-called conspiracy. It has nothing to do with the murder. I thought it might have. I\rquote ll admit that. Yesterday in the kitchen, I thought we were in danger. But what happened? They followed us out, were quickly lost on the strips, and that was that. That was not the action of well-organized and desperate men.\par
\ldblquote My own son found out where we were staying easily enough. He called the Department. He didn\rquote t even have to identify himself. Our precious conspirators could have done the same if they had really wanted to hurt us.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Didn\rquote t they?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Obviously not. If they had wanted riots, they could have started one at the shoe counter, and yet they backed out tamely enough before one man and a blaster. One robot, and a blaster which they must have known you would be unable to fire once they recognized what you were. They\rquote re Medievalists. They\rquote re harmless crackpots. You wouldn\rquote t know that, but I should have. And I would have, if it weren\rquote t for the fact that this whole business has me thinking in--in foolish melodramatic terms.\par
\ldblquote I tell you I know the type of people that become Medievalists. They\rquote re soft, dreamy people who find life too hard for them here and get lost in an ideal world of the past that never really existed. If you could cerebroanalyze a movement as you do an individual, you would find they are no more capable of murder than Julius Enderby himself.\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel said slowly, \ldblquote I cannot accept your statements at face value.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What do you mean?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Your conversion to this view is too sudden. There are certain discrepancies, too. You arranged the appointment with Dr. Gerrigel hours before the evening meal. You did not know of my food sac then and could not have suspected me as the murderer. Why did you call him, then?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I suspected you even then.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And last night you spoke as you slept.\rdblquote  Baley\rquote s eyes widened. \ldblquote What did I say?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Merely the one word \lquote Jessie\rquote  several times repeated. I believe you were referring to your wife.\rdblquote\par
Baley let his tight muscles loosen. He said, shakily, \ldblquote I had a nightmare. Do you know what that is?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I do not know by personal experience, of course. The dictionary definition has it that it is a bad dream.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And do you know what a dream is?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Again, the dictionary definition only. It is an illusion of reality experienced during the temporary suspension of conscious thought which you call sleep.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All right. I\rquote ll buy that. An illusion. Sometimes the illusions can seem damned real. Well, I dreamed my wife was in danger. It\rquote s the sort of dream people often have. I called her name. That happens under such circumstances, too. You can take my word for it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I am only too glad to do so. But it brings up a thought. How did Jessie find out I was a robot?\rdblquote\par
Baley\rquote s forehead went moist again. \ldblquote We\rquote re not going into that again, are we? The rumor--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I am sorry to interrupt, partner Elijah, but there is no rumor. If there were, the City would be alive with unrest today. I have checked reports coming into the Department and this is not so. There simply is no rumor. Therefore, how did your wife find out?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Jehoshaphat! What are you trying to say? Do you think my wife is one of the members of--of ...\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, Elijah.\rdblquote\par
Baley gripped his hands together tightly. \ldblquote Well, she isn\rquote t, and we won\rquote t discuss that point any further.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote This is not like you, Elijah. In the course of duty, you accused me of murder twice.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And is this your way of getting even?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I am not sure I understand what you mean by the phrase. Certainly, I approve your readiness to suspect me. You had your reasons. They were wrong, but they might easily have been right. Equally strong evidence points to your wife.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote As a murderess? Why, damn you, Jessie wouldn\rquote t hurt her worst enemy. She couldn\rquote t set foot outside the City. She couldn\rquote t ...\rdblquote  --Why, if you were flesh and blood I\rquote d--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I merely say that she is a member of the conspiracy. I say that she should be questioned.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Not on your life. Not on whatever it is you call your life. Now, listen to me. The Medievalists aren\rquote t after our blood. It\rquote s not the way they do things. But they are trying to get you out of the City. That much is obvious. And they\rquote re trying to do it by a kind of psychological attack. They\rquote re trying to make life unpleasant for you and for me, since I\rquote m with you. They could easily have found out Jessie was my wife, and it was an obvious move for them to let the news leak to her. She\rquote s like any other human being. She doesn\rquote t like robots. She wouldn\rquote t want me to associate with one, especially if she thought it involved danger, and surely they would imply that. I tell you it worked. She begged all night to have me abandon the case or to get you out of the City somehow.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Presumably,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel, \ldblquote you have a very strong urge to protect your wife against questioning. It seems obvious to me that you are constructing this line of argument without really believing it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What the hell do you think you are?\rdblquote  ground out Baley. \ldblquote You\rquote re not a detective. You\rquote re a cerebroanalysis machine like the electroencephalographs we have in this building. You\rquote ve got arms, legs, a head, and can talk, but you\rquote re not one inch more than that machine. Putting a lousy circuit into you doesn\rquote t make you a detective, so what do you know? You keep your mouth shut, and let me do the figuring out.\rdblquote\par
The robot said quietly, \ldblquote I think it would be better if you lowered your voice, Elijah. Granted that I am not a detective in the sense that you are, I would still like to bring one small item to your attention.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m not interested in listening.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Please do. If I am wrong, you will tell me so, and it will do no harm. It is only this. Last night you left our room to call Jessie by corridor phone. I suggested that your son go in your place. You told me it was not the custom among Earthmen for a father to send his son into danger. Is it then the custom for a mother to do so?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, of cour--\rdblquote  began Baley, and stopped.\par
\ldblquote You see my point,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel. \ldblquote Ordinarily, if Jessie feared for your safety and wished to warn you, she would risk her own life, not send her son. The fact that she did send Bentley could only mean that she felt that he would be safe while she herself would not. If the conspiracy consisted of people unknown to Jessie, that would not be the case, or at least she would have no reason to think it to be the case. On the other hand, if she were a member of the conspiracy, she would know, she would know, Elijah, that she would be watched for and recognized, whereas Bentley might get through unnoticed.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Wait now,\rdblquote  said Baley, sick at heart, \ldblquote that\rquote s feather-fine reasoning.\rdblquote\par
There was no need to wait. The signal on the Commissioner\rquote s desk was flickering madly. R. Daneel waited for Baley to answer, but the latter could only stare at it helplessly. The robot closed contact.\par
\ldblquote What is it?\rdblquote\par
R. Sammy\rquote s slurring voice said, \ldblquote There is a lady here who wishes to see Lije. I told her he was busy, but she will not go away. She says her name is Jessie.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Let her in,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel calmly, and his brown eyes rose unemotionally to meet the panicky glare of Baley\rquote s.\par
