\pard\keepn\s2\sb240\sa240\qc\kerning0\i\fs28 POWER OF A NAME\par
\pard\fi216\qj\b0\i0\f0\fs24 Baley remained standing in a tetany of shock, as Jessie ran to him, seizing his shoulders, huddling close.\par
His pale lips formed the word, \ldblquote Bentley?\rdblquote\par
She looked at him and shook her head, her brown hair flying with the force of her motion. \ldblquote He\rquote s all right.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, then ...\rdblquote\par
Jessie said through a sudden torrent of sobs, in a low voice that could scarcely be made out, \ldblquote I can\rquote t go on, Lije. I can\rquote t. I can\rquote t sleep or eat. I\rquote ve got to tell you.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t say anything,\rdblquote  Baley said in anguish. \ldblquote For God\rquote s sake, Jessie, not now.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I must. I\rquote ve done a terrible thing. Such a terrible thing. Oh, Lije ...\rdblquote  She lapsed into incoherence.\par
Baley said, hopelessly, \ldblquote We\rquote re not alone, Jessie.\rdblquote\par
She looked up and stared at R. Daneel with no signs of recognition. The tears in which her eyes were swimming might easily be refracting the robot into a featureless blur.\par
R. Daneel said in a low murmur, \ldblquote Good afternoon, Jessie.\rdblquote\par
She gasped. \ldblquote Is it the--the robot?\rdblquote\par
She dashed the back of her hand across her eyes and stepped out of Baley\rquote s encircling right arm. She breathed deeply and, for a moment, a tremulous smile wavered on her lips. \ldblquote It is you, isn\rquote t it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, Jessie.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You don\rquote t mind being called a robot?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, Jessie. It is what I am.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And I don\rquote t mind being called a fool and an idiot and a--a subversive agent, because it\rquote s what I am.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Jessie!\rdblquote  groaned Baley.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s no use, Lije,\rdblquote  she said. \ldblquote He might as well know if he\rquote s your partner. I can\rquote t live with it any more. I\rquote ve had such a time since yesterday. I don\rquote t care if I go to jail. I don\rquote t care if they send me down to the lowest levels and make me live on raw yeast and water. I don\rquote t care if ... You won\rquote t let them, will you, Lije? Don\rquote t let them do anything to me. I\rquote m fuh--frightened.\rdblquote\par
Baley patted her shoulder and let her cry.\par
He said to R. Daneel. \ldblquote She isn\rquote t well. We can\rquote t keep her here. What time is it?\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel said without any visible signs of consulting a timepiece, \ldblquote Fourteen-forty-five.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote The Commissioner could be back any minute. Look, commandeer a squad car and we can talk about this in the motorway.\rdblquote\par
Jessie\rquote s head jerked upright. \ldblquote The motorway? Oh, no, Lije.\rdblquote\par
He said, in as soothing a tone as he could manage, \ldblquote Now, Jessie, don\rquote t be superstitious. You can\rquote t go on the expressway the way you are. Be a good girl and calm down or we won\rquote t even be able to go through the common room. I\rquote ll get you some water.\rdblquote\par
She wiped her face with a damp handkerchief and said drearily, \ldblquote Oh, look at my makeup.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Don\rquote t worry about your makeup,\rdblquote  said Baley. \ldblquote Daneel, what about the squad car?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s waiting for us now, partner Elijah.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Come on, Jessie.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Wait. Wait just a minute, Lije. I\rquote ve got to do something to my face.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It doesn\rquote t matter now.\rdblquote\par
But she twisted away. \ldblquote Please. I can\rquote t go through the common room like this. I won\rquote t take a second.\rdblquote\par
The man and the robot waited, the man with little jerky clenchings of his fists, the robot impassively.\par
Jessie rummaged through her purse for the necessary equipment. (If there were one thing, Baley had once said solemnly, that had resisted mechanical improvement since Medieval times, it was a woman\rquote s purse. Even the substitution of magnetic clotures for metal clasps had not proven successful.) Jessie pulled out a small mirror and the silver-cased cosmetokit that Baley had bought her on the occasion of three birthdays before.\par
The cosmetokit had several orifices and she used each in turn. All but the last spray were invisible. She used them with that fineness of touch and delicacy of control that seems to be the birthright of women even at times of the greatest stress.\par
The base went on first in a smooth even layer that removed all shininess and roughness from the skin and left it with the faintly golden glow which long experience had taught Jessie was just the shade most suited to the natural coloring of her hair and eyes. Then the touch of tan along the forehead and chin, a gentle brush of rouge on either cheek, tracing back to the angle of the jaw; and a delicate drift of blue on the upper eyelids and along the earlobes. Finally there was the application of the smooth carmine to the lips. That involved the one visible spray, a faintly pink mist that glistened liquidly in air, but dried and deepened richly on contact with the lips.\par
\ldblquote There,\rdblquote  said Jessie, with several swift pats at her hair and a look of deep dissatisfaction. \ldblquote I suppose that will do.\rdblquote\par
The process had taken more than the promised second, but less than fifteen seconds. Nevertheless, it had seemed interminable to Baley.\par
\ldblquote Come,\rdblquote  he said.\par
She barely had time to return the cosmetokit to the purse before he had pushed her through the door.\par
The eerie silence of the motorway lay thick on either side.\par
Baley said, \ldblquote All right, Jessie.\rdblquote\par
The impassivity that had covered Jessie\rquote s face since they first left the Commissioner\rquote s office showed signs of cracking. She looked at her husband and at Daneel with a helpless silence.\par
Baley said, \ldblquote Get it over with, Jessie. Please. Have you committed a crime? An actual crime?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote A crime?\rdblquote  She shook her head uncertainly.\par
\ldblquote Now hold on to yourself. No hysterics. Just say yes or no, Jessie. Have you--\rdblquote  he hesitated a trifle, \ldblquote killed anyone?\rdblquote\par
The look on Jessie\rquote s face was promptly transmuted to indignation. \ldblquote Why, Lije Baley!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes or no, Jessie.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, of course not.\rdblquote\par
The hard knot in Baley\rquote s stomach softened perceptibly. \ldblquote Have you stolen anything? Falsified ration data? Assaulted anyone? Destroyed property? Speak up, Jessie.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I haven\rquote t done anything--anything specific. I didn\rquote t mean anything like that.\rdblquote  She looked over her shoulder. \ldblquote Lije, do we have to stay down here?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Right here until this is over. Now, start at the beginning. What did you come to tell us?\rdblquote  Over Jessie\rquote s bowed head, Baley\rquote s eyes met R. Daneel\rquote s.\par
Jessie spoke in a soft voice that gained in strength and articulateness as she went on.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s these people, these Medievalists; you know, Lije. They\rquote re always around, always talking. Even in the old days when I was an assistant dietitian, it was like that. Remember Elizabeth Thornbowe? She was a Medievalist. She was always talking about how all our troubles came from the City and how things were better before the Cities started.\par
\ldblquote I used to ask her how she was so sure that was so, especially after you and I met, Lije (remember the talks we used to have), and then she would quote from those small book-reels that are always floating around. You know, like Shame of the Cities that the fellow wrote. I don\rquote t remember his name.\rdblquote\par
Baley said, absently, \ldblquote Ogninsky.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, only most of them were lots worse. Then, when I married you, she was really sarcastic. She said, \lquote I suppose you\rquote re going to be a real City woman now that you\rquote ve married a policeman.\rquote  After that, she didn\rquote t talk to me much and then I quit the job and that was that. Lots of things she used to say were just to shock me, I think, or to make herself look mysterious and glamorous. She was an old maid, you know; never got married till the day she died. Lots of those Medievalists don\rquote t fit in, one way or another. Remember, you once said, Lije, that people sometimes mistake their own shortcomings for those of society and want to fix the Cities because they don\rquote t know how to fix themselves.\rdblquote\par
Baley remembered, and his words now sounded flip and superficial in his own ears. He said, gently, \ldblquote Keep to the point, Jessie.\rdblquote\par
She went on, \ldblquote Anyway, Lizzy was always talking about how there\rquote d come a day and people had to get together. She said it was all the fault of the Spacers because they wanted to keep Earth weak and decadent. That was one of her favorite words, \lquote decadent.\rquote  She\rquote d look at the menus I\rquote d prepare for the next week and sniff and say, \lquote Decadent, decadent.\rquote  Jane Myers used to imitate her in the cook room and we\rquote d die laughing. She said, Elizabeth did, that someday we were going to break up the Cities and go back to the soil and have an accounting with the Spacers who were trying to tie us forever to the Cities by forcing robots on us. Only she never called them robots. She used to say \lquote soulless monster-machines,\rquote  if you\rquote ll excuse the expression, Daneel.\rdblquote\par
The robot said, \ldblquote I am not aware of the significance of the adjective you used, Jessie, but in any case, the expression is excused. Please go on.\rdblquote\par
Baley stirred restlessly. It was that way with Jessie. No emergency, H no crisis could make her tell a story in any way but her own circuitous one.\par
She said, \ldblquote Elizabeth always tried to talk as though there were lots of people in it with her. She would say, \lquote At the last meeting,\rquote  and then stop and look at me sort of half proud and half scared as though she wanted me to ask about it so she could look important, and yet scared I might get her in trouble. Of course, I never asked her. I wouldn\rquote t give her the satisfaction.\par
\ldblquote Anyway, after I married you, Lije, it was all over, until--\rdblquote  She stopped.\par
\ldblquote Go on, Jessie,\rdblquote  said Baley.\par
\ldblquote You remember, Lije, that argument we had? About Jezebel, I mean?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What about it?\rdblquote  It took a second or two for Baley to remember that it was Jessie\rquote s own name, and not a reference to another woman.\par
He turned to R. Daneel in an automatically defensive explanation.\par
\ldblquote Jessie\rquote s full name is Jezebel. She is not fond of it and doesn\rquote t use it.\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel nodded gravely and Baley thought: Jehoshaphat, why waste worry on him?\par
\ldblquote It bothered me a lot, Lije,\rdblquote  Jessie said. \ldblquote It really did. I guess it was silly, but I kept thinking and thinking about what you said. I mean about your saying that Jezebel was only a conservative who fought for the ways of her ancestors against the strange ways the newcomers had brought. After all, I was Jezebel and I always ...\rdblquote\par
She groped for a word and Baley supplied it. \ldblquote Identified yourself?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes.\rdblquote  But she shook her head almost immediately and looked away. \ldblquote Not really, of course. Not literally. The way I thought she was, you know. I wasn\rquote t like that.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I know that, Jessie. Don\rquote t be foolish.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But still I thought of her a lot and, somehow, I got to thinking, it\rquote s just the same now as it was then. I mean, we Earth people had our old ways and here were the Spacers coming in with a lot of new ways and trying to encourage the new ways we had stumbled into ourselves and maybe the Medievalists were right. Maybe we should go back to our old, good ways. So I went back and found Elizabeth.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes. Go on.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote She said she didn\rquote t know what I was talking about and besides I was a cop\rquote s wife. I said that had nothing to do with it and finally she said, well, she\rquote d speak to somebody, and then about a month later she came to me and said it was all right and I joined and I\rquote ve been at meetings ever since.\rdblquote\par
Baley looked at her sadly. \ldblquote And you never told me?\rdblquote\par
Jessie\rquote s voice trembled. \ldblquote I\rquote m sorry, Lije.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, that won\rquote t help. Being sorry, I mean. I want to know about the meetings. In the first place, where were they held?\rdblquote\par
A sense of detachment was creeping over him, a numbing of emotions. What he had tried not to believe was so, was openly so, was unmistakably so. In a sense, it was a relief to have the uncertainty over.\par
She said, \ldblquote Down here.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Down here? You mean on this spot? What do you mean?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Here in the motorway. That\rquote s why I didn\rquote t want to come down here. It was a wonderful place to meet, though. We\rquote d get together--\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote How many?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m not sure. About sixty or seventy. It was just a sort of local branch. There\rquote d be folding chairs and some refreshments and someone would make a speech, mostly about how wonderful life was in the old days and how someday we\rquote d do away with the monsters, the robots, that is, and the Spacers, too. The speeches were sort of dull really, because they were all the same. We just endured them. Mostly, it was the fun of getting together and feeling important. We would pledge ourselves to oaths and there\rquote d be secret ways we could greet each other on the outside.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Weren\rquote t you ever interrupted? No squad cars or fire engines passed?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No. Never.\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel interrupted, \ldblquote Is that unusual, Elijah?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Maybe not,\rdblquote  Baley answered thoughtfully. \ldblquote There are some side passages that are practically never used. It\rquote s quite a trick, knowing which they are, though. Is that all you did at the meetings, Jessie? Make speeches and play at conspiracy?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s about all. And sing songs, sometimes. And of course, refreshments. Not much. Sandwiches, usually, and juice.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote In that case,\rdblquote  he said, almost brutally, \ldblquote what\rquote s bothering you now?\rdblquote\par
Jessie winced. \ldblquote You\rquote re angry.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Please,\rdblquote  said Baley, with iron patience, \ldblquote answer my question. If it were all as harmless as that, why have you been in such a panic for the last day and a half?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I thought they would hurt you, Lije. For heaven\rquote s sake, why do you act as though you don\rquote t understand? I\rquote ve explained it to you.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No, you haven\rquote t. Not yet. You\rquote ve told me about a harmless little secret kaffee-klatsch you belonged to. Did they ever hold open demonstrations? Did they ever destroy robots? Start riots? Kill people?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Never! Lije, I wouldn\rquote t do any of those things. I wouldn\rquote t stay a member if they tried it.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, then, why do you say you\rquote ve done a terrible thing? Why do you expect to be sent to jail?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well ... Well, they used to talk about someday when they\rquote d put pressure on the government. We were supposed to get organized and then afterward there would be huge strikes and work stoppages. We could force the government to ban all robots and make the Spacers go back where they came from. I thought it was just talk and then, this thing started; about you and Daneel, I mean. Then they said, \lquote Now we\rquote ll see action,\rquote  and \lquote We\rquote re going to make an example of them and put a stop to the robot invasion right now.\rquote  Right there in Personal they said it, not knowing it was you they were talking about. But I knew. Right away.\rdblquote\par
Her voice broke.\par
Baley softened. \ldblquote Come on, Jessie. It was all nothing. It was just talk. You can see for yourself that nothing has happened.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I was so--so suh--scared. And I thought: I\rquote m part of it. If there were going to be killing and destruction, you might be killed and Bentley and somehow it would be all muh--my fault for taking part in it, and I ought to be sent to jail.\rdblquote\par
Baley let her sob herself out. He put his arm about her shoulder and stared tight-lipped at R. Daneel, who gazed calmly back.\par
He said, \ldblquote Now, I want you to think, Jessie. Who was the head of your group?\rdblquote\par
She was quieter now, patting the corners of her eyes with a handkerchief. \ldblquote A man called Joseph Klemin was the leader, but he wasn\rquote t really anybody. He wasn\rquote t more than five feet four inches tall and I think he was terribly henpecked at home. I don\rquote t think there\rquote s any harm in him. You aren\rquote t going to arrest him, are you, Lije? On my say-so?\rdblquote  She looked guiltily troubled.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m not arresting anyone just yet. How did Klemin get his instructions?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t know.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Did any strangers come to meeting? You know what I mean: big shots from Central Headquarters?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Sometimes people would come to make speeches. That wasn\rquote t very often, maybe twice a year or so.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Can you name them?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote No. They were always just introduced as \lquote one of us\rquote  or \lquote a friend from Jackson Heights\rquote  or wherever.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I see. Daneel!\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Yes, Elijah,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel.\par
\ldblquote Describe the men you think you\rquote ve tabbed. We\rquote ll see if Jessie can recognize them.\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel went through the list with clinical exactness. Jessie listened with an expression of dismay as the categories of physical measurements lengthened and shook her head with increasing firmness.\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s no use. It\rquote s no use,\rdblquote  she cried. \ldblquote How can I remember? I can\rquote t remember how any of them looked. I can\rquote t--\rdblquote\par
She stopped, and seemed to consider. Then she said, \ldblquote Did you say one of them was a yeast farmer?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Francis Clousarr,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel, \ldblquote is an employee at New York Yeast.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Well, you know, once a man was making a speech and I happened to be sitting in the first row and I kept getting a whiff, just a whiff, really, of raw yeast smell. You know what I mean. The only reason that I remember is that I had an upset stomach that day and the smell kept making me sick. I had to stand up and move to the back and of course I couldn\rquote t explain what was wrong. It was so embarrassing. Maybe that\rquote s the man you\rquote re speaking of. After all, when you work with yeast all the time, the odor gets to stick to your clothes.\rdblquote  She wrinkled her nose.\par
\ldblquote You don\rquote t remember what he looked like?\rdblquote  said Baley.\par
\ldblquote No,\rdblquote  she replied, with decision.\par
\ldblquote All right, then. Look, Jessie, I\rquote m going to take you to your mother\rquote s. Bentley will stay with you, and none of you will leave the Section. Ben can stay away from school and I\rquote ll arrange to have meals sent in and the corridors around the apartment watched by the police.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What about you?\rdblquote  quavered Jessie.\par
\ldblquote I\rquote ll be in no danger.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote But how long?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t know. Maybe just a day or two.\rdblquote  The words sounded hollow even to himself.\par
They were back in the motorway, Baley and R. Daneel, alone now. Baley\rquote s expression was dark with thought.\par
\ldblquote It would seem to me,\rdblquote  he said, \ldblquote that we are faced with an organization built up on two levels. First, a ground level with no specific program, designed only to supply mass support for an eventual coup. Secondly, a much smaller elite dedicated to a well-planned program of action. It is this elite we must find. The comic-opera groups that Jessie spoke of can be ignored.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote All this,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel, \ldblquote follows, perhaps, if we can take Jessie\rquote s story at face value.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I think,\rdblquote  Baley said stiffly, \ldblquote that Jessie\rquote s story can be accepted as completely true.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote So it would seem,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel. \ldblquote There is nothing about her cerebra-impulses that would indicate a pathological addiction to lying.\rdblquote\par
Baley turned an offended look upon the robot. \ldblquote I should say not. And there will be no necessity to mention her name in our reports. Do you understand that?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote If you wish it so, partner Elijah,\rdblquote  said R. Daneel calmly, \ldblquote but our report will then be neither complete nor accurate.\rdblquote\par
Baley said, \ldblquote Well, maybe so, but no real harm will be done. She has come to us with whatever information she had and to mention her name will only put her in the police records. I do not want that to happen.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote In that case, certainly not, provided we are certain that nothing more remains to be found out.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Nothing remains as far as she\rquote s concerned. My guarantee.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Could you then explain why the word, Jezebel, the mere sound of a name, should lead her to abandon previous convictions and assume a new set? The motivation seems obscure.\rdblquote\par
They were traveling slowly through the curving, empty tunnel.\par
Baley said, \ldblquote It is hard to explain. Jezebel is a rare name. It belonged once to a woman of very bad reputation. My wife treasured that fact. It gave her a vicarious feeling of wickedness and compensated for a life that was uniformly proper.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Why should a law-abiding woman wish to feel wicked?\rdblquote\par
Baley almost smiled. \ldblquote Women are women, Daneel. Anyway, I did a very foolish thing. In a moment of irritation, I insisted that the historic Jezebel was not particularly wicked and was, if anything, a good wife. I\rquote ve regretted that ever since.\par
\ldblquote It turned out,\rdblquote  he went on, \ldblquote that I had made Jessie bitterly unhappy. I had spoiled something for her that couldn\rquote t be replaced. I suppose what followed was her way of revenge. I imagine she wished to punish me by engaging in activity of which she knew I wouldn\rquote t approve. I don\rquote t say the wish was a conscious one.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Can a wish be anything but conscious? Is that not a contradiction in terms?\rdblquote\par
Baley stared at R Daneel and despaired at attempting to explain the unconscious mind. He said, instead, \ldblquote Besides that, the Bible has a great influence on human thought and emotion.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote What is the Bible?\rdblquote\par
For a moment Baley was surprised, and then was surprised at himself for having felt surprised. The Spacers, he knew, lived under a thoroughly mechanistic personal philosophy, and R. Daneel could know only what the Spacers knew; no more.\par
He said, curtly, \ldblquote It is the sacred book of about half of Earth\rquote s population.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I do not grasp the meaning here of the adjective.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I mean that it is highly regarded. Various portions of it, when properly interpreted, contain a code of behavior which many men consider best suited to the ultimate happiness of mankind.\rdblquote\par
R. Daneel seemed to consider that. \ldblquote Is this code incorporated into your laws?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I\rquote m afraid not. The code doesn\rquote t lend itself to legal enforcement. It must be obeyed spontaneously by each individual out of a longing to do so. It is in a sense higher than any law can be.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Higher than law? Is that not a contradiction in terms?\rdblquote\par
Baley smiled wryly. \ldblquote Shall I quote a portion of the Bible for you? Would you be curious to hear it?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Please do.\rdblquote\par
Baley let the car slow to a halt and for a few moments sat with his eyes closed, remembering. He would have liked to use the sonorous Middle English of the Medieval Bible, but to R. Daneel, Middle English would be gibberish.\par
He began, speaking almost casually in the words of the Modern Revision, as though he were telling a story of contemporary life, instead of dredging a tale out of Man\rquote s dimmest past:\par
\ldblquote Jesus went to the mount of Olives, and at dawn returned to the temple. All the people came to him, and he sat down and preached to them. And the scribes and Pharisees brought to him a woman caught in adultery, and when they had placed her before him, they said to him, \lquote Master, this woman was caught in adultery, in the very act. Now Moses, in the law, commanded us to stone such offenders. What do you say?\rquote\par
\ldblquote They said this, hoping to trap him, that they might have grounds for accusations against him. But Jesus stooped down, and with his finger wrote on the ground, as though he had not heard them. But when they continued asking him, he stood up and said to them, \lquote He that is without sin among you, let him first cast a stone at her.\rquote\par
\ldblquote And again he stooped down and wrote on the ground. And those that heard this, being convicted by their own conscience, went away one by one, beginning with the oldest, down to the last: and Jesus was left alone, with the woman standing before him. When Jesus stood up and saw no one but the woman, he said to her, \lquote Woman, where are your accusers? Has no one condemned you?\rquote\par
\ldblquote She said, \lquote No one, Lord.\rquote\par
\ldblquote And Jesus said to her, \lquote Nor do I condemn you. Go, and sin no more.\rquote  \rdblquote\par
R. Daneel listened attentively. He said, \ldblquote What is adultery?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote That doesn\rquote t matter. It was a crime and at the time, the accepted punishment was stoning; that is, stones were thrown at the guilty one until she was killed.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote And the woman was guilty?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote She was.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Then why was she not stoned?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote None of the accusers felt he could after Jesus\rquote s statement. The story is meant to show that there is something even higher than the justice which you have been filled with. There is a human impulse known as mercy; a human act known as forgiveness.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I am not acquainted with those words, partner Elijah.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I know,\rdblquote  muttered Baley. \ldblquote I know.\rdblquote\par
He started the squad car with a jerk and let it tear forward savagely. He was pressed back against the cushions of the seat.\par
\ldblquote Where are we going?\rdblquote  asked R. Daneel.\par
\ldblquote To Yeast-town,\rdblquote  said Baley, \ldblquote to get the truth out of Francis Clousarr, conspirator.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote You have a method for doing this, Elijah?\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote Not I, exactly. But you have, Daneel. A simple one.\rdblquote\par
They sped onward.\par
